<FIRST>r a PM-HollywoodHomecoming     01-18 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hollywood Homecoming,0727</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagans' Return Is the Talk of Hollywood</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Army in 4th graf is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan returns to his beloved
California as the toast of Hollywood, reinvigorating the social
scene with the stature of a popular two-term president who never
forgot his show business past.
   Ronald and Nancy Reagan don't hide their eagerness to step out of
the national spotlight and re-enter a private world among friends.
The president has said: ``Every time I come home I say to myself,
`Why did I ever leave?'''
   Their affluent friends are no less eager.
   ``It's tough to beat a former president living in your midst.
They are now going to be the superstars in the Bel-Air circuit,''
entertainment industry observer Army Archerd said.
   ``Hollywood feels it sent one of its own to the White House and
now he's returned as the most popular president in history. He's one
of us,'' said TV producer Gregory Willenborg.
   Merv Griffin and Barron Hilton set the social tone by throwing a
$25,000-a-table homecoming gala earlier this month.
   The Reagans will be a star attraction Feb. 23 at the America's
Hope Award presentations honoring Elizabeth Taylor and a Valentine's
Day party is on tap for Mrs. Reagan.
   ``They will really re-invigorate things,'' dance man Donald
O'Connor predicted. Griffin said the social calendar is already
topsy-turvy. ``I'm sure they will be the leaders of everything that
happens here,'' he said.
   Reagan never forgot Hollywood, where he starred in motion
pictures and led the Screen Actors Guild. Throughout his eight years
in the White House he delighted in spinning show business yarns.
   There are those who hope Reagan's fondness for his old vocation
will lead him back to the screen. Actress Joan Collins said a script
has been written for Reagan to play her ex-husband on ``Dynasty'' if
he chooses, and Griffin suggested the Reagans might make a movie
together.
   But one longtime Reagan friend said television and movies aren't
part of the Reagan post-presidential agenda.
   ``I think the idea of him being interested in an acting career is
absurd,'' said the Reagan confidant, who spoke on condition that his
name be withheld. ``I don't think he will do anything in
entertainment.''
   However, the same source said the nation may hear Reagan on
Saturday morning radio again, expressing his thoughts and opinions
on issues facing the country.
   Reagan expects to be inundated with requests to make speeches on
``the mashed-potato circuit'' and has offered himself up as a foot
soldier in what he calls the Bush Brigade of his successor's
supporters.
   He and Mrs. Reagan also have plans to write memoirs and push
their pet causes.
   Not everyone is happy the Reagans are back in town. Residents of
Lake View Terrace, 20 miles north of Los Angeles, have been fighting
to keep the Nancy Reagan Center for drug rehabilitation out of their
neighborhood.
   Homeowners fear the center, an extension of Mrs. Reagan's ``Just
Say No'' anti-drug crusade, will bring addicts into the area and
endanger residents. During the recent Beverly Hills welcome-home
gala, which raised $1 million for the center, residents marched
outside with signs reading, ``If you really care, put it in
Bel-Air.''
   That affluent hillside enclave is the Reagan's new neighborhood.
Although they are keeping their Santa Barbara ranch as a retreat,
they intend to spend most of their time in their new $2.5 million
Bel-Air home.
   Perched in hills among $10 million-plus mansions, the
6,500-square-foot ranch-style home is modest by neighborhood
standards.
   Little can be seen behind an electronic iron gate leading to 668
Saint Cloud Rd. A guard shack was constructed recently, a chain link
fence was thrown up over vintage stone walls and roof-mounted
cameras scan the property.
   The address was changed last summer from 666 Saint Cloud because
of connotations surrounding the number 666, believed by some to be
the symbol of the devil.
   Tourists clutching $5 maps to stars' homes ply the winding roads
aboard tour vans or in rental cars. So far, little notice has been
paid to the Reagan house _ the real stars are the ``Beverly
Hillbillies'' mansion and the home of entertainer Zsa Zsa Gabor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
