<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Germany-Draft     01-18 0128</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Germany-Draft,0131</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government To Lengthen Military Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany has lengthened its
compulsory military service from 15 months to 18 months, a move the
opposition Social Democrats say could jeopardize East-West
disarmament efforts.
   Following Tuesday's announcement by the Defense Ministry, the
Free Democrats, a minority party in Chancellor Helmut Kohl's
coalition government, also expressed reservations and asked that the
move be delayed.
   Given that about 400,000 more draft-age men than needed are now
available, the opposition says extending service time is unnecessary.
   The Social Democrats also point to a lessened threat from the
East bloc. The armed forces now have about 495,000 members. Men aged
18 through 28 are subject to be drafted and about half of those in
service are draftees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
