<SECOND>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0777,1072</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS Cruickshank Garcia and Sheatsley; Separates moved for AMs
as a0669 on Wilson, a0736 on Bentsen, a0756 on Allott, a0763 on Probst
and as a0762 on Cruickshank Garcia. Probst also moved on the business wire.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MCA1,DN2,DN5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Trey Wilson</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trey Wilson, a character actor who appeared on
stage and screen in recent hits from ``Raising Arizona'' to ``Bull
Durham,'' died Monday of a cerebral hemorrhage at age 40.
   Wilson also appeared in ``A Soldier's Story,'' ``F-X'' and ``The
House on Carroll Street.'' Two other films _ ``Welcome Home'' and
``Miss Firecracker'' _ have not yet been released, along with the
just-completed ``Great Balls of Fire,'' the Jerry Lee Lewis story.
   He appeared on stage in ``The Front Page'' at Lincoln Center,
``Custom of the Country'' at the Second Stage and ``The Debutante
Ball'' at Manhattan Theater Club. His Broadway credits included
``Peter Pan,'' ``Tintypes,'' ``The First'' and ``Foxfire.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Lloyd Bentsen Sr.</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDINBURG, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lloyd M. Bentsen Sr., an early developer
of Texas' Lower Rio Grande Valley whose son, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, was
the Democratic vice-presidential candidate last year, was killed
Tuesday in a traffic accident. He was 95.
   Bentsen held nearly 50,000 acres of farms and six ranches
scattered over a South Texas empire he started in 1920.
   By the 1970s his holdings ranged from farm, cattle, oil, gas and
nursery operations to control of six banks, stock in other banks and
land sales entimated at $1 million a month. Although he had sold his
bank holdings, Bentsen continued farming, running 5,000 head of
cattle, operating a nursery, taking in oil and gas revenues and
managing a real estate business.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Gordon Allott</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ENGLEWOOD, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gordon Allott, a former U.S. senator,
died Tuesday of cancer at the age of 82.
   Allott graduated from the University of Colorado in Boulder in
1927 and from its law school in 1929.
   During World War II, he was a major in the Army Air Corps.
   Allott served terms as Lamar city attorney, district attorney and
Colorado's lieutenant governor from 1951-1955. He was also vice
chairman of the state Board of Parole.
   Allott, a Republican, served three terms in the U.S. Senate from
1955 to 1973. He also worked on the Appropriations and Interior
committees. Allott was the Senate sponsor for the Colorado River
Basin Storage Act of 1968, which provided for construction of five
Colorado water projects and the Central Arizona Project.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Gerald Probst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gerald G. Probst, 65, a decorated World War
II pilot who later rose through the corporate ranks to become
chairman of Sperry Corp., died Sunday. The cause of death had not
been determined as of Tuesday.
   Probst joined the Air Force in 1942 and commanded a B-24 bomber
in World War II missions over Europe. He was awarded the
distinguished flying cross and the air medal with three oak leaf
clusters.
   Probst joined Sperry Univac in St. Paul, Minn., in 1961. He was
named to positions of increasing responsibility over the next
decade, being promoted to a divisional presidency in 1971.
   Probst became corporate vice president in 1974, executive vice
president in 1975, and company president in 1980. He was elected
chairman of the board of Sperry in 1982.
   Probst was named chairman and chief executive officer of Sperry
in September 1986 when the $5 billion computer and defense systems
company merged with Burroughs Corp. to form Uinsys. He retired a few
months later but continued to serve as a member of Uinsys
International's advisory board.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>George Tweed</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRANTS PASS, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Tweed, a World War II Navy
radioman who eluded Japanese forces on the Pacific island of Guam
for more than two years and became the subject of a movie, died
Monday in a car accident in Northern California at age 86.
   When Japanese forces overran Guam in 1941, Tweed and several
others slipped into the jungle rather than surrender. He became the
lone survivor after the others were captured and killed.
   Tweed managed to elude Japanese soldiers for two years and seven
months, providing information to American forces that recaptured the
island in 1944. He was awarded the Legion of Merit.
   His story was told in the book ``Robinson Crusoe USN,'' and the
1962 movie ``No Man is an Island,'' starring Jeffrey Hunter as
Tweed.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Fred Cooper</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fred Cooper, an editor with the Sanford
Herald, died Tuesday of lung cancer. He was 58.
   Cooper was editorial page editor of the newspaper.
   He worked for the New Orleans Times-Picayune and the Washington
Evening Star early in his career.
   Cooper spent 15 years as sports information director at Stetson
University in DeLand and earlier was a psychological warfare writer
with the U.S. Army.
   Most recently, Cooper played a key role in development of the
Florida Sports Hall of Fame and helped cover sports events for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Jorge Cruickshank Garcia</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressman Jorge Cruickshank Garcia,
co-founder and leader for two decades of the Popular Socialist
Party, died Tuesday of a brain tumor Tuesday at age 73.
   With the late Vicente Lombardo Toledano, Cruickshank Garcia
helped found the party in 1948 and had been its secretary-general
since 1968.
   Cruickshank Garcia was serving his fourth term in Congress,
representing Mexico City's Federal District, similar to the District
of Columbia in the United States. He was a senator from 1976-1982.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Paul Sheatsley</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul B. Sheatsley, an expert in the field of
survey research, died Sunday after a long bout with empheysema. He
was 72.
   Sheatsley began his career in survey research as an interviewer
for the Gallup organization. He joined the National Opinion Research
Center at the University of Chicago in 1942 and directed the
center's New York office until 1961, when he became head of the
research center's main office in Chicago. He was president of the
research center from 1967-68.
   He supervised a number of innovative studies, including one on
the public reaction to the assassination of President John F.
Kennedy in 1963. He was known for his work in survey design and
methods and in health care and race relations research.
</TEXT>
