<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 0710EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--LoudParties     01-18 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Loud Parties,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rowdy Parties Could Mean Hefty Fines under Proposed Ordinance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTH LAKE TAHOE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People who throw parties that get
out of hand could find themselves in trouble with more than the
neighbors.
   A bill that got its first reading Tuesday by South Lake Tahoe
City Council would let the city bill people for the police time
involved if somebody calls the police to the same address twice.
   The measure would let the party-thrower be charged up to $500.
   Council member Neva Roberts voiced the only opposition to the
measure, saying the city already has laws to deal with disturbing
the peace and adding that she thinks there are people who will
complain even when a party isn't loud enough to warrant it.
   Besides, she asked, ``What fun is a party with no noise, anyway?''
   The ordinance is scheduled for a second reading Feb. 7. If
approved then, it will become law 30 days later.
</TEXT>
