<FIRST>r a PM-BoxOffice     01-18 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Box Office,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Rain Man' and `Twins' Remain At Top</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brotherly sagas ``Rain Man'' and ``Twins''
maintained the top two positions in box office receipts for the
fifth consecutive weekend.
   ``Rain Man,'' starring Dustin Hoffman as an autistic savant
kidnapped by his brother, portrayed by Tom Cruise, was No. 1 last
weekend with $10.1 million in ticket sales. ``Twins,'' with Danny
DeVito and Arnold Schwarzenegger as reunited twins who had been
separated at birth, brought in $6.7 million.
   It was the third straight weekend that the films finished in that
order. The previous two weekends, ``Twins'' finished ahead of ``Rain
Man.''
   ``Beaches,'' starring Better Midler and Barbara Hershey as two
women with an inseparable friendship, earned $5.1 million for third
place last weekend as Disney widened its distribution.
   In fourth place was ``Accidental Tourist,'' earning $4.8 million,
followed by ``Working Girl'' with $4.5 million.
   ``The Naked Gun: From the Files of Police Squad'' earned $4.4
million in its seventh week of release.
   ``Mississippi Burning,'' a fictionalized account of two FBI
agents investigating the real slaying of three civil rights workers
in the South during the 1960s, also went to wider distribution last
weekend and took seventh place with just over $4 million.
   ``Deep Star Six,'' about a giant crab that devours undersea
explorers, made a weak debut in eighth with $3.3 million.
   ``Dirty Rotten Scoundrels'' was next with just over $3 million
and ``Oliver and Co.'' with $1.9 million.
   No major releases were announced for this week, with theater
owners anticipating the usual poor box office during Super Bowl
weekend, said Exhibitor Relations Co. chief John Krier.
   Here are the top movies for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations, with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross and number of weeks in
release.
   1. ``Rain Man,'' MGM-UA, $10.1 million, 1,482 screens, $6,823 per
screen, $69 million, five weeks.
   2. ``Twins,'' Universal, $6.7 million, 1,630 screens, $4,140 per
screen, $73.4 million, six weeks.
   3. ``Beaches,'' Disney, $5.1 million, 706 screens, $7,309 per
screen, $6.2 million, four weeks.
   4. ``Accidental Tourist,'' Warner Bros., $4.8 million, 954
screens, $5,107 per screen, $13.4 million, four weeks.
   5. ``Working Girl,'' 20th Century Fox, $4.5 million, 1,140
screens, $3,960 per screen, $29.6 million, four weeks.
   6. ``Naked Gun: From the Files of Police Squad,'' Paramount, $4.4
million, 1,765 screens, $2,494 per screen, $60.1 million, seven
weeks.
   7. ``Mississippi Burning,'' Orion, $4 million, 551 screens,
$7,417 per screen, $5.7 million, six weeks.
   8. ``Deep Star Six,'' TriStar, $3.3 million, 1,117 screens,
$2,960 per screen, $3.3 million, one week.
   9. ``Dirty Rotten Scoundrels,'' Orion, $3 million, 1,490 screens,
$2,021 per screen, $31.1 million, five weeks.
   10. ``Oliver and Co.,'' Disney, $1.9 million, 1,410 screens,
$1,360 per screen, $45.9 million, nine weeks.
</TEXT>
