<FIRST>r w PM-FriendlyTakeover Bjt   01-18 0749</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Friendly Takeover, Bjt,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time for Goodbyes for Reagan Veterans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Through her window, she can see the tourists on
Pennsylvania Avenue gawking through the wrought-iron fence at the
White House. She can scan the stream of visitors arriving to see the
president. She sits at the center of a universe of prime ministers,
senators and heroic warriors who will headline the evening news.
   For only one more day, Leslye Arsht will sit in the little
cubicle in the West Wing of the White House, dealing with the
affairs of _ and sometimes speaking for _ the president of the
United States. Then, at the stroke of 12 on Friday, she turns in her
pass and is out.
   ``There's life after the White House,'' says Ms. Arsht, her voice
the least bit uncertain.
   In Washington, a company town if there ever was one, 4,307 Reagan
administration jobs are up for grabs. Some who hold those jobs will
stay where they are, but many more, like Leslye Arsht, find
themselves on the job market.
   It is the friendliest of takeovers, this quadrennial rite,
compared to the agony that occurs when a Democrat turns the White
House over to a Republican, or vice versa. Not for 156 years has a
president handed the reins to the man who served him as vice
president.
   Yet, while the Bushites aren't exactly storming the gates, it's a
traumatic time for many.
   As Ronald Reagan flies off into the sunset, he leaves behind many
loyal workers who wonder why they are suddenly out, while others
stay on. The answer, of course, is that people work hard in a
campaign, and the jobs that serve as rewards are in great demand.
   ``We had our turn; now it's their turn,'' says Ms. Arsht, who
came from the Commerce Department two years ago with Marlin
Fitzwater when he became Reagan's spokesman. She has been deputy
press secretary, a job that will go to Bush spokesman Steve Hart.
   ``I'm a Texan, a lifetime supporter of George Bush,'' she says.
``It's a bittersweet time.''
   Outside her door in the White House press office is a huge box
being filled with files for the National Archives. The work of the
press office goes on, but it's obvious that things are being readied
for the big change.
   On Friday, the rooms will be mostly empty, the cupboards bare,
the walls nude. It won't be as stark as, say, when Jimmy Carter left
town eight years ago, because Fitzwater will stay on to serve Bush
as chief spokesman.
   In one part of the office, a cardboard box is marked ``Do not
throw away. This is not trash.'' In the hallway, a photo gallery
that has been dominated by pictures of Ron and Nancy Reagan has
undergone a subtle turn: The pictures of the Reagans have been
augmented by photos of Reagan and Bush.
   One of those who is leaving is Connie Gerrard, the closest thing
the White House has to an institutional memory. Ms. Gerrard came
into the White House 25 years ago with Lyndon Johnson, as a
fresh-from-college secretary after the assassination of John F.
Kennedy.
   She has stayed, serving as the press secretary's secretary,
through Nixon, Carter, Ford and Reagan, and she is ready to live a
life without the endless workdays and the constant crises.
   ``I now want to be able to control my own schedule,'' she says.
She knows what the incoming Bush staffers will soon learn, that ``in
the press office, you have to hit the ground running. There is
nothing to prepare you for what you find when you get here.''
   Indeed, reporters were pressing Fitzwater on Tuesday about where
they will get information after noon on Friday. Fitzwater and B. Jay
Cooper will be the only veteran hands remaining in the Bush
administration.
   The rest of the press office staff will come from the Bush team.
Many of them will see the inside of the office for the first time
when they come to work on inauguration day.
   ``It's a matter of sensitivity,'' Cooper says. ``Nobody wants to
have the new person watching over their shoulder.''
   Many of the people leaving spent the weekend packing their own
belongings. Reagan, too, was seen by Fitzwater last week putting
some things into a box.
   ``The president and first lady have been packing for some time,''
Fitzwater said. ``They have shipped most of their private goods to
California already.'''
</TEXT>
