<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     01-18 0865</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,870</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets, Chinese Make US Wheat Purchase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Private exporters have new orders for 530,000
metric tons of U.S. wheat from the Soviet Union and 200,000 metric
tons from the Chinese under the Agriculture Department program that
lets them buy grain at cut-rate prices.
   The wheat sold to the Soviet Union by private exporters was part
of 2 million tons authorized Dec. 23 under the department's Export
Enhancement Program, or EEP, Melvin E. Sims, general sales manager
for the department's Foreign Agricultural Service, said Tuesday.
   The wheat was bought under a long-term supply agreement with the
United States, now in its sixth year.
   Sims said the wheat is for shipment in January, February and
March. Counting some wheat left over from previous EEP arrangements,
the Soviets have 670,200 tons still available under the program.
   The Chinese, however, have used almost all of their current
subsidy authorization. In the past, each country has had new
authorizations set by USDA after exhausting what was available.
   The Soviet Union bought more than 9 million tons of wheat under
EEP arrangements during the fifth year of the grain agreement. The
pact expired last Sept. 30 but was later extended through Dec. 31,
1990.
   The EEP arrangement allows exporters to sell wheat and other
designated commodities to specified countries at reduced prices in
order to meet foreign competition. The exporters then collect free
government surpluses of grain or other products as bonuses, or
subsidies.
   Last year, U.S. corn sales to the Soviet Union totaled slightly
less than 5.2 million tons. Wheat sales in 1987-88, all subsidized,
totaled slightly more than 9 million tons.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 530,000 tons of
wheat would be about 19.5 million bushels.
   Wheat prices at the farm have been averaging more than $4 per
bushel, according to recent USDA market figures, making the new sale
worth an estimated $78 million.
   Besides the wheat for 1988-89 delivery under the pact, the
Soviets have ordered 10.2 million tons of corn, 450,000 tons of
soybeans, and 1,132,500 tons of soybean meal, plus 500,000 tons of
grain sorghum. Only the wheat is subsidized.
   Sims said the wheat sales will carry an average subsidy rate of
$23.35 per ton, or about 64 cents per bushel. He said the bonuses on
the 530,000 tons of wheat will be paid to eight companies: Cargill
Inc., 80,000 tons; Continental Grain Co., 200,000; Garnac Grain Co.,
50,000; Richco Grain Ltd., 50,000; Tradigrain Inc., 50,000;
Mitsubishi International Corp., 25,000; Louis Dreyfus Corp., 25,000;
and Bunge Corp., 50,000.
   In the case of the 200,000 tons sold to China, Sims said the
wheat was part of 1 million tons authorized Dec. 30 for China.
   The wheat sales were handled by two companies: Cargill Inc.,
115,000 tons, and Louis Dreyfus Corp., 85,000 tons.
   Sims said the wheat was sold for March shipment and will carry an
average subsidy rate of $22.49 per ton, or about 62 cents per bushel.
   Only 10,000 tons remain available to China under the program, he
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says that for the
first time it will reserve some of its summer jobs for students from
17 historically black universities.
   Deputy Secretary Peter C. Myers said Tuesday that 563 of the 1989
summer jobs will be held aside as part of the department's effort
``to increase the number of minority students in agriculture,
forestry and home economics.''
   Last year 17,753 students nationwide worked during the summer
months for various USDA agencies, and officials said they expect
about that many this year. The 563 jobs reserved for the black
schools would represent about 3 percent of the total.
   ``Agriculture is more than crop and livestock production,'' Myers
said. ``Animal and plant sciences, economics, forestry, marketing
and computer technology are just some of the varied career fields in
agriculture today.''
   Myers said the jobs will be with 19 USDA agencies and will be
located nationwide. He said interested students at 17 institutions
should contact university placement offices before March 1.
   The universities, collectively known as 1890 institutions because
of land-grant legislation that year, are being targeted in other
ways by USDA, Myers said.
   On Dec. 29, the department announced it is establishing offices
at each of the 17 schools to help encourage more minorities in
agriculture. Also, on Jan. 9, the proposed USDA budget for next year
included $80.2 million for new and expanded programs to increase the
teaching, recruitment and research capabilities at the 1890 schools,
a 20 percent increase from the current level.
   The 17 schools are:
   Alabama A&amp;M, Huntsville.
   Alcorn State University, Lorman, Miss.
   University of Arkansas, Pine Bluff.
   Delaware State College, Dover.
   Florida A&amp;M University, Tallahassee.
   Fort Valley State College, Fort Valley, Ga.
   Kentucky State University, Frankfort.
   Langston University, Langston, Okla.
   Lincoln University, Jefferson City, Mo.
   University of Maryland-Eastern Shore, Princess Anne.
   North Carolina A&amp;T State University, Greensboro.
   Prairie View A&amp;M University, Prairie View, Texas.
   South Carolina State College, Orangeburg.
   Southern University, Baton Rouge, La.
   Tennessee State University, Nashville.
   Tuskegee University, Tuskegee, Ala.
   Virginia State University, Petersburg.
</TEXT>
