<FIRST>r w PM-WorldGrain     01-18 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-World Grain,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>European Countries Making Hay with Grain Sales</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wheat supply crunch in the United States and
Canada is helping the 12-nation European Economic Community export
surplus grain at record levels and fat prices, according to
Agriculture Department analysts.
   The department's Foreign Agricultural Service said Tuesday that
``limited southern hemisphere exportable supplies'' of wheat,
coupled with a tight inventory in North America, is behind the surge
in EEC exports.
   According to the agency's report, the EEC will export a record 19
million metric tons of wheat in the international trading year that
runs through June, up from 15.3 million tons in 1987-88.
   Meanwhile, U.S. wheat exports were projected at 40.9 million
tons, down from 43.4 million tons in 1987-88. Canada's exports were
shown at 11.7 million tons, down from 23.6 million last year.
Australia and Argentina also showed declines.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat.
   It said the 1989 U.S. winter wheat crop, for harvest this coming
summer, ``will be the first new-crop supplies available for export
and, given the nature of the world wheat market, the size and
quality of this crop will likely set the stage for prices in
1989-90.''
   The USDA reported last week that American farmers had boosted
plantings of winter wheat for this year's harvest by 12 percent.
However, much of the newly planted crop is in need of moisture.
   ``Wheat prices continue to strengthen and have reached their
highest level since January 1982 amid a flurry of recent purchases
and early concerns about the North America wheat crop,'' the report
said.
   The global wheat stockpile by this summer is expected to shrink
to 115.3 million tons from 145.6 million tons a year ago, the report
said. Foreign supplies were projected at 100.8 million tons,
compared with 14.5 million tons in the United States.
   Last summer the U.S. share of the wheat inventory was 34.3
million tons and the remainder of the world, 111.3 million tons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
