<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 0223EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-AutoSafety     01-18 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Safety,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fiero Fire Allegations Subject of New NHTSA Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration says it will investigate reports of fires in the
engine compartments of 1985 and 1986 Pontiac Fiero cars.
   The preliminary evaluation, the lowest level of investigation by
the safety agency, follows the recall in 1987 of 125,000 Fieros from
the 1984 model year after similar fire reports.
   The latest investigation involves about 147,000 Fieros and was
ordered after the agency received 16 unconfirmed complaints of
fires. One of the complaints said the fire resulted in an injury,
NHTSA said Tuesday.
   General Motors Corp., which makes the Fiero, said it was
reviewing the allegations in preparing its response to NHTSA. GM
spokesman John Anderson said, as is usual in such cases, that the
opening of an inquiry doesn't necessarily mean there is a defect.
   NHTSA also opened six other low-level investigations into safety
allegations involving cars, vans and light trucks made by major U.S.
manufacturers.
   The preliminary evaluations focused on unconfirmed reports of:
   _Steering-linkage lockup causing a loss of control in 35,000 1988
GM Chevrolet Blazer and Jimmy K5 vehicles. NHTSA reported five
complaints with one accident reported.
   _Electronic air-suspension failure involving 60,000 1988-1989
Ford Motor Co. Lincoln Continental cars. The agency had received
three complaints, including one involving an accident with injury.
   _Fires under the bodies of 1986-1988 Ford F150 and F350 pickup
trucks having the F1 fuel-injected engine. The agency had received
three complaints.
   _Cutting and fraying of the right-hand front seatbelt in 450,000
1986-1988 Ford Aerostars. Two complaints were received.
   _Antifreeze fires under the hoods of 1,000 1983-1987 Ford F350
trucks converted to ambulances. NHTSA received five complaints.
   _Electrical shorts in the tail-light wiring harness of 416,000
1987 Chrysler Dodge Omni cars. Three complaints were reported by
NHTSA.
   NHTSA raised to an engineering analysis, a higher level of
investigation, its study of unconfirmed reports of brake-light
failure in 1985 BMW cars.
   The agency also ended three preliminary evaluations into major
manufacturers' vehicles and concluded in each case there was ``no
defect trend.''
   The investigations closed were into unsubstantiated reports of:
   _Heater-core rupture in 1987 VW Golf vehicles.
   _Floor-mat interference with the gas pedal on 1987-1988 Ford
Thunderbird and Mercury Cougar cars.
   _Rear-hub failure in 1986-1987 GM Pontiac Fieros.
</TEXT>
