<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 0236EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Nader-Reagan     01-18 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nader-Reagan,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nader Groups Challenge Reagan Record Against `Media Cloud Nine'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An environmental group says it is applying one
of Ronald Reagan's favorite slogans to George Bush's claim to care
about fighting pollution: ``Trust but Verify.''
   David Baker, political director of Friends of the Earth, said
Tuesday the slogan applies because Bush spearheaded the Reagan
administration's drive to relax many government regulations early in
its tenure.
   ``We're willing to take him at his word right now when he says
he's an environmentalist, but we're keeping him on a short leash,''
Baker said. ``Trust but Verify'' is slogan Reagan has often quoted
about arms control negotiations with the Soviet Union.
   Baker's was one of several advocacy groups represented at a news
conference held by consumer activist Ralph Nader to promote their
highly critical view of the Reagan years.
   The groups summed up their longstanding differences with the
administration's regulation of food, drugs, the environment,
pesticides, auto safety and energy.
   The Environmental Protection Administration was ``in bed with the
polluters'' in the early years of the Reagan administration, Baker
said.
   Although that stopped with a change in agency leadership, EPA has
removed only 18 sites from the list of 1,175 scheduled for priority
handling under the ``Superfund'' toxic waste cleanup program and has
completed work at only 45 more, said Baker.
   Nader said he called the news conference to offset what Nader
called an ``orchestrated media cloud nine'' that he blamed in part
on ``the abdication of the role of loyal opposition by the
Democratic Party, none of whose leaders have made any attempt to
reflect publicly on the record of the Reagan government.''
   Among the criticisms:
   _The administration's opposition to and delay of air bags in cars
cost 40,000 lives and 1 million injuries, said Joan Claybrook, head
of Public Citizen, the umbrella advocacy organization founded by
Nader. Ms. Claybrook was head of the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration in President Carter's administration.
   _Relaxed oversight of drugs and medical devices cost thousands of
lives, said Dr. Sidney M. Wolfe, director of Public Citizen's Health
Research Group. Delay of warnings on aspirin about Reye's syndrome
cost 1,000 lives, he said. ``The worst of my fears have come to
pass,'' Wolfe said.
   _The Environmental Protection Agency plans to relax pesticide
residue standards on foods and has adopted a farmworker protection
policy ``that protects employers,'' said Jay Feldman, coordinator of
the National Campaign Against the Misuse of Pesticides.
   _The administration failed to pursue conservation, overemphasized
nuclear power and rolled back auto efficiency standards, complained
Ken Bossong, director of Public Citizen's Critical Mass Energy
Project and Clarence Ditlow, executive director of the Center for
Auto Safety, a group founded with Nader's help.
   _Under orders from the White House, FDA ``fought hard to keep
cancer-causing food additives on the market, has substituted
politics and rigid ideology for reasoned scientific
decision-making'' and has starved its food regulatory program so
much that even the industry pleaded for bigger budgets, said Bruce
Silverglade, legal director of the Center for Science in the Public
Interest.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
