<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 0236EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-InauguralGala     01-18 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Inaugural Gala,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big-Name Stars Rehearse for $9 Million Inaugural Gala</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the biggest names in show business are
rehearsing for a glittering, nationally televised inaugural gala
Thursday night that will boast George Bush and Dan Quayle as special
guests in the black-tie audience of 12,000 people.
   Inaugural officials say the two-hour show may attract a
prime-time TV audience of 40 million to 60 million viewers. Ticket
sales and proceeds from TV commercials may gross about $9 million,
making the gala the biggest moneymaker in four days of privately
financed inaugural festivities.
   Rehearsals began at midday Tuesday in the cavernous Washington
Convention Center when a Walter Cronkite stand-in introduced
Broadway and TV star Nell Carter, who danced and belted out the
opening number, Fats Waller's ``The Joint is Jumpin,'' with a
frenetic chorus line wearing sweatsuits.
   Miss Carter said she voted for Bush in the November election. ``I
think he's an honorable man,'' she said. ``I think he should be
given a chance.''
   Other gala headliners will include singers Frank Sinatra, Anita
Baker and Julio Iglesias; ballet dancers Susan Jaffe and Mikhail
Baryshnikov, actor and muscleman Arnold Schwarzenegger, child
fiddlers from Kentucky and Idaho, Broadway hoofer Tommy Tune,
cellist Yo Yo Ma, actor Chuck Norris, opera singer Roberta Peters,
Gen. Chuck Yeager, the U.S. Naval Academy Glee Club and the Mormon
Tabernacle Choir.
   The 13 acts will include two of Bush's country and Western
favorites, Loretta Lynn and the Oak Ridge Boys, along with Randy
Travis, Crystal Gayle, Cissy Lynn and Peggy Sue Wright.
   Producer Don Mischer of Los Angeles said the cast of more than
1,100 performers will represent a ``cross-section of American
entertainment'' and will include ``some surprises'' which he refused
to disclose. However, a stack of oversized cue cards for comedian
Bob Hope was spotted behind a TV camera in the rear of the hall.
   All 90 of the eight-seat ``boxes'' at the gala _ actually stack
chairs surrounded by flimsy blue partitions on the floor facing the
stage _ were sold for $25,000 each, for a total of $2.25 million.
Other seats were ticketed at $150 to $250, depending on location.
   The president-elect, his family and guests will sit in a large,
elevated box facing the front of the stage, which will be surrounded
by seats. A smaller box for Vice President-elect Quayle and his
guests will be situated to Bush's left.
   Inaugural officials say 14 minutes of TV commercial time already
have been sold for $4.9 million. Proceeds from invitation-only
ticket sales could boost gross revenues to about $9 million.
   With big-name performers donating their time for free, the gala
could yield about $6 million after expenses to help defray inaugural
costs.
</TEXT>
