<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 0245EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Budget     01-18 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soft-Pedaling Increases Won't Fool Public, Bush Adviser Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The public is likely to view higher levies on
gasoline, alcohol and tobacco as tax increases, even if politicians
try to soft-pedal them by calling them ``user fees,''
President-elect Bush's incoming budget director says.
   The comments by Richard Darman shed light on the thinking of the
new administration and Bush, who campaigned on a pledge of no new
taxes. Lawmakers and others in Washington have been closely watching
the words of Bush and his aides to see if the vice president backs
off his campaign promise.
   Darman submitted written answers to questions posed by the Senate
Governmental Affairs Committee, which holds confirmation hearings
Thursday on his appointment. The questionnaire and responses were
obtained Tuesday from a source who asked to not be identified.
   Darman, who has been tapped as Bush's chief of the Office of
Management and Budget, said that ``depending on the application of
funds,'' taxes on gasoline, tobacco and alcohol might be called user
fees.
   But he added, ``the public, however, tends to see these rather
unequivocally as taxes.''
   He said fees for government services are not a tax ``as long as
the government is directly charging the beneficiary only for the
cost of the service provided by the government.''
   He also said eliminating the deduction for interest on certain
types of borrowing and taxing employer-provided fringe benefits
could be considered ``definitional changes.''
   ``One could engage in long discussions of when one or another
revenue measure is or is not a tax,'' Darman wrote.
   ``Putting academics and sophistry aside, however, my suspicion is
that in the end such definitional matters are political: applying
the old if-it-looks-like-a-duck rule, if it looks like a tax to most
Americans, it's a tax.''
   Many congressional Democrats have said they do not understand how
the fiscal 1990 deficit can be reduced to $100 billion, as required
by the Gramm-Rudman balanced budget law, without new taxes.
   Senate Budget Committee Chairman Jim Sasser, D-Tenn., asked
Tuesday about Darman's comments on taxes, said President Reagan was
never tagged as a taxer, even though he signed 11 tax increases into
law.
   ``George Bush may find he wants to try to follow in that
tradition, but one thing should be clear: We in Congress stand ready
to work with the administration to deal with these massive deficits,
regardless of semantics, and we look forward to a budget proposal
from George Bush,'' he said in a written statement.
   House Budget Committee Chairman Leon Panetta, D-Calif., also
discussed budget matters Tuesday, indicating that the $13 billion in
new revenues contained in the spending plan Reagan submitted last
week might be a good starting point for negotiations between the
White House and Congress.
   ``If the Reagan number is used, which is $13 billion, then
obviously that gives us the opportunity to look not only at those
that were suggested by the administration, but other areas as well
in order to meet that number,'' Panetta told members of the National
Press Club.
   Panetta said the revenue raisers proposed by Reagan, along with
excise taxes on items such as energy, ``are worthy of
consideration.''
   In his budget, Reagan proposed raising new money by selling
federal assets, imposing or increasing user fees, repealing a
reduction in aviation taxes, and other measures.
</TEXT>
