<FIRST>r w PM-House-CampaignFunds     01-18 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-House-Campaign Funds,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Loophole Open for $39 Million in House Campaign Funds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A select group of 190 House members stockpiled
$39.2 million in campaign money that can be converted to their
personal use under a loophole in election laws, a non-profit group
says.
   Public Citizen's Congress Watch noted Tuesday that the select
group is covered by a special provision in federal law permitting
those who were serving in the House on Jan. 8, 1980, to keep any
remaining campaign funds.
   The report also said the members of the House elected to the new
Congress have built combined campaign war chests of $67 million.
   Public Citizen is a research, lobbying and litigation group
founded by consumer advocate Ralph Nader in 1971.
   Its report blamed the surplus campaign chests for the 98 percent
success rate among House incumbents running in 1988 and 1986,
adding, ``There is a greater turnover in the Supreme Soviet than in
the U.S. House of Representatives.''
   ``This certainly discourages qualified candidates from
challenging the financially stronger representatives and further
ensures the `incumbent lock' on the House.''
   The report covered the period from Jan. 1, 1987, through Nov. 28,
1988.
   The $67 million in surplus money averages $154,000 per member, up
39 percent from the 1985-86 balance of $48.4 million _ an average of
$111,332.
   The $39.2 million stockpiled by 189 current members and the late
Rep. Bill Nichols, D-Ala., for possible personal use is a 34 percent
increase from the amount on hand in January 1987.
   Those who can take advantage of the loophole can watch their
money grow ``until they retire,'' the report said. The money ``can
be transferred to other political races, donated to their favorite
charities (while writing off the tax deduction), used to buy a new
car or pay for that needed vacation,'' according to the report.
   The report said Reps. David Dreier, R-Calif., Stephen J. Solarz,
D-N.Y., and Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., each have more than $1 million
stockpiled, with Solarz and Rostenkowski permitted to convert the
money to personal use.
   After surveying how former House members used the money, the
report said that Rep. Mario Biaggi, D-N.Y., spent $386,064 in
leftover campaign funds on legal expenses related to his criminal
convictions.
   He was found guilty of accepting an illegal gratuity and
obstruction of justice in accepting a paid Florida vacation from a
former Brooklyn Democratic leader; and of racketeering and accepting
bribes from Wedtech Corp. in exchange for his Washington influence.
   The late Rep. James Howard, D-N.J., left $310,000 to his wife,
and the late Rep. John Duncan, R-Tenn., left more than $600,000 to
his family, the report said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
