<DOCNO> AP890118-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 0256EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China-Suicide     01-18 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Suicide,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suicides, Other Unnatural Deaths On The Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suicides and other unnatural deaths have increased
by 50 percent during the 1980s, the official Xinhua News Agency said
today.
   A survey of 10 million people in 25 locales found that the death
rate from unnatural causes increased from 31 per 100,000 people in
1981 to 47 in 1987.
   Four-fifths of the deaths came by suicide, drowning, poisoning
and traffic accidents, Xinhua said. The report did not say if murder
was included in the statistics.
   China gives no statistics on suicide, but Xinhua said that in the
countryside, where most Chinese live, one-third of unnatural deaths
were by suicide. More women than men took their own lives, it said.
   The survey found that family disputes, marital problems and poor
personal relations led to half the suicides. About 20 percent of
suicides were terminally ill patients.
   The report said two-thirds of those killing themselves used
poison, and called for tighter control over dispensing of poisons.
   Tens of thousands of Chinese are believed to have killed
themselves during the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution when
ultra-leftists persecuted huge numbers of people.
   Today, most suicides are linked to personal problems and
difficulties in adjusting to social changes as China switches to a
more market-oriented, competitive economic system. Last year, the
nation's first non-governmental suicide prevention center was
established in Canton.
</TEXT>
