<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     01-18 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VERSAILLES, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ah, soon the pitter-patter of little feet
_ lots of them _ might be heard at the White House.
   Millie, President-elect and Barbara Bush's springer spaniel, has
spent the last two weeks at a farm in Kentucky, where she was mated
with Tug, a springer spaniel owned by Will and Sarah Farish.
   ``We believe she's pregnant, but we don't know that for a fact,''
Farish said Monday.
   Farish said they would know in about three weeks if the
2-year-old dog is pregnant. If she is, she likely would give birth
in March.
   The Farishes gave Millie to the Bushes about a year ago.
   Farish said he telephoned Mrs. Bush on Friday and ``told her
everything had gone fine.''
   ``She's very close to Millie,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired obstetrician used his trade
skills and techniques he saw on a television show about a
veterinarian to ``deliver'' a 55-pound dog from the 6-foot deep hole
it had been digging for months.
   Dr. Daniel B. Dorman's next-door neighbor called him Saturday
night when she found Dusty, a 10-year-old mutt, was stuck in the
hole, with just his wagging tail sticking out.
   Dorman got a shovel and pickax, but found they were of limited
use on the frozen ground.
   Drawing on his experience delivering breech babies and memories
of the TV show ``All Creatures Great and Small,'' Dorman worked his
arm into the hole, grabbed the dog's hind legs, stretched them out
and tied them with a rope.
   He then pulled the rope slowly to free the mutt, which was dirty
but unharmed.
   ``This was the first delivery I've had since I stopped practicing
seven years ago,'' Dorman said. ``I hope it's my last breech
delivery.''
</TEXT>
