<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 0341EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-InauguralArtists     01-18 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Inaugural Artists,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Artists, Government Figures Mingle At National Gallery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Artists such as Frank Stella and Roy
Lichtenstein mingled with congressmen, bureaucrats, judges, patrons,
diplomats and other dignitaries at a pre-inaugural party marking the
10th anniversary of the National Gallery of Art's East Building.
   More than 1,000 people attended the black-tie event Tuesday
night, including I.M. Pei, the architect who designed the East
Building at the foot of Capitol Hill; Supreme Court Justice Anthony
M. Kennedy; art collector Estee Lauder; Sen. Charles Robb, D-Va.;
and Carla Hills, nominated by President-elect Bush to be U.S. trade
representative.
   Touring the gallery's newly mounted exhibition of 20th Century
paintings, drawings and sculpture on three floors of the East
Building, Stella predicted that George Bush will continue government
support for the arts, though without any ``great outpouring'' of
federal assistance.
   ``The emphasis will be on the performing arts,'' said Stella,
waving a cigar under one of the giant canvases. ``He won't be
interested in supporting the avant garde. The government's job is to
take care of the majority.''
   ``They don't need to take care of those who can take care of
themselves,'' said Stella, known for his minimalist paintings on
different shaped canvases. ``We're not charity cases.''
   Stella and Lichtenstein agreed that the healthy economy favors
artists by spurring purchase of their works as financial investments
and additions to private collections.
   ``The arts are doing very well now,'' said Lichtenstein, who
famous for his comic strip technique. ``My guess is that they (the
Bush administration) will do more for the arts.''
   Nevertheless, he said: ``It's not that you just spend money and
everything gets better. It's shameful, too, that we have such a
wealthy government that supports art so little compared with other
Western countries.''
   The gallery's recently installed exibition of more than 230 early
art works from Picasso will remain on view for two years with
support by a grant from American Express.
</TEXT>
