<HEAD>Dollar Inches Up Against Yen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched up against the Japanese yen
Wednesday, while share prices closed at another record high as
investors were concerned about U.S. trade figures to be released
later in the day.
   The dollar closed at 127.90 yen, up 0.20 yen from Tuesday's
127.70-yen finish. The currency moved in a range of 127.63-128.00
yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, a 70.86-point loser the
previous day, regained 127.03 points, or 0.41 percent, to finish at
31,354.55.
   Stock dealers said trading was slow because of investor concern
over the upcoming U.S. trade report, although market sentiment is
still strong.
   In the currency market, traders said the dollar will remain in a
narrow trading range before the Commerce Department releases its
November merchandise trade report. The department will announce the
figure later Wednesday in Washington.
   Tokyo investors predict the U.S. monthly trade deficit will widen
to between $11 billion and $12 billion, compared with $10.35 billion
in October. In recent years the U.S. trade deficit numbers have
become a powerful influence on the foreign-exchange market, because
of their role in U.S. economic policy as well as their
unpredictability from month to month.
