<HEAD>Sport Vehicle Importers, U.S. Makers Debate Customs Ruling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. automakers are urging the government to
uphold a Customs Service decision to impose a high import duty on
sport vehicles and vans.
   The chairmen of the three largest U.S. auto manufacturers,
General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp., urged
Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady on Tuesday to affirm a Customs
decision that the popular vehicles are trucks and therefore are
subject to a 25 percent import duty, 10 times the duty levied on
cars.
   A reversal of the ruling would ``cause substantial harm to the
U.S. motor vehicle industry, deprive the U.S. Treasury of several
hundred million dollars in anticipated tariff revenues, and unleash
a long battle in the courts and in Congress...'' said GM's Roger
Smith, Ford's Donald Petersen and Chrysler's Lee Iacocca.
   A group representing dealers in imported vehicles, however,
estimated the higher duty would directly add $500 million a year to
the cost of buying cars in the United States.
   ``This is a $500 million new tax, in effect,'' said Bart Fisher,
attorney for the American International Automobile Dealers
Association.
   The association's president, Robert McElwaine, estimated the
higher import duty would add on average $2,500 to the price of each
vehicle. About 200,000 imported vehicles a year would be affected,
McElwaine said.
