<HEAD>Mixed Reactions In Kokomo To TV's `Ryan White Story'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KOKOMO, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The television movie ``The Ryan White Story''
got mixed reviews from the players in the real saga the hemophiliac
boy who was barred from school after being diagnosed with AIDS.
   The Hollywood version, starring George C. Scott, Judith Light and
Lukas Haas, was broadcast Monday night on ABC.
   ``If the purpose of the film was to portray Ryan, his family and
his feelings, then I am sure it was accurate as they saw it,'' said
Ron Colby, principal of Western Middle School, which barred Ryan
from attending after he was diagnosed with acquired immune
deficiency syndrome in December 1984.
   ``I thought George C. Scott played a nice Charlie Vaughan (Ryan's
attorney) and Lukas Haas reminded me a lot of Ryan. The film
captured the relentless pressure applied to all by the media.''
   But David Rosselot, the attorney for parents who sought to keep
Ryan out of school, called the film ``a subtle insult to the
community as a whole simply because it left the impression that the
community was anti-Ryan White, when in the proper context, it was
not anti-Ryan White, but anti-AIDS in the classroom.''
   The 17-year-old Ryan, who appeared on ABC's Good Morning America
on Monday, said people in Kokomo were apprehensive about how the
movie would depict them, but their behavior was much worse than the
movie lets on.
   Charles Vaughn, Ryan's attorney, said the movie was accurate but
he wished the courtroom scenes had distinguished the difference
between the White family's case against the local school
corporation, which initially sought to bar Ryan, and the injunction
against the boy won by other parents.
   Ryan's family eventually prevailed in both battles, but they have
since moved south to Cicero and Ryan is attending Hamilton Heights
High School in Arcadia.
   Vaughan said the movie ``was very good to Kokomo.''
   ``They better not complain,'' he said. ``I could fill a book with
the conduct of the Western School Corporation.''
   A Western official who was school board president at the time did
not watch the movie.
   ``I'm a high school graduate. I know the meaning of the word
fiction,'' said Don Carter.
</TEXT>
