<FIRST>r a PM-LastSeason     01-18 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Last Season,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Little Leaguer Helps Team To Victory Despite Fatal Tumor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirteen-year-old Eddy Melucci knew he had a
fatal brain tumor, but insisted on playing one more game with his
Little League baseball team before he died.
   The team won the championship. Eddy died Sunday, a few months
later.
   ``I visited him in the hospital 22 days before our first game,
and he told me he was going to play,'' said Randy Hien, Eddy's coach
and manager of the Tigers. ``I half believed him, but he was back at
practice the day before our first game, and he had two hits opening
day.''
   Eddy, who was diagnosed with the tumor last spring, decided to
return to the baseball diamond less than a month after an operation.
   Eddy, normally a third baseman and pitcher, was kept in the
outfield until his reaction time returned to normal. He had to wear
a 15-pound helmet in the early weeks following March's surgery.
   ``We were dealing with a really tough kid who could handle
anything mentally,'' said Russell Fiore, safety director for the
Lincoln Little League and designer of the helmet. ``He was a kid who
just wouldn't quit.''
   ``He made his own decisions: when to have the operation and to
die at home,'' Eddy's mother, Patricia Melucci, said Monday.
   The operation would have left Eddy with five to 15 years to live
if successful, said his father, Edward Melucci. But Eddy fell ill in
Novemeber, and doctor's revised their prognosis to six months.
   Sitting on the Meluccis' kitchen table Monday were the three
baseball awards Eddy won last summer: his league championship
trophy, a smaller trophy for making the league All-Star team that
played in the state tournament, and the Ray Banville Award, the
Lincoln Little League's most prestigious award.
   Inscribed on the Banville plaque are the words ``Performance,
Attitude, Loyalty, Effort.''
   ``He epitomized American youth. He was a parent's dream,'' said
Mrs. Melucci.
</TEXT>
