<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     01-18 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow Blankets Northern Wisconsin; Rain along Northern Pacific Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow fell along part of the nation's northern tier, with up to 8
inches recorded in Wisconsin, while rain was scattered along the
northern Pacific Coast and in Texas.
   Strong gusty winds continued to buffet the eastern slopes of the
Rockies in Montana, and a high wind warning was in effect this
morning for the upper Yellowstone Valley in the state.
   A low pressure system generated snow from eastern North Dakota to
upper Michigan Tuesday. Wisconsin got the brunt of the snowfall,
with up to 8 inches blanketing Douglas County in the state's
northwest corner.
   Clouds extended over the Great Lakes and New England, and
scattered snow dusted New England.
   A storm system at sea spread showers along the northern Pacific
Coast and extended cloud cover to the northern Rockies. Quillayute,
Wash., received 1.21 inches of rain in the six hours ended at 1 a.m.
EST.
   Light rain also fell in southern Texas.
   Today's forecast called for widespread snow in northeast
Minnesota, upper Michigan and northern portions of New York and
Vermont. Scattered rain was expected from southeast Wisconsin into
northern Ohio and western Pennsylvania, along the western and
central Gulf Coast and along the northern Pacific Coast. Fair
weather was forecast for the remainder of the nation.
   Highs were expected in the 20s and 30s from the upper Mississippi
Valley through the Great Lakes to New England, and in much of Idaho,
Utah and Nevada; in the 60s from the southern Atlantic Coast through
the lower Mississippi Valley into central and southern Texas, in
southern portions of Nevada and California, and in the valleys of
northern California; in the 70s along the Southern California coast,
the desert Southwest and in northern and central Florida; and around
80 degrees across southern Florida.
   The rest of the nation could expect highs in the 40s and 50s.
   At 2 a.m. EST, temperatures ranged from 3 degrees below zero at
Craig, Colo., to 72 degrees at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 34 fair; Boston 33 fair; Buffalo 29 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 46 fair; Cincinnati 37 fair; Cleveland 37 cloudy;
Detroit 35 cloudy; Miami 68 fair; New York 39 fair; Philadelphia 30
fair; Pittsburgh 31 fair; Portland, Maine 33 fair; Washington 34
fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 32 fair; Chicago 40 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 48
fair; Denver 32 fair; Des Moines 40 fair; Indianapolis 42 fair;
Kansas City 41 partly cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 28 fair;
Nashville 33 fair; New Orleans 47 fair; St. Louis 46 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 31 fair; Anchorage -11 foggy; Las Vegas 39
fair; Los Angeles 57 fair; Phoenix 47 fair; Salt Lake City 18 foggy;
San Diego 53 fair; San Francisco 45 fair; Seattle 49 windy.
