<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador     01-18 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigation Into Archbishop's Slaying To Continue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The investigation of the 1980
assassination of Archbishop Oscar Romero will continue despite the
Supreme Court's refusal to extradite a former army captain
implicated in the murder, says President Jose Napoleon Duarte.
   He told reporters on Tuesday during a visit to a downtown
hospital construction site that the government has continued trying
to solve the case and ``we will continue as far as we can.''
   ``The case definitely is not closed,'' Justice Minister Julio
Alfredo Samayoa said in a telephone interview.
   Some believe the case was effectively closed last month when the
country's highest court refused to extradite former Capt. Alvaro
Saravia from the United States. In 1987, Duarte's administration
accused Saravia of arranging the assassination of Romero, who was
slain while saying Mass in March 1980.
   During his weekly homilies, Romero had called on soldiers and
security forces to halt the then-rampant murders of suspected
leftists.
   Duarte alleges Saravia acted on orders from Roberto D'Aubuisson,
a cashiered army intelligence major and leader of the rightist
Republican Nationalist Alliance political party, known as Arena.
   D'Aubuisson allegedly directed right-wing death squads in the
early 1980s, but denies any link to death squads and any
responsibility in Romero's murder.
   Arena accuses the Christian Democrats of bringing up the case
before every election in an effort to erode its electoral base. El
Salvador holds presidential elections March 19. Arena, which won
legislative and municipal elections in last March, leads the
Christian Democrats in recent polls.
   Saravia, 46, was freed Thursday from the Miami jail where he had
spent 13 months awaiting resolution of the extradition request and
illegal immigration charges pending against him. He lives in the
Miami suburb of Kendall, and his attorney said he is seeking
political asylum.
   The Salvadoran Supreme Court ruled Dec. 19 that testimony linking
Saravia to the assassination was not credible.
</TEXT>
