<FIRST>r a PM-Miami-Crisis     01-18 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Miami-Crisis,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Riots; Refugee Arrivals, Super Bowl Coincide</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Overtown Riot, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rioting that left at least three blacks dead came as
Miami was trying to absorb 200 asylum-seeking Nicaraguans a day and
coincided with the city's hopes to polish its tarnished image with
the Super Bowl.
   Tensions have been simmering among some blacks over what they
perceive as unjust treatment from police and feelings of frustration
concerning the attention given to the Nicaraguan newcomers,
community leaders said.
   The hoopla over the Super Bowl _ with the city showing off its
new skyline, new bayside attractions and improved image _ may have
added to the disaffection. The fatal shooting of a 23-year-old black
motorcyclist by a white police officer Monday evening provided the
spark, they said.
   ``There have been a lot of other tensions the last few weeks.
They just needed a catalyst,'' said state Rep. James Burke, who
represents Miami. ``These people involved could care less about the
Super Bowl being here. It's not going to help their lives.''
   The motorcyclist's 24-year-old passenger died Tuesday afternoon,
and a young black man was shot to death early today as violence
spread from the poor Overtown section to Liberty City, about 30
blocks to the northwest.
   ``It's really close to what happened before in 1980,'' said Garth
Reeves, long-time publisher of the black-oriented newspaper Miami
Times, referring to the acquittal of Metro-Dade police officers
charged with beating a black man to death. The acquittals sparked
three days of riots that killed 18 people and caused hundreds of
millions of dollars in damage.
   The outbreak of violence in 1980 came as 125,000 Cuban refugees
were arriving in the Mariel boatlift.
   Willie Simms of the Community Relations Board said the warning
signs of this week's violence were apparent. He said his group keeps
a weekly ``tension chart'' and had voiced alarm in recent weeks when
it saw levels similar to 1980 and 1982.
   But, as in the past, perceptions of violence likely will linger
after the violence subsides.
   ``This really puts a damper on literally hundreds of thousands of
volunteer hours that have been put in by this community preparing
for the (Sunday's) Super Bowl,'' said Tom Ferguson, president of the
Beacon Council, which promotes Dade County.
   ``It's not that we have things that are any different from other
urban areas; it's just that the timing of how they occur is
absolutely incredible,'' he added. ``An incident like this you don't
ever want to happen, but it's just doubly unfortunate that it
happens this week.''
   Houston Post sports writer Ray Buck, whose car windshield was
shattered in Monday night's violence, said publicity about the
violence will cancel out Miami's hospitality this week.
   ``Unfortunately, I think a lot of good effort was ruined in one
short three- or four-hour period,'' he said. ``A year of hard work
went down the drain.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
