<FIRST>r a PM-Overtown-Suarez     01-18 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Overtown-Suarez,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayor Suarez Tries To Build Black Ties To Contain Riots</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Overtown Riot, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILL LESTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A weary and frustrated Mayor Xavier Suarez is
reaching out to blacks in an attempt to stem the violence and
tension that has fractured his city for two days.
   Suarez promised an intensive investigation into the fatal
shooting of an unarmed black motorcyclist by a white Hispanic police
officer Monday, which triggered the wave of gunfire, lootings and
arson in the city's Overtown and Liberty City districts.
   ``We will not rest until we come to the bottom of what happened
to spark this riot,'' said Suarez in a televised appeal for calm
Tuesday night. ``We must curb our anger with restraint. We must turn
our fear into strength, for our families and our city.''
   His appeal came after the apparent failure of a police strategy
to end the riots by avoiding major confrontations with angry blacks
in Overtown on Monday night.
   But despite a tranquil morning in Overtown, violence was renewed
Tuesday night and spread to Liberty City, where a young black man
was fatally shot and six other people were wounded.
   Minutes after Monday's fatal shooting, Suarez attempted to
intervene between police and an angry crowd.
   At one point, he walked up to a hostile crowd that had gathered
near the body of the dead motorcyclist and asked for calm. But his
efforts were met with a shower of rocks and bottles.
   City Manager Cesar Odio, watching with police down the street,
told an officer: ``Somebody go get him, he's crazy.'' But Suarez
stood his ground and promised the angry gathering: ``I promise you
to look into this. I will get to the bottom of this.''
   When the 39-year-old Suarez was re-elected to his second two-year
term, he claimed 62 percent of the vote and a majority among the
city's three major groups _ English-speaking whites, Hispanics and
blacks.
   He saw the vote as a sign of better relations between the three
groups.
   He points to his efforts to provide affordable housing projects
in Overtown, the building of the nearby Miami Arena and his frequent
visits to the Overtown community as signs of progress.
   The Cuban-born Suarez grew up in Washington, D.C., and moved to
Miami in 1975. He ran unsuccessfully for the City Commission and for
mayor before his election in 1985. He runs as an independent, but he
is a strong supporter of President-elect Bush.
   Suarez is an attorney with a law degree from Harvard. The married
father of four has been described in national publications as sign
that the Cuban immigrants are coming of age in America.
   But Bill Perry, former leader of the Greater Miami National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, said a year ago
that the Cubans' gain could be perceived as the blacks' loss unless
Suarez does more to build unity.
   And on Tuesday, Suarez was defending his record in the black
community and looking for a way out of the nightmare sparked by the
police shooting.
   ``Overtown was neglected but now is the area in which the city
has been making its greatest effort with the largest urban renewal
project _ affordable housing _ possibly in the entire nation,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
