<FIRST>u i PM-Dali 1stLd-Writethru   01-18 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dali, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0491,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dali In Stable Condition After Suffering Heart Failure</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with seven grafs, doctors saying Dali in stable condition,
quotes. Picks up graf 8 pvs, `A native ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FIGUERAS, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Surrealist painter Salvador Dali was in
stable condition today in the intensive care unit of a Spanish
hospital after suffering heart failure, doctors said.
   A six-doctor team at Figueras Hospital said the 84-year-old
artist was in no immediate health danger. In a medical statement
this morning, the doctors said, ``If there is no major change in his
condition, no further medical statements will be issued until
Friday.''
   Dali has suffered chronic heart ailments in recent years. He has
been hospitalized three times the last two months for severe heart
trouble and in 1986 underwent surgery to receive a pacemaker.
   Dali, a founding member of the surrealist movement, is the last
of an outstanding generation of Spanish painters that included Pablo
Picasso, who died in 1973, and Joan Miro, who died a decade later.
   The statement did not mention whether Dali suffered a lung clot,
although earlier a hospital spokesman had said such a clot had
aggravated the artist's condition.
   The team signing the statement included the artist's longtime
physician, Carles Punsati, and five other doctors.
   Hospital spokeswoman Maria Hernandez said by telephone that Dali
``was resting comfortably,'' but she did not elaborate.
   Doctors permitted Dali to return home Dec. 25 after a three-day
stay in the same hospital for treatment of an intestinal lesion.
   Before that, the painter spent 16 days in Barcelona's Quiron
Clinic in extremely critical condition due to severe heart trouble
aggravated by clots in his left lung. He was released Dec. 14.
   A native of Figuras, 60 miles north of Barcelona, Dali has been
in poor health and wheelchair-bound since August 1984, when he
suffered severe burns in a fire in the bedroom of Pubol Castle, his
residence at the time, in nearby La Pera.
   He was hospitalized for three months after the fire before moving
to Galatea Tower. He has since lived in seclusion, fed by
gastro-nasal tube and watched round-the-clock by a team of nurses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
