<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Kissinger     01-18 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Kissinger,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kissinger Meets With Gorbachev</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev met with
former U.S. Secretary of State Henry Kissinger, the official Soviet
news agency Tass reported.
   Kissinger was in Moscow for a meeting of the Trilateral
Commission, along with former President Valery Giscard d'Estaing of
France and former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone of Japan.
   The 15-year-old commission is a private group of business,
government, labor and academic leaders from North America, Europe
and Japan.
   Tass said without elaborating that Gorbachev and Kissinger on
Tuesday discussed ``some considerations on the development of
Soviet-American relations, which were set forth by Kissinger on
behalf of U.S. President-elect George Bush.''
   A senior official in Bush's transition office said in Washington
that Kissinger was not an emissary of the vice president but,
speaking on condition of anonymity, added: ``We expect him to pass
along greetings from the president-elect.''
   Kissinger, secretary of state under President Nixon, was a
foreign policy adviser to Bush during the presidential campaign.
   Kissinger and other participants in the Trilateral Commission
meeting were scheduled to meet with Gorbachev later today.
</TEXT>
