<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 0636EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-HospitalClosings     01-18 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hospital Closings,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Association Reports Record Number of Closings in 1988</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A record number of community hospitals closed for
the sixth year in a row last year, the American Hospital Association
said, promising to fight any further cuts in federal Medicare and
Medicaid funding.
   Eighty-one hospitals in 28 states shut down in 1988, the
organization said Tuesday. The Southwest was hardest hit, with 18
closings in Texas alone.
   In addition, 21 non-community hospitals closed in 15 states, the
association said.
   Community hospitals are generally defined as those not serving a
specific group like a university, military base or prison. They can
be publicly or privately owned. Non-community hospitals typically
provide rehabilitative or long-term care.
   The closings were primarily due to inadequate Medicare and
Medicaid payments for treatment of the elderly and poor, said
association President Carol McCarthy.
   ``Hospitals cannot lose money or barely break even year after
year and remain open,'' Ms. McCarthy said. ``It's just that simple.''
   She said the association would ``pull out all the stops'' to stop
cuts in Medicare and improve health care funding for America's
indigent.
   Since 1980, 445 community hospitals have closed, and the number
has increased steadily since 1982, the association said.
   Forty-three of the 81 community hospitals that closed in 1988
were rural.
   ``For the last several years, seven out of 10 rural hospitals and
50 percent of urban hospitals have lost money caring for patients,''
Ms. McCarthy said.
   For most hospitals, profit margins are disappearing, and they
cannot cut costs to stay open, said association vice president
Alexander Williams.
   ``The problem is not excess expenses,'' Williams said. ``The ones
that close have gone through draconian cost cutting measures. The
problem is one of revenue.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
