<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 0647EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Libya-Planes     01-18 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Libya-Planes,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Firm That Allegedly Helped Libyans Refit Warplanes Under Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUNICH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors said today that they have
begun a criminal investigation of a Bavarian firm that a news
magazine says helped Libya develop the ability for in-flight
refueling of warplanes.
   Munich Prosecutor Heinz Stocker said the Intec Technical Trade
and Logistic company was suspected of violating West Germany's
export laws.
   He said the probe was focusing on whether ``(fuel) tank equipment
sent to Libya required an export permit.''
   ``We don't know what was done with this equipment in Libya. That
is something that must be examined,'' Stocker told The Associated
Press in a telephone interview. He did not elaborate on the
equipment sent to Libya and said he could not give out other details.
   It was not immediately clear whether investigators were also
looking into a report by Der Spiegel magazine that Intec engineers
had helped refit Libyan warplanes so they can be refueled in
mid-flight.
   Prosecutors also did not say whether the investigation was at all
related to the involvement by West German companies in the
construction and outfitting of a suspected chemical weapons plant in
Libya.
   Der Spiegel reported this week that 10 Intec-hired engineers were
playing a key role in helping Libya fit warplanes and transport
planes with equipment necessary for in-flight refueling.
   ``In addition to the construction of its own chemical weapons
plant, Libya is re-equipping its air force with the goal of
increasing the operations radius of its bombers to as far away as
Jerusalem,'' it said.
   ``For over two years, the German technicians have been involved
in turning Hercules transport planes into flying gas stations'' for
Libya, Spiegel said.
   It alleged that Intec-hired engineers are also equipping Libyan
warplanes with the special devices needed for mid-air refueling.
   The Hamburg-based magazine said the work has been going on at a
``tightly guarded air base'' near Tripoli.
   Spiegel quoted an official with the Bavarian firm as denying the
company was guilty of any wrongdoing. Intec ``has nothing to do with
construction work on airplanes in Libya,'' the magazine quoted Ingo
Moehring as saying.
   Moehring is the son of Eberhard Moehring, identifed by Spiegel as
owner of the Bavarian firm. Ingo Moehring said the company last year
had only delivered ``metal, rivets and nuts'' to Libya, Spiegel
reported.
   Intec is based in Vatterstetten, which is located near Munich.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
