<DOCNO> AP890118-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 0651EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-AirlineInspections 1stLd-Writethru a0457 01-18 0748</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Airline Inspections, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0457,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>737 Tests Find Nothing, Two 757s Have Wiring Problems</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, bgng: ``But one...'' to add details; INSERTS
3 grafs after 6th graf pvs, bgng: ``Delta Air...'' to add details; picks
up 7th graf pvs, bgng: ``FAA orders...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven U.S. airlines that fly Boeing 737s
similar to the British Midland Airways airliner that crashed Jan. 8
in England say they found no wiring problems during inspections
ordered by the Federal Aviation Administration.
   But one airline conducting an unrelated inspection found other
wiring foulups in two larger Boeing 757 aircraft. FAA officials in
Seattle said they were concerned about an apparent delay in
reporting the problem in another case.
   Officials of America West, Continental, Delta, Piedmont,
Southwest, United and U.S. Air said Tuesday that all their 737-300s
had been checked and no cross-wiring or other problem was found in
engine warning systems.
   The 737 inspections resulted from speculation that crosed-wiring
might have misled the pilot of the British Midland jet to shut down
his good right engine after the left one caught fire. Officials have
yet to determine the cause of the crash, which killed 44 people, but
they say they found no evidence of a problem with the right engine
except that it had been shut down.
   American and Aloha airlines officials did not immediately respond
to inquiries about the testing, but FAA spokesman Bob Buckhorn said
it appeared there were no problems with any of the airlines covered
by the ``airworthiness directive.'' He said, however, the FAA had
not yet compiled all the reports from airlines.
   Delta Air Lines, responding to another FAA order covering fire
sprinkler systems in Boeing 757 cargo holds, said Tuesday it found
faulty wiring in two of its aircraft. That brings to seven the total
number of 757s found with such problems worldwide.
   One case of faulty wiring in a 757 was reported to Boeing in
August by Royal Brunei Airlines, but Boeing relayed the information
to the FAA only this month, Mitch Barker of the agency's Seattle
office told the Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
   ``Boeing is under an obligation to look into these types of
things and report them to the FAA,'' Barker said Tuesday. ``There's
some leeway in the process, but if there is a long delay that would
be a concern to us.''
   The reporting delay was a ``blip,'' said David Jiminez of Boeing.
``It was a breakdown in communication. Generally (both manufacturer
and carrier) report to the FAA, but in this case it just didn't
happen.''
   FAA orders cover only domestic airliners, but foreign carriers
using U.S. built aircraft generally comply with any safety
inspections ordered.
   ``We're looking to see what happened in the system to allow this
(faulty wiring) to happen, where it happened, how it happened, and
to see how we can make it not happen again,'' said Boeing spokesman
Tom Cole in Seattle.
   Cole said officials would not take any steps affecting production
of new 757s until they received the results of the inspections from
the FAA.
   The FAA orders covering 737s and 757s were not related, except
that they both involved cross-wiring.
   The cargo-hold problems have been reported in another
Delta-operated 757, one belonging to Royal Brunei Airlines, two
owned by Air Holland, and one operated by the British airline Air
2000. One of the Air Holland planes was being used by a charter
company in Canada.
   Officials of Eastern, which operates 25 of the 757s; Northwest,
which has 33; and America West, which has seven, said Tuesday that
they found no problems with any of their planes. No other U.S.
airline operates the 757.
   Jim Lundy, a Delta spokesman in Atlanta, said the carrier
immediately notified the FAA of the latest two cases and corrected
the problems which would have prevented sprinklers from working
properly in the event of a fire in a baggage hold.
   One airplane had a crossed-wiring problem that would have turned
on the wrong sprinklers if a fire had broken out, Lundy said. The
other had faulty wiring that would have warned the pilot of a fire
but would not have activated the sprinklers, he said.
   He said it was a similar crossed-wiring problem found on a Delta
plane before delivery from the Boeing factory that prompted the FAA
757 airworthiness directive last week.
   Airlines had until Tuesday morning to complete the inspections
and regular airline service was not affected, officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
