<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka-Crash 2ndLd-Writethru   01-18 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka-Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0510,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Relatives Rush To Hospitals Looking For Crash Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE death toll of 45, details. Picks
up 6th pvs, ```Bodies were ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of people rushed to hospitals
in southern Sri Lanka today, hoping to find that loved ones had
survived a train-bus collision in which at least 45 people were
killed, officials said.
   Most of the dead were schoolchildren.
   Police and witnesses to Tuesday's crash said the bus driver
apparently thought he could beat the express train, but his
vehicle's engine stalled on the unguarded crossing about 43 miles
south of Colombo.
   At a Cabinet meeting today, President Ranasinghe Premadasa
ordered all the country's 758 railway crossings to have gates
installed by Monday, said spokesman Festus Perera.
   Seventy-one of the 120 mostly young people on the bus were
injured, and six critically injured victims were taken to Colombo
today for emergency surgery, police said. No one on the train was
injured.
   The train, traveling at about 40 mph, knocked the bus about 150
feet down the track, witnesses said, and many bus passengers were
hurled into a field. Others, most of them aged 5 to 15, were trapped
inside the mangled vehicle.
   ``Bodies were all over ... Children were screaming,'' said a
Buddhist priest who helped carry the injured to ambulances.
   Many of the victims could not easily be identified, and nurses
asked relatives to check clothing for identification. At the crash
site, police searched through bloodstained school books, pencils and
shoes for clues to the victims' identities.
   ``We are working with badly mutilated bodies, some of them only
limbs,'' said one police officer.
   Relatives crowded into the two government-run hospitals where the
dead and injured were taken.
   One wailing mother walked through the hospital halls calling out,
``Inoka, Inoka.'' Nurses ran after her and stopped her from entering
the morgue.
   Hema Premadasa, the president's wife, visited the accident site
and hospitals this morning, going from bed to bed trying to comfort
the injured and console relatives of the dead.
   The bus had picked up children from four schools in Amblangoda
and was headed toward Urgasmanhandiya, about 10 miles away, when the
crash occurred.
   One witness said she tried to flag the bus down because she
thought the driver probably could not see the train because of a
light drizzle. But other witnesses and police said they thought the
driver saw the train and still tried to make it across the track,
especially since five children riding on the steps of the bus jumped
out and escaped injury.
   The bus driver suffered minor injuries, they said.
</TEXT>
