<DOCNO> AP890118-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 0743EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-East-WestTalks     01-18 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-East-West Talks,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czechoslovak Foreign Minister Rebuffs Western Criticism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Jaromir Johanes of
Czechoslovakia today dismissed harsh Western criticism of a police
crackdown on dissidents in Prague and said the demonstrators had
broken the law by assembling.
   ``Anyone in this hall who wants to point the finger at other
nations, including Czechoslovakia, should first of all look at
himself,'' Johanes said.
   ``Acts in breach of legal and public order cannot be tolerated by
any government,'' he said, departing from his prepared text. ``Laws
have to be observed by all.''
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze, meanwhile, said upon
arriving in Vienna that the Berlin Wall is not a subject for
negotiations at the conference in Vienna on human rights and
East-West relations.
   Shevardnadze, scheduled to address the final session of the
35-nation conference on Thursday, also told reporters there are
``many areas in which (East and West) just disagree'' on human
rights issues.
   Johanes spoke a day after police armed with truncheons broke up
crowds of protesters in Prague's Wenceslas Square for a third day,
chasing hundreds of youths with water cannons.
   On Sunday, police used tear gas, batons, dogs and water cannons
to break up 5,000 demonstrators gathered to remember Jan Palach, a
Czech student who killed himself in 1969 to protest the 1968
Soviet-led invasion of his homeland.
   On Monday, 14 prominent dissidents including banned playwright
Vaclav Havel were detained after they tried to lay flowers in
Palach's memory.
   Havel, Charter 77 spokespersons Dana Nemcova and Sasha Vondra and
the other 11 activists remained in detention today.
   In an interview with Austrian radio after his speech, Johanes
said: ``What is happening in Prague is not a violation of human
rights.''
   Asked what he meant by his comment that other countries should
look at their own rights records, Johanes cited as an example the
wave of arrests in Miami in the past two days following rioting by
blacks there.
   U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz and British Foreign
Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe strongly criticized the Czechoslovak
police action Tuesday, the first day of a three-day meeting of the
foreign ministers from the 35 nations to wrap up new accords on
human rights and security.
   Shultz said Czechoslovakia violated the new accords just one hour
after they were formally adopted Sunday by delegates who worked 27
months to draft them. Shultz, however, praised the Soviet Union,
Hungary and Poland for recent economic and political reforms.
   Polish Foreign Minister Tadeusz Olechowski, speaking after his
country's communist leaders set conditions for legalizing
Solidarity, pledged his country would fully adhere to the accords
reached in Vienna.
   ``I can assure you that Poland will scrupulously implement all
the obligations which she has assumed,'' Olechowski said.
   ``We shall review the existing legislation to see whether it is
consistent with these new recommendations and, where it is not, to
introduce the necessary amendments. We shall expect similar moves by
other states,'' he added.
   Johanes made no such pledge to review Czechoslovak laws, thus
emphasizing the gap that opened up at the Vienna conference between
reformist nations in the Soviet bloc and those more reluctant to
change.
   The accords call for new arms control talks between NATO and the
Warsaw Pact to reduce conventional arms across Europe. Those
negotiations are due to open in Vienna March 9.
   Johanes said the new talks ``will become an important practical
test of the political resolve to reach tangible progress'' toward
disarmament.
   Shevardnadze was asked by reporters if the recently concluded
agreement at the conference indicated the Berlin Wall could now be
dismantled.
   ``I don't think that the Berlin Wall is a subject for the Vienna
meeting,'' he said. ``Each state has the right to build its
frontiers as it wishes and we must proceeed from there.''
</TEXT>
