<FIRST>r a PM-Penn'sLanding     01-18 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Penn's Landing,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Developer Abandons $120 Million Waterfront Project</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A developer is abandoning his $120 million
Penn's Landing mall and office project along the Delaware River
about three months before its scheduled groundbreaking, calling it
``an expensive mistake.''
   Willard Rouse III, admitting ``deep regret and certainly
embarrassment,'' said Tuesday he had received construction and
marketing reports in the past three weeks showing rents in the first
stage of development wouldn't balance costs.
   The major problems were a nationwide slump in retailing and a
glut of office space in Philadelphia, he said.
   City officials were shocked by the announcement after three years
of negotiations and lengthy City Council hearings on the project on
the waterfront where William Penn and other English settlers landed
more than 350 years ago.
   ``We are very disappointed and surprised,'' said City Commerce
Director William P. Hankowsky. ``Things had been moving along very
well.''
   Plans called for a hotel and a parking garage in addition to
offices and stores. More buildings were contemplated in the next
decade for an additional $400 million investment.
   The city had pledged to provide up to $19.5 million in subsidies
for the project and to pay $2 million a year for maintenance as part
of a lease agreement on the city-owned tract. Rouse was to pay rent
of $100,000 a year plus a percentage of profits.
   Rouse had not signed the lease agreement, but had been expected
to do so by the end of this month, Hankowsky said.
   The developer said it was more prudent to quit now, even though
he already has spent $5 million on the project.
   ``It was an expensive mistake,'' he told a news conference at his
Rouse and Associates' 21st-floor headquarters at One Liberty Place,
the city's tallest building which he completed last year. ``It was a
terribly challenging project we wanted to do, and it will take a
while to get over it.''
   Groundbreaking was to begin before May 1.
   Asked the consequences for Philadelphia, Rouse replied, ``It
leaves the city with a great piece of dirt.''
   Hankowsky said city officials would re-evaluate the Penn's
Landing plan, and might negotiate with Rouse to build part of the
project or seek proposals from other developers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
