<FIRST>r a PM-PoliceSting     01-18 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Police Sting,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feds Investigate Civil Rights in Alleged Racism, Brutality Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI is investigating the conduct of a
white police officer who was secretly filmed as he rammed a black
man's head through a plate glass window.
   The Long Beach City Council on Tuesday also asked the Los Angeles
district attorney to investigate Saturday's incident, in which
NBC-TV filmed officer Mark Dickey shoving Don Jackson's head into
the store-front window.
   Jackson is a police sergeant in suburban Hawthorne on a leave
pending the outcome of his race-related stress disability lawsuit
against that city.
   Jackson said he and off-duty state corrections officer Jeffrey
Hill set up the self-styled ``sting'' with NBC-TV as part of an
investigation into racism.
   ``We are involved. We have opened a ticket on it into possible
civil rights violations,'' said FBI spokesman Fred Reagan.
   The tape showed Jackson getting out of a car after being stopped
by Long Beach officers. After a verbal exchange, an officer
searching for weapons then shoved Jackson's head through the window.
   ``We will not tolerate any type of racism or brutality,'' said
Mayor Ernie Kell. ``We need to find out what actually happened here
and, if we were at fault, make sure it never happens again. We must
get to the bottom of this.''
   Jackson's attorney, Tom Beck, said ``a lawsuit is inevitable.''
   Kell said ``it is critical'' that the city get NBC's complete
unedited tape, but NBC attorneys said only those segments that were
broadcast would be turned over. The mayor said the city would fight
to get the tapes.
   Mike Tracy, a Long Beach Police Officers Association board
member, agreed that the entire tape was needed.
   ``We're incensed. All we are seeing is what NBC wants us to
see,'' Tracy complained. ``We want to see a reverse angle. It could
have been the officer's body part that went through that window.''
   Dickey has asked to work in the police department's detective
bureau until the case is resolved, Tracy said.
</TEXT>
