<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Teamsters     01-18 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Teamsters,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Meets with Teamsters Leaders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush has met with Teamsters
union leaders, including six scheduled for trial on racketeering
charges, to thank them for their support in the election.
   The meeting was held Tuesday without announcement in the office
of John Sununu, chief of staff to the incoming president, according
to Sheila Tate, a spokeswoman for Bush.
   Confirming an account of the meeting in today's editions of The
Washington Post, Ms. Tate said: ``The Teamsters people were meeting
with Sununu and the president-elect simply stopped by briefly. The
purpose was to thank them for their support during the election
campaign.''
   The Teamsters have supported the Republicans in the last three
presidential elections, and Bush appeared at the union's board
meetings in the inaugural weeks in 1981 and in 1985 to express
thanks for the endorsements of the Reagan-Bush ticket.
   Many members reportedly opposed the 1988 endorsement because of
the Justice Department's success in winning the racketeering
indictment. The department is seeking a federal trusteeship for the
union in the trial scheduled to begin Feb. 27 in New York.
   The union's president, William McCarthy of Boston, was strongly
opposed to the Democratic candidate, Gov. Michael Dukakis of
Massachusetts.
   Defendants in the case are McCarthy and 17 other members of the
union's executive board.
   According to an unidentified aide quoted in the Post account,
Bush ``just stuck his head in the door'' in lieu of another public
appearance at a board meeting, during a session of Sununu and the
Teamsters leaders that lasted less than 20 minutes.
   Sununu told the gathering that any discussion of the racketeering
case or any other case ``would be inappropriate.''
</TEXT>
