<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 0931EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     01-18 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rival Lebanese Governments Agree To Arab League Talks On Crisis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of rival Christian and Moslem
cabinets have agreed to cooperate with the Arab League in a bid to
prevent the formal partition of Lebanon, officials reported today.
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, head of the Moslem cabinet,
said he will leave for Tunis later this month for talks with a
special committee of the 22-member league on ways of resolving a
4-month-old political crisis that threatens to cement Lebanon's
partition into sectarian cantons.
   ``We are prepared to cooperate with the Arab League committee,''
Hoss told The Associated Press. He said he will meet the committee
in Tunis on Jan. 28.
   The panel, headed by Kuwaiti Foreign Minister Sheik Sabah
al-Ahmed al-Sabah, was formed Thursday in Tunis at a meeting of Arab
foreign ministers. It also includes the foreign ministers of Sudan,
Tunisia, Algeria, Jordan and the United Arab Emirates and the
league's secretary-general, Chedli Klibi.
   Parliament Speaker Hussein Husseini, a Shiite Moslem, will also
meet the committee in Tunis later this month, his office announced.
   A political source in Christian east Beirut said army commander
Gen. Michel Aoun, who heads the Christian cabinet, also ``welcomed
the Arab League's interest in the Lebanese situation and expressed
readiness to cooperate with the committee.''
   The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Aoun ``would
decide on the level of his representation at a meeting with the
committee after he formally receives an invitation, which is
expected later this week.''
   Hoss, a Sunni Moslem, and Husseini were invited by Kuwaiti envoys
to meet the committee when the Lebanese officials visited the Syrian
capital of Damascus on Tuesday.
   The Kuwaiti diplomats, Abdel Mohsen al-Gaian and Ahmed ben
al-Jassem, were expected to visit east Beirut later this week to
deliver Sabah's invitation to Aoun, the independent An-Nahar daily
said.
   While they were in Damascus, Hoss and Husseini met Syria's vice
president, Abdul-Halim Khaddam, and discussed efforts by the
committee to resolve the Lebanese crisis and facilitate the election
of a new president to succeed Amin Gemayel, whose term expired Sept.
22.
   Parliamentary efforts to elect a successor failed when Christian
deputies opposed to Syrian-backed candidates boycotted the electoral
sessions.
   Minutes before he stepped down, Gemayel appointed Aoun head of an
interim military cabinet to rule Lebanon until a new president was
elected. Moslem leaders backed by Syria rejected Aoun's appoinment
and support Hoss' cabinet, the remnant of the long-fractured
government which served under Gemayel.
   An-Nahar said Khaddam told Hoss and Husseini that Syria supports
the Arab League's moves to find ``ways to end the Lebanese crisis.''
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, maintains about 40,000
troops in eastern and northern provinces as well as Moslem sectors
of Beirut.
</TEXT>
