<FIRST>r w PM-InauguralSecurity 1stLd-Writethru a0454 01-18 0784</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Inaugural Security, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0454,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tight Security Planned for Inauguration</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 13th graf, In past, to update with bulletproof shield being
installed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security for George Bush's inauguration as the
nation's 41st president will be tight, with all law enforcement
officers throughout the area on duty following cancellation of all
days off.
   The 150,000 invited guests at the Capitol swearing-in ceremonies
will be screened by metal detectors, even if they'll be sitting
hundreds of yards away at the edge of the Capitol lawn.
   This is the first time those guests on the lawn will be screened
so carefully, and Sen. Wendell Ford, D-Ky., chairman of the Joint
Congressional Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies, says he's upset
about the tightened regimen.
   ``Security is something that bothers me considerably,'' he said
at a news conference Tuesday. ``We're a free and open nation
insisting that those in the inner circle go through megadetectors.''
   Anyone going to any of the galas or anywhere else that the first
families might be will also be checked with the magnetometers.
   Demonstrations by those who want to see changes in the
administration's policies are planned throughout the ceremonies.
   A corner of Lafayette Park across from the White House has been
set aside ``to ensure First Amendment rights,'' in the words of Park
Police Capt. Michael Barrett. But other protests will be held across
the city.
   The Counter-Inaugural Coalition for a People's Agenda has
scheduled everything from a Union Station ``banquet'' _ a soup
kitchen _ to a ``No Honeymoon'' benefit concert for the Christic
Institute featuring David Crosby and Graham Nash at the Warner
Theater. The National Organization for Women plans to protest
silently all along the Pennsylvania Avenue parade route.
   The manholes along Pennsylvania Avenue already have been welded
shut, but many other details of the security measures remain secret.
   ``We certainly wouldn't want to give anyone who had harmful
intent any kind of advantage,'' said Secret Service spokesman Ken
Lynch.
   Reports on previous inaugurations have indicated that agents
carrying shoulder-fired Stinger missiles to protect against air
attack were on the Capitol roof. Will that be the case this year? No
comment, say all the agencies involved.
   Bob Buckhorn, a Federal Aviation Administration spokesman, noted
only that flying over the White House or the Capitol is a violation
of federal air regulations.
   In past inaugurals, bullet-proof panels have protected the new
president as he takes the oath of office and delivers his inaugural
address. Workers at the Capitol's West Front were installing a
bulletproof shield around the podium this week.
   Everybody willing to talk about it says Bush will ride in an
armored limousine as he travels from the Capitol to the White House
following the oath-taking. But then, that's what they said about
President Jimmy Carter before he and his wife, Rosalynn, climbed out
of their car and marched the 1{ miles down Pennsylvania Avenue in
January 1977.
   Jody Powell, Carter's press secretary, says Carter told him about
his plans the week before the inauguration, but the news was ``very
tightly held, for security purposes.''
   ``What he told me at the time was the deal was the Secret Service
wasn't going to fight it as long as it was kept secret, but if word
got out ahead of time, they'd be very opposed to it,'' Powell said.
   Secret Service spokesman Rich Adams says his agency will be
prepared to protect Bush if he decides to stroll down Pennsylvania
Avenue, but he admitted the service would not be too happy about it.
   ``If we had our way, he would not leave the White House,'' he
said.
   Law enforcement agencies involved in security for the inaugural
ceremonies include the Secret Service, Capitol Police, the local
police department, Metro transit police, Park Police, Federal
Protective Service and the District of Columbia National Guard. In
addition, private security guards have been arranged for various
parties.
   Approximately 8,500 military personnel will be involved in
inaugural duties, including bands and other units marching in the
parade, a cordon lining the parade route, and drivers for the first
families and governors.
   The Capitol will be closed to all unauthorized people starting at
5 p.m. Thursday, the day before the ceremony, Nichols said.
   On Inauguration Day, all streets within a two-block radius of the
Capitol will be closed. Even members of Congress and their staffs
won't be allowed to park on the lot on the building's east side.
   Security was in place a week in advance on the west side of the
Capitol where risers have been built for several hundred VIPs who
will sit behind Bush as he faces the mall to deliver his speech,
Nichols said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890118-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 0936EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Aeroflot-Food     01-18 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Aeroflot-Food,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Maryland Company To Supply In-Flight Meals for Aeroflot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHESDA, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frequent fliers might liken it to a
resumption of the cold war, but a U.S. company has signed a contract
to provide hot American airline food to passengers on the Soviet
Union's airline, Aeroflot.
   Officials of Aeroflot and the Marriott Corp., the world's largest
supplier of in-flight meals, announced Tuesday that they had formed
a joint venture to provide food service for Aeroflot, the world's
largest airline.
   The contract creates a new company, Aeromar Ltd., which is 51
percent owned by the Soviet Union and 49 percent owned by the
Marriott. The two said they will share profits and both will invest
capital, equipment and technical expertise.
   J.W. Marriott Jr., chairman and president of the Bethesda-based
hotel and restaurant company, said Marriott already caters Aeroflot
flights in New York, Washington, Paris, London and Manchester,
England.
   But the new agreement, covering both international and domestic
Aeroflot flights, will be the first contract food service operation
in the Soviet Union involving a Western company, he said.
   At a news conference at the Soviet Embassy in Washington,
Aeroflot director general Vladimir A. Nacharov said Aeroflot does
not presently serve meals on all its flights.
   Under terms of the agreement, formally signed in Moscow last
month, Marriott will participate in the renovation and modernization
of the flight kitchen at Moscow's Sheremetjevo Airport, the largest
airport in the Soviet Union.
   The project will cost about $5 million, Marriott said. He said
the company expects annual revenues of $15 million to $20 million
once the facility is fully operational.
   Airline food may not be the only thing Marriott is selling to the
Soviet Union. Marriott said the company will send a representative
to Moscow next week to evaluate the feasibility of a Moscow hotel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
