<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 0943EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Poland 2ndLd-Writethru a0474 01-18 0764</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0474,0784</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Complains About Conditions On Legalization Offer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to ADD confidence vote, Walesa to speak
Thursday. Pickup 10th graf pvs, ``The authorities...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist leaders passed a resolution early
today that could restore Solidarity's legal status, but officials of
the banned trade union movement said too many unacceptable
conditions appeared to be attached.
   Among conditions set before today's vote by the party's governing
Central Committee was that Solidarity declare itself in favor of
socialism, promise no strikes for two years and forfeit financial
assistance from the West.
   There was no immediate comment from Solidarity leader Lech
Walesa. An aide said he would hold a news conference Thursday.
   Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski said during debate Tuesday
he favored ending the seven-year ban on Solidarity if its leaders
promised not to drag the economically depressed country ``into
anarchy.''
   The official PAP news agency said today a majority of the
230-member Central Committee had approved the party leadership's
stand on trade union and political pluralism. Other details of the
proposal, debated 17 hours until 3 a.m., were not immediately
available.
   The vote occurred too late to be included in morning newspapers
and the text was not immediately carried by PAP.
   The Central Committee also gave an overwhelming vote of
confidence to top party authorities led by First Secretary Wojciech
Jaruzelski. PAP reported unanimous approval with four abstentions.
   A Solidarity source in Warsaw said Rakowski's proposal to
reinstate the only independent labor movement ever allowed in the
Soviet bloc appeared at first glance unclear, ``unacceptable'' or
even ``laughable.''
   The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Solidarity
could not function as a free trade union if forced to embrace an
ideology and stripped of the right to strike.
   Rakowski said the government needed assurances that a legally
functioning Solidarity would differ from the movement that used
general strike threats as a pressure tactic during its 16-month
heyday, which began in 1980. The organization was outlawed in 1982.
   Solidarity activists on Tuesday welcomed the shift in the party's
stance but said they must proceed with caution, because authorities
had acted out of necessity rather than good will.
   ``The authorities will do whatever that have to do to stay on
top. Let's wait and see what they have to say and read the fine
print carefully,'' said Maciej Jankowski, a Solidarity leader at
Warsaw University.
   Jaruzelski crushed Solidarity in a December 1981 military
crackdown, interning thousands of activists and banning the movement
the next year.
   After a series of spring and summer strikes demanding higher pay
and Solidarity's reinstatement, Jaruzelski agreed to resume contacts
with the movement. However, promised negotiations with the
opposition were repeatedly delayed over conditions set by both sides.
   Walesa has warned that the public mood is reaching the boiling
point because of rising prices and annoying consumer shortages.
   In the latest sign of tension, a strike for higher pay and
legalization of Solidarity on Tuesday shut down the 1,100-worker
Pabianice Fabric Works in the textile city of Lodz.
   Under the proposal Rakowski put to the Central Committee, final
legalization of Solidarity would follow a two-year probationary
period lasting until May 3, 1991, the 200th anniversary of the
adoption of a progressive constitution that Imperial Russia quickly
invalidated by force.
   ``We have to gain certainty that this Solidarity, which cannot be
a simple repetition of the old one, does not pull the country into
anarchy,'' Rakowski said.
   Rakowski addressed specific questions to Solidarity in his
speech, saying the answers would determine if the union could be a
partner, or whether it would remain a ``political opponent.''
   He asked what position Solidarity would take toward
anti-communist Polish groups like the Confederation for an
Independent Poland, and whether it would continue to take money from
the U.S. Congress and other foreign organizations.
   The U.S. government has granted Solidarity $1 million a year the
last two years, but Polish authorities have held up spending of half
of this. Total U.S. aid to Solidarity was estimated last year at $5
million by The New York Times.
   Solidarity does not deny receiving foreign help. Walesa said he
would take money from the Kremlin if he could use it to defend trade
union freedoms.
   Rakowski stressed that the economy would be the most important
factor for Poland during the next few years.
   ``It above all needs order and peace,'' he said. ``Even the best
administration methods and solutions will not meet our hopes if the
... economy becomes a field of political struggles.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
