<FIRST>r a PM-HonestBystanders     01-18 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Honest Bystanders,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Clumsy Robber Drops Loot, Passersby Return It To Bank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FONTANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As might have been expected, when a
bumbling bank robber dropped his loot on the street a crowd quickly
gathered to grab what was blowing in the wind.
   What might not have been expected was that the bystanders
returned almost all the money to the bank.
   ``I think it's wonderful when citizens are willing to step in and
help,'' police Sgt. Dan Castellini said of Tuesday's incident. ``I'm
not sure there's anything pleasant about a robbery ... but when you
see something positive happen, you can't help but have a smile on
your face.''
   All but $20 of the $2,900 taken from Redlands Federal Savings was
returned, Castellini said. He said the missing $20 bill probably
blew away before anyone could grab it.
   Police said the incident began at 9:48 a.m. when a man walked
into the bank and handed a teller a bag and a note demanding money.
   After receiving the filled bag, the man fled, but dropped the bag
almost as soon as he got outside. Rather than stop to retrieve it,
he kept on running, leaving the money to scatter in the wind.
   The robber escaped in the commotion, Castellini said.
</TEXT>
