<FIRST>r a PM-CruiseCrash     01-18 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cruise Crash,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>14 Hurt When Colorado River Tour Boat Hits Sand Bar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEEDLES, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Colorado River tour boat smashed into a
sand bar and flung passengers from their chairs onto the deck ``like
ballast,'' injuring 14 people, authorities said.
   Three of those injured in Tuesday's crash suffered broken bones
and cuts, said San Bernardino County sheriff's spokesman Jim Bryant.
The rest suffered shock or complained of chest pain, said sheriff's
Sgt. Dave Austin.
   They were taken to Needles Desert Community Hospital.
   ``The Lord was watching over them, I'll tell you,'' sheriff's
spokeswoman Nancy Wegner said of the boat's 44 passengers.
   The accident happened shortly before noon as the boat, piloted by
Lyle Browning, made its way along the river near Ski Beach during a
two-hour sightseeing cruise, authorities said.
   The 50-foot boat was on a tour that normally leaves the gambling
resort town of Laughlin, Nev., turns around under the London Bridge
in Lake Havasu City, Ariz., and returns to Laughlin.
   ``They got down there and were coming back. The water is low
now,'' Bryant said. ``The captain saw the sand and sped up the
vessel to lift the boat over the sand bar. But it didn't lift. It
was going a pretty good speed. The people on board in chairs got
tossed around like ballast.''
   The boat is owned by Laughlin River Tours Inc., said a company
official who refused to give her name or comment further.
</TEXT>
