<FIRST>r i PM-HamadiTrial     01-18 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hamadi Trial,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Psychiatrists: Confessed TWA Hijacker Mentally Competent for Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Psychiatric experts said today
that confessed hijacker Mohammed Ali Hamadi is mentally competent to
stand trial, despite head wounds he received during fighting in his
native Beirut.
   Hamadi is charged with air piracy and murder in the June 14, 1985
hijacking of a TWA jetliner in which U.S. Navy diver Robert Stethem
was slain. Hamadi admitted taking part in the hijacking but denied
killing Stethem.
   Following the seizure of the Athens-to-Rome flight, 39 Americans
were held hostage for 17 days.
   The Frankfurt court, acting on a defense request in November,
ordered psychiatric tests for Hamadi after it was revealed in court
testimony that he had received head wounds in fighting in Beirut,
where a civil war has raged for 13 years.
   Willi Schumacher and Hasso Sachs, professors of psychiatry at
Giessen University, 35 miles north of Frankfurt, testified today on
the results of their tests of Hamadi.
   Schumacher said Hamadi's mental processes ``are quick, coherent,
and concise.'' His head has some scars, but ``none of them is
sensitive to outside pressure,'' Schumacher said.
   He said the defendant's reflexes were normal and that Hamadi had
no coordination problems.
   ``Mr. Hamadi is in all respects mentally fit,'' Schumacher said.
   Sachs said he tested Hamadi for mental disturbances, intellectual
development and concentration. He described the defendant as
``orderly thinking, and stable.''
   ``He was friendly, courteous, cooperative, absolutely not
withdrawn,'' Sachs said.
   Sachs said his tests showed Hamadi was of average intelligence
and that ``cerebal damage could not be established, indicating a
fully healthy brain.''
   Following the psychiatrists' testimony, the defense asked that
Hamadi be given additional tests. Chief Judge Heiner Mueckenberger
did not immediately rule on the request.
   The trial, which began July 5, resumed this week after a break of
nearly one month.
   Hamadi has been kept in Frankfurt's Preungesheim prison since his
arrest at the city's airport Jan. 23, 1987. He was arrested after
being caught with liquid explosives in his luggage.
   The United States requested his extradition, but following the
kidnapping of two West Germans in Beirut, West Germany said he would
be tried here instead.
   Hamadi's brother, Abbas Hamadi, was sentenced by a Duesseldorf
court in April to 13 years in prison for his part in kidnapping the
West Germans, allegedly to win Mohammed's freedom.
   The two West Germans have since been freed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
