<FIRST>r a PM-Ten-YearMystery     01-18 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ten-Year Mystery,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Maryland Men Arrested in 1979 Deaths of Elderly Pair</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANCASTER, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After nearly 10 years of dead-ends, police
have arrested two men for killing an elderly sister and brother who
died of thirst and hunger after being left trussed in their home in
1979.
   John Arthur Askew, 51, of Princess Anne, Md., and Robert Paul
O'Neill, 40, of Finksburg, Md., have been charged with homicide in
the case, Lancaster County Assistant District Attorney John A.
Kenneff said Tuesday.
   The two suspects allegedly bound and gagged Mary and Horace Swarr
and robbed their home of an undetermined quantity of coins and
currency on or about Sept. 10, 1979.
   Someone _ apparently one of the robbers _ later called police and
reported that an elderly couple had been tied up and robbed at 442
E. Walnut St. The Swarrs lived at 432 W. Walnut St.
   Police found the trussed couple seven days later after a
newspaper carrier reported seeing a large number of newspapers on
the doorstep of the Swarr home.
   By the time they were discovered, Mary Swarr, 57, was dead. Her
81-year-old brother died the following day. According to criminal
complaints released Tuesday, both died of dehydration and
malnutrition.
   At a news conference Tuesday night, authorities said the
perplexing case was finally broken through a 1987 tip from Baltimore
County police that led to an extended investigation of the two
suspects, who were arrested Saturday.
   Two others suspects are under investigation in the case,
authorities said, but their identities were not released.
   Askew waived extradition Tuesday and should be returned to
Lancaster from Maryland within seven days, Kenneff said. O'Neill's
extradition hearing began Tuesday and was scheduled to today in
Carroll County, Md.
</TEXT>
