<FIRST>u i PM-Britain-Refugee 1stLd-Writethru   01-18 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Refugee, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0575,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sir Lankan Refugee Facing Deportation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 12th graf pvs, ``Mendis took...'' to ADD
details on tradition of sanctuary. Pickup 13th graf pvs, ``Mendis came...''
TRIMS.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police broke into a church early today
and dragged away a Sri Lankan who had taken refuge there and was
sleeping handcuffed to a radiator, his supporters said.
   Home Office Minister Timothy Renton said Viraj Mendis, 32, would
be sent back to Sri Lanka if he did not find another country to
accept him by Friday.
   Mendis says he faces persecution and possible death in his native
country because of his communist beliefs and support for the Tamil
minority. The British government and courts disagree.
   The Rev. John Methuen of the Church of the Ascension said police
arrived at his home about 7:30 a.m. and broke down the door leading
to the vestry where Mendis was staying with two supporters.
   Methuen said there was ``quite a lot'' of damage done to the
building.
   A Home Office spokesman confirmed that two immigration officers
and 50 police officers forced their way into the Church of England
premises in northern England.
   ``The door into the sacristy (or vestry) was a large wooden door
which was heavily bolted and barred,'' said Terry Platt, head of the
Immigration and Nationality section at the Home Office.
   ``They forced that door with special equipment which had the
result of doing some damage to the door and wall.''
   Ingrid Falat, a member of the church council, said Mendis was
``handcuffed to the radiator in the room ... they dragged him out by
his hands and feet.''
   Falat and other witnesses said the police used acetylene torches
to remove the handcuffs.
   Mendis has lost two immigration appeals, a High Court judicial
review and a Court of Appeal review of a deportation order issued in
December 1986.
   Last month, Britain's highest court, the Law Lords of the House
of Lords, also refused to hear his case.
   Mendis took refuge in the church Dec. 20, 1986, two days after
Home Secretary Douglas Hurd, the senior Cabinet minister responsible
for immigration, signed the deportation order against him for
``overstaying'' in Britain.
   Mendis was trying to revive the ancient right of sanctuary, which
dates back to the Old Testament and had a long tradition in Britain
until it was abolished by Parliament in 1623. The medieval sanctuary
at London's Westminster Abbey harbored so many people it was said to
resemble a small town.
   Mendis came to Britain in 1973 on a student visa to study at the
University of Manchester. He ran into financial difficulties after
two years, dropped out, went to work and joined a communist splinter
group.
   Mendis is a member of Sri Lanka's Sinhalese majority but has
actively supported the rights of the Tamil minority. Tamil rebels
are fighting for an independent homeland in Sri Lanka.
   ``The Sri Lankan government have, in the past, given assurances
that he is not wanted in Sri Lanka for any offense and is free to go
there without impediment,'' Renton said in a statement.
   ``We have always felt that the situation in Sri Lanka did not
justify the position that Mendis and his supporters were adopting.''
</TEXT>
