<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--Iran-Embargo     01-18 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Iran-Embargo,0168</SECOND>
<HEAD>West German Gets 5 Years Probation for Sending U.S. Aircraft Parts
to Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A West German businessman who pleaded guilty to
conspiring to export American aircraft navigational systems to Iran
in violation of a U.S. embargo has been sentenced to five years
probation.
   The sentence imposed Tuesday on Bernd Pleuger, former managing
director of Beechcraft Vertrieb Und Service Co. of Munich, was
recommended by Assistant U.S. Attorney Phil Halpern, who said
Plueger had a secondary role in the scheme.
   Plueger, 51, of Augsburg, West Germany, and Juergen Zimmermann,
37, one of the company's sales representatives, both pleaded guilty
to trying to bribe a U.S. official, an undercover Customs agent, and
conspiring to illegally export the radar systems. Zimmermann is to
be sentenced April 17.
   The radar systems are produced primarily by Teledyne Ryan
Electronics of San Diego for the U.S. military. Beechcraft Vertrieb
sells, services and distributes parts for Beechcraft Aircraft Corp.
of Wichita, Kan., and other manufacturers.
