<HEAD>Thieves Kill Armored Car Guard In Failed Robbery Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRESCIA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bandits shot and killed a security guard in
a botched attack on an armored car, police said today.
   Eight or nine masked gunmen fired a hail of machine-gun rounds to
stop the armored car Tuesday night at a railroad crossing near this
northern town, according to police.
   Antonio Bozzi, 37, a guard riding in the rear of the car, was
struck in the head and killed by at least one of the bullets, which
police said had probably been intended as warning shots.
   Two guards in the front got out of the car and the bandits
grabbed what police described as a ``modest'' amount of money. They
said the bandits fired their weapons at the back of the car in an
attempt to break open the back door, but they couldn't get the door
open and fled.
   The Italian news agency ANSA reported the gunmen were believed to
be those responsible for a Nov. 9 robbery in Bergamo, about 30 miles
away.
   In that attack, gunmen engaged in a shootout with guards before
fleeing with $425,000.
