<FIRST>r a PM-CocaineMothers     01-18 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cocaine Mothers,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Expectant Mother in Five Uses Cocaine, Study Shows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A study at a Boston hospital serving inner-city
residents found that nearly one in five expectant mothers used
cocaine, sparking concern among doctors who reported an increase in
addicted newborns.
   ``It's very alarming,'' said Dr. Barry Zuckerman of Boston City
Hospital. ``Cocaine is not only bad during pregnancy, but being a
cocaine abuser is not a great way for a child to be reared.''
   Zuckerman, of the hospital's Division of Development Behavioral
Pediatrics, conducted the study of 1,226 pregnant woman, most of
whom were from the inner city. The study found that 18 percent had
used cocaine at least once during pregnancy, the Boston Herald
reported today.
   Nearly a quarter of those who admitted using cocaine said they
took the drug three or more times a week.
   Zuckerman said he expects to complete the study in six months. He
is analyzing the data to determine the impact of cocaine use on
developing fetuses.
   ``We were actually studying the effects of marijuana during
pregnancy, but it became clear cocaine was used more frequently, so
we looked at the effects of cocaine,'' he said.
   A study released last summer by the National Association for
Perinatal Addiction Research and Education showed that at least 11
percent of women in 36 hospitals had used illegal drugs during
pregnancy. The hospitals were chosen to represent a range of
socio-economic levels among patients.
</TEXT>
