<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 1123EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-ReaganPardons 1stLd-Writethru a0448 01-18 0714</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Reagan Pardons, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0448,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan Pardons 10; More Pleas Pending</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 12 grafs with Hearst petition not before Reagan, editing
changes; picks up at pvs 7th graf, Patty Hearst</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said today the request of
newspaper heiress Patty Hearst Shaw for a pardon has not come to his
desk for attention, and an administration official cautioned against
expecting any ``too extraordinary'' pardons during Reagan's final
days in office.
   ``There are always pardons coming across my desk from the Justice
Department,'' Reagan told reporters.
   Asked specifically about Mrs. Shaw, convicted for her role in a
San Francisco bank robbery 14 years ago, the president said, ``No,
that hasn't come to my desk for attention yet.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said, ``There are pardons
that are in the system, but I don't have any status report on
whether or not he has had a chance to review them.''
   A senior official, speaking on condition he not be identified,
said Reagan has pardoned 10 people in the last few weeks through the
normal process, in which they are announced by the courts rather
than the White House.
   ``My private guidance is not to expect anything too extraordinary
here in the form of pardons,'' the official said. He added, however,
that Reagan has not made final decisions and ``I can never preempt
the president.''
   The official said former national security aide Oliver L. North,
Mrs. Shaw and industrialist Armand Hammer were in the category of
potential pardon recipients he had in mind as ``extraordinary.''
   With time running out on his two-term presidency, Reagan has ``as
many as a couple of dozen'' requests still pending, said the source
who declined to be publicly identified.
   Mrs. Shaw, 34, said earlier this week that she did not know if
Reagan's expression of interest in her case means she stands a good
chance of being pardoned.
   Reagan has been reluctant to discuss the subject of pardons,
although he did tell reporters Sunday that ``I have asked everybody
to look into'' the Shaw case. He has repeatedly said he plans no
pardon for North, who faces a trial on an array of charges related
to the Iran-Contra affair.
   The administration source would not divulge the names of the 10
pardon requests that Reagan reviewed and referred back to the
Justice Department. ``There are no big names,'' he said.
   Spokesman Fitzwater had told reporters Tuesday, ``It's certainly
possible that a decision could be made (on Shaw) before he leaves.''
   Patty Hearst was sentenced to seven years in a federal prison for
her role in the 1974 armed robbery of a San Francisco bank. She now
is married and living in Connecticut with her husband and two
daughters under the married name of Patty Hearst Shaw.
   Shaw, granddaughter of newspaper tycoon William Randolph Hearst,
last August quietly asked for a pardon for her role in the robbery.
She has maintained she was brainwashed by the radical Symbionese
Liberation Army, a group of revolutionaries who kidnapped her in
Berkeley, Calif., in February 1974 and orchestrated the bank heist.
   Her seven-year sentence was commuted by President Carter and she
was released from prison on Feb. 1, 1979, after serving 23 months.
   In an interview Monday with The Advocate of Stamford at her
Westport, Conn., home, Shaw said, ``It's a little premature for
anything like that. If he (Reagan) doesn't approve it, it would go
to the next administration.''
   Attention also is being given to a longstanding pardon request by
Hammer, the Los Angeles industrialist and head of Occidental
Petroleum Corp. He was fined $3,000 and placed on a year's probation
in connection with his guilty plea to three misdemeanor charges in
connection with the Watergate scandal of the early 1970s.
   Fitzwater said that he would not ``comment on any individuals
that are in this category. Some of them are recent. Some of them,
we've had for weeks or for months.''
   The administration official who spoke on the condition of
anonymity said that the pardon approvals ``tend to trickle over. ...
We got 10 back from the White House, approved, last week.''
   Under routine procedure, the Justice Department's pardons office
would contact the person receiving a pardon or that person's
attorney, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
