<FIRST>r a PM-GynecologistHearing     01-18 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gynecologist Hearing,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gynecologist Offers to Give Up Medical Certificate, Attorney Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gynecologist who faces charges from the
State Medical Board for allegedly performing unnecessary surgery on
women has offered to surrender his certificate to practice medicine,
his attorney said.
   Attorney Earl Moore said Tuesday that he and Dr. James C. Burt
made the offer while meeting with state officials in Columbus.
   The board has charged Burt, a 67-year-old Dayton doctor, with
gross immorality for 41 alleged violations ranging from
overprescribing drugs to performing unnecessary surgeries.
   Most of the charges against Burt have to do with his
self-described ``love surgery,'' in which he rebuilt women's genital
areas, allegedly to enhance their sexual responsiveness. The
surgery, however, caused sexual dysfunction, emotional distress,
infection, chronic pain, incontinence and the need for corrective
surgery in many patients, the board charged.
   Burt sent a letter to the board last month denying the charges
and requesting a hearing. The board tentatively set a Jan. 30
hearing date.
   But Moore said Tuesday his client ``offered to surrender the
license and dispense with the hearing. Whether they do that or not,
I don't know. Otherwise, we'll go ahead with the hearing.''
   He said Burt has, in effect, retired anyway. ``He's not
practicing any medicine at all,'' Moore said.
   State Medical Board spokeswoman Lauren Lubow did not immediately
return telephone calls for comment today. Calls to Burt's office
went unanswered today.
   Ms. Lubow has said the severest penalty the state board could
impose would be permanent revocation of Burt's license. The board
limited the doctor to non-surgical medical practice in November.
   At least three of Burt's former patients have each filed $3
million medical malpractice suits against the gynecologist.
   Burt has denied performing the surgery without his patients'
permission.
</TEXT>
