<FIRST>r a PM-LiftExams     01-18 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lift Exams,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ski Resorts Ordered to Inspect Lifts After Cracks Are Discovered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State officials have ordered nine ski resorts to
immediately inspect ski lifts after cracks were found in a chairlift.
   In an emergency session Tuesday, the Colorado Passenger Tramway
Safety Board gave the resorts one week to test up to 47 lifts for
cracks in a metal brace on chairs. The lifts will not have to be
dismantled and can be used in the meantime.
   Fractures were found in four chairs at Loveland Basin during
routine maintenance Saturday. The lift was immediately shut down.
Tramway board engineer John Carrick said the cracks resulted from
metal fatigue.
   ``You try to decide how excited to get about something like
this,'' he said. ``Faced with four broken chairs, I'm moderately
excited.''
   The chairs bear the trademark Yan and were designed by Lift
Engineering and Manufacturing of Nevada.
   ``It's not as if the chairs were on the verge of falling off,''
said Ken Abrahamson, mountain manager at Loveland. ``They weren't
dangling by a thread.''
   Ken Pearson, plant manager at Lift Engineering, said the company
is trying to find ways to reinforce the connection. ``We are asking
other ski areas if they too have this problem,'' he said. ``There
have been no real incidents.''
</TEXT>
