<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   01-18 0946</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0995</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers throughout
the nation.
   Jan. 12
   The Evening Journal, Martinsburg, W.Va., on the federal budget:
   Federal budget-making is the complex and often painful process of
sorting out national priorities. ...
   This year, to compound the difficulties inherent in this task,
these choices are now being made by two groups _ President Reagan's
departing band of officeholders and President-elect Bush's incoming
group of government managers. Like all new presidents, Bush must
live for a while with the budget he inherits from the departing
incumbent. ...
   Although the Bush transition team is working closely with the
Reagan administration on the fiscal 1990 budget, undoubtedly the new
president will want to establish his own priorities as soon as
possible. There well may be two budgets this year.
   Of course, what Congress finally comes up with in the way of
government spending generally bears little relationship to the
fiscal proposals coming from the White House and all the budgets
could wind up being exercises in futility.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 13
   Scottsdale (Ariz.) Progress on the Supreme Court and abortion:
   The forces against abortion are elated. They smell victory in the
fight to overturn the 1973 decision which legalized abortion
nationwide, Roe vs. Wade.
   The cause of this elation is the Supreme Court's decision to
review Missouri's law regulating public financing of and
participation in abortions.
   The Missouri law prohibits abortions being performed in public
hospitals, requires viability tests for fetuses beyond the 19th week
and defines life as beginning at conception.
   The 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals struck down all of these
provisions.
   Abortion opponents hope the Supreme Court will uphold at least
one of these points and be unable to reconcile it to Roe vs. Wade.
...
   No Supreme Court action, though, is going to stop abortion. It
will only move it back to the horrors of those back alleys.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 14
   Starkville (Miss.) Daily News on the death of Emperor Hirihito:
   Many Americans old enough to remember the events of World War II
have mixed feelings about Japanese Emperor Hirohito. ...
   During the war, Hirohito images were everywhere in the United
States as symbols of Japanese aggression and cruelty.
   But, historians have now told us that the emperor, who had no
constitutional powers, fought privately to keep the country out of
war with America. He lost out to the warloards who ran the military.
...
   Japan has become one of our strongest allies, and it's partly
because this country, even while conquering the Japanese, recognized
how important the emperor was to them.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 13
   The Salina (Kan.) Journal on banning chemical weapons:
   An international pledge to avoid using chemical weapons is a
small step toward greater safety for the people of the entire world.
But much more will need to be done to make that security solid. ...
   The threat will not be removed by a pledge not to use the
weapons. What must be stopped are all aspects of chemical weapons
production and storage _ especially export of technology and raw
materials from industrial nations to Third World countries.
   President-elect George Bush has said he will make ending chemical
weapons a priority of his administration. The challenge will be to
enlist support of other nations in doing so.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 17
   The Flint (Mich.) Journal on federal pay increases:
   Every now and then, we wish history would repeat itself. Case in
point: On Jan. 20, 115 years ago, Congress repealed the ``Salary
Grab'' Act of 1873. That act had increased members' salaries by 50
percent. It had to be repealed because of public outrage.
   Today, Congress is quietly on the verge of allowing itself
another 50 percent pay increase that will add $128 million to a
federal budget already bloody with red ink _ this for men and women
who already earn more than 98 percent of our country's workers.
   We've heard some moaning and grumbling. But is the public
outraged enough to demand Congress to put an end to this blatant
salary grab?
   Our ancestors taught us we don't have to put up with such
shameless antics. They did something. Will we?
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 17
   The Miami Herald on William Bennett as drug czar:
   What did Congress intend when it created the Cabinet-level
position of Director of the Office of National Drug Control Policy?
   Many members and non-political drug experts had hoped for an
experienced team builder who could bring law enforcement and the
military together with business leaders, educators, rehabilitation
experts and public health authorities to forge a coherent attack on
both the supply and the demand side of the drug problem.
   Instead of such a leader, however, (President-elect) Bush has
designated the fiery former Education Secretary, William J. Bennett.
...
   Bennett made his reputation as a rhetorical flame-thrower. ...
   To win Senate approval and to succeed as the nation's first drug
czar, then, Bennett first must learn to listen instead of preach.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 17
   The Kansas City (Mo.) Times on William Bennett as drug czar:
   Under William J. Bennett, America's drug war will get attention.
The blunt and pugnacious former secretary of education couldn't ride
out a post if he wanted to; and he's already thundered about the
need for tougher action on drugs. ...
   For all Bennett's uncompromising words, no dramatic change in
public education occurred under his leadership. ...
   In many areas, the job of remedial education has been turned over
to the colleges, a task suffocating higher education.
   Let us hope Bennett learned from his failings in the Department
of Education. The country needs answers and action on addiction.
</TEXT>
