<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 1151EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   01-18 0804</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0841</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: American family.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 15
   El Paso (Texas) Times on trends in smoking habits:
   It's been 25 years since former Surgeon General Luther Terry
first told Americans that smoking was bad for their health.
   Since then, the percentage of smokers has declined, particularly
among men and the better educated.
   What does this tell us?
   First that the vast efforts to educate the U.S. public about the
dangers of smoking has helped. In particular, Surgeon General C.
Everett Koop has waged a battle against smoking. ...
   But the second development, one that Koop also supports, is that
smoking simply isn't ``in'' anymore. It is social pressure that has
stopped some people smoking and has kept some from starting.
   As Koop said to The Associated Press: ``This is not a prohibitive
society. We're not going to tell people they can't smoke. We learned
that we can't tell people they can't drink.''
   Yet programs such as Mothers Against Drunk Drivers have helped
alleviate that serious problem. So has Koop's educational battle
against smoking.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 16
   The Albuquerque (N.M.) Tribune on insurance for bank and thrift
deposits:
   In its final report, President Reagan's Council of Economic
Advisers made an interesting recommendation: lower the ceiling on
federally insured deposits in banks and thrift institutions.
   Deposit insurance is a Depression-era idea that once made sense.
It discouraged runs on banks and gave small savers a safe place for
their money. Recently, however, it contributed to a national crap
shoot that may cost the public $100 billion.
   In 1980, Congress unwisely raised the insurance limit to $100,000
from $40,000. Thus a device designed to protect mom and pop
depositors became a no-lose game for the wealthy, who could put a
no-risk $100,000 in one bank _ or $1 million in 10 banks.
   Because of go-go banking, money brokers, lax regulation and
deposit insurance, the taxpayers are about to take a huge hit to
rescue the thrift industry. The way to protect themselves from a
future hit is to stop guaranteeing other people's unwise investments.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 11
   The News Tribune, Woodbridge, N.J., on federal pollution controls:
   Because all four air-quality regions of the state have
unacceptable levels of ozone, the federal government forced the
state to require major gas stations to install pump nozzles designed
to retrieve gasoline vapors.
   There is a better way. If Congress acknowledged that controlling
air pollution is indeed a national task, it would require automobile
manufacturers to equip new cars with special canisters that would
provide the same result. Vapors would be directed toward the
gasoline tank through a system that would cost an estimated $15 to
$35 per car.
   Under the present rules, only areas that fail ozone tests _ such
as Los Angeles, Washington, D.C., Long Island and New Jersey _ are
forced to act. But hydrocarbons let loose in wide-open Wyoming and
rural Pennsylvania are just as unhealthy ... and all contribute to
the so-called ``greenhouse'' effect.
   By not acting on a national level, Congress is bowing to its
friends in the automobile business while giving a
less-than-sufficient response to ozone pollution.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 16
   Argus Leader, Sioux Falls, S.D., on the Martin Luther King
holiday:
   South Dakota is one of only six states that does not observe the
(Martin Luther King Jr.) holiday. ...
   Gov. George Mickelson and the South Dakota Legislature should, at
the least, declare the third Monday in January a working holiday in
King's honor.
   A regular holiday would be even more fitting. ...
   King deserves a holiday. He spoke for freedom and justice for all
Americans. He championed the cause of peaceful protest and won a
Nobel Prize for leadership in blacks' fight for racial equality. ...
   South Dakota could and should help restore King's dream by
recognizing the holiday in his honor.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 13
   Wisconsin State Journal, Madison, Wis., on schools and balloon
launchings:
   The state Department of Public Instruction is letting the air out
of a common classroom project _ balloon launches.
   While perhaps not ranking on the scale of deforestation, offshore
oil spills and disposable diapers as a source of enviromental harm,
DPI is warning teachers and students that helium-filled latex and
Mylar balloons can have a disastrous effect on wildlife.
   In 1985, a young sperm whale munching on a school of squid
accidentally swallowed a deflated Mylar balloon. The balloon blocked
the whale's intestines and it contracted food poisoning.
   Dead and dying hawksbill sea turtles and loggerhead turtles, both
endangered species, have been found with latex balloons in their
intestines.
   Balloons are wondrous playthings, but massive balloon launches
are wasteful and destructive. Teachers would not approve of dumping
30 message-filled bottles in a stream just to see where they go;
neither should they encourage students to loose message-filled
balloons into the air.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Editorial Rdp</NOTE>
