<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--AthensSmog     01-18 0138</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Athens Smog,0141</SECOND>
<HEAD>Smog Levels High Despite Anti-Pollution Measures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmental groups warned people to stay
indoors Wednesday because of dangerous smog levels, but government
officials said there was no need for concern.
   ``There is no reason to worry. We are watching the pollution
levels and we will inform the public responsibly if there is a
problem,'' Deputy Environment Minister Giorgos Ktenas said.
   The state-run Program for Pollution Control said smog readings
were ``moderately'' above dangerous levels.
   The Panhellenic Center for Ecological Studies, a private
monitoring group, disputed that and said 386 people were
hospitalized with smog-related breathing and cardiac problems.
   Smog has become a major problem in Athens, home to almost
one-third of Greece's population of 9.8 million. Cars, diesel taxis
and the city's aging buses are blamed for most of the pollution.
</TEXT>
