<FIRST>u w AM-PackingUp Bjt   01-18 0879</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Packing Up, Bjt,880</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Old Reagan Gang Leaves Town</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Don Hodel is going skiing. Ann McLaughlin is
going back to school. George Shultz is going to have to get a
driver's license.
   As Ronald Reagan's presidency comes to an end, so do the heady
times atop Washington's power structure for many members of his
Cabinet and other ranking officials of the administration.
   Some are staying on with President-elect Bush, including
Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos, Treasury Secretary Nicholas
Brady, and administration veteran James Baker III, who will be the
new secretary of state.
   But for some of the others, January has meant packing boxes,
selling homes and deciding what to do next. In some cases, what's
next may be a fat salary and a job with a big law firm or
corporation. Or it may mean taking it easy.
   Secretary of State George Shultz and his wife Helena have sold
their house in Bethesda, Md., and booked a commercial flight back
home to California on Inauguration Day.
   Shultz plans to write his memoirs and consider what else to do.
He has a standing offer to return to teaching at Stanford
University, but he appears to have left behind the corporate world,
where he earned $1 million a year as an executive of Bechtel Corp.
   But first things first. After 6{ years of being chauffeured and
accompanied by security agents, and not driving a car once, Shultz
plans to take the California driver's test to obtain a new license.
   He will keep a bodyguard for at least a month after leaving
Washington.
   Housing and Urban Development Secretary Samuel R. Pierce Jr., the
only member of Reagan's original Cabinet to last all eight years,
plans to return to New York, where he has kept a home two blocks off
Central Park. At age 66, he'll return to practicing law, although he
says he may not return to the firm he left in 1981.
   ``I've been in Washington three times,'' Pierce said. ``I served
under three separate presidents. And each time I always do the same
thing _ I go back to New York and practice law and join a bunch of
boards of companies.''
   Donald P. Hodel, secretary of interior, is going to think about
what to do next while spending the remainder of the winter skiing in
Colorado.
   ``I'm going to have to get serious about earning a living,''
Hodel said. ``And I really at this point don't have any idea.''
   He's sold his Washington home and has bought one west of Denver.
He's also bought a season ski pass for four big ski areas there.
   ``I think I'll make a better decision about what I should do and
what I should be in the future after a little of that,'' he said.
   Ann D. McLaughlin, secretary of labor for little more than a
year, will resume studies at the Wharton School of Business, where
she was studying when Reagan asked her to join the Cabinet. She had
worked at the treasury and interior departments earlier in the
administration.
   Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng says he'll sleep in on the
day after the inauguration _ and maybe the next day, too.
   ``I intend to take it easier,'' he said. ``I've reached that age
(70) when I don't have to worry about justifying myself every day,
so I'm not going to worry about that.''
   He came to Washington from California 20 years ago when Richard
Nixon named him an assistant secretary of agriculture. He plans to
remain, but is considering buying a second home in California.
   Health and Human Services Secretary Otis R. Bowen, also 70, has
put his condominium on the market. He plans to retire to rural
Indiana, where he was a doctor, and spend his time reading, writing
and tending to his five acres.
   His first priority is getting tomato seedlings going in his
greenhouse in time for spring transplanting. He's bought a riding
lawnmower and recently installed a hot tub in the greenhouse, for
relaxing after all that work.
   Energy Secretary John Herrington plans to return to San Francisco
and his real estate investments. He's considering job prospects, and
he seems to be in a hurry to get started. He's booked on a plane out
Thursday night, the evening before Inauguration Day.
   Commerce Secretary C. William Verity, 71, who has been in the job
just 14 months, will return to his home in Beaufort, S.C. His
agenda: fishing, hunting, golf, tennis and sailing.
   Frank Carclucci, the Defense Department secretary, says he'd like
to find a job outside government and remain in Washington.
   ``I've given thought to it but I haven't decided anything,'' he
said. ``It's a little hard from this perch to look around for jobs.
Every time somebody calls me on the phone, I have to disqualify
myself.''
   Charles Z. Wick, head of the U.S. Information Agency and a close
friend of the Reagans, will return to Los Angeles with his wife Mary
Jane.
   Wick, a former band leader whose name originally was Zwick, plans
to resume doing what he was doing before Reagan's election _
arranging financing for movies and other show business deals. A son,
Douglas Wick, produced the hit movie ``Working Girl.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
