<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 1241EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-WaterFilter     01-18 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Water Filter,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chicago Company Signs Consent Decree on Water-Filter Ads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chicago company has agreed not to contend in
ads that its water treatment system removes certain chemicals unless
it can back up what it says, the Federal Trade Commission said
Wednesday.
   The company, Associated Mills Inc., signed a proposed consent
decree that also requires it not to claim without substantiation
that the membrane cartridge of its Pollenex Bottled Water Maker
Reverse Osmosis System can last a year without replacement.
   The commission's complaint said the company had contended in
advertising that its system removed ``up to 99 percent of organic
chemicals and other contaminants from tap water,'' and nearly all or
most of the family of chemicals called trihalomethanes, which can be
produced by chlorination.
   However, the company had no basis for that claim, the FTC said.
   Under the decree, Associated must have a ``reasonable basis'' for
any claims of performance or longevity of its water treatment
products.
   By signing the decree, Associated neither admitted nor denied
guilt. However, it will make itself liable for a fine of $10,000 if
it should be found to have violated any terms in the future, if the
decree is adopted.
   The commission will receive public comment on the decree until
March 20, after which it will decide whether to adopt it.
</TEXT>
