<FIRST>d i AM-BRF--BeeperBear     01-18 0133</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Beeper Bear,0136</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teddy Bear Blamed for False Alarm at School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CASTLEGAR, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security guards, baffled for
eight days by false alarms at Twin Rivers Elementary School, have
found the culprit: a teddy bear.
   Principal Paul Phipps said the mystery was solved when a
maintenance worker smacked his hand down on a ladder in frustration.
The teddy bear replied with a beep.
   The bear, a learning tool for special needs children, responds
with a beep to touch, movement or sound, Phipps said.
   Someone had left the bear on a heat register. Every time the
hot-water heater clanked at night, the bear beeped, triggering a
silent alarm repeatedly over the winter holidays.
   ``All we had to do was move the toy,'' Phipps said. ``The bear's
been behaving himself ever since.''
</TEXT>
