<FIRST>r w AM-FactoryUse     01-18 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Factory Use,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Factory Use Inches to Nine-Year High in December</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. industry operated at its highest rate in
nine years last month, the government reported Wednesday, but
analysts said the modest pace of growth should allay fears of
increasing inflation.
   Use of industrial capacity at factories, mines and utilities rose
0.1 percentage point to 84.2 percent last month, the highest rate
since it hit 84.3 percent in November 1979, the Federal Reserve
said. The operating rate for November 1988 was a revised 84.1
percent, and October's figure was 84.0 percent.
   In an accompanying report, the agency said industrial production
climbed a moderate 0.3 percent in December following a revised
increase of 0.4 percent in November.
   While high operating rates can cause concern that factories will
have trouble meeting demand, resulting in shortages and higher
prices, economists said December's increases were small enough that
they didn't point to higher inflation.
   Lawrence Chimerine of the WEFA Group, consultants in Bala Cynwyd,
Pa., said the reports were ``consistent with continued recovery in
the industrial sector and moderate growth in the economy as a
whole.''
   ``It's probably the best of both worlds,'' he said. ``It showed
continued expansion but at a moderate pace.''
   Robert Brusca of Nikko Securities Co. International Inc. in New
York said that while operating rates were high, the specter of
inflation ``doesn't seem to be as much on our doorstep as some
people have pretended.''
   On the other hand, Brusca expressed concern that production ``is
not increasing fast enough to satisfy domestic demand and to make
progress'' on the U.S. trade deficit, which widened to $12.5 billion
in November.
   At manufacturing plants, the operating rate climbed to 84.4
percent last month from 84.3 percent in October. The operating rate
for durable goods _ ``big ticket'' items expected to last at least
three years _ rose by 0.1 percentage point to 83.0 percent, while
the rate for non-durable goods fell by a like margin to 86.4 percent.
   Industries with especially strong operating rates over the past
two years include primary metals, chemicals, fabricated metal
products, non-electrical machinery, autos and automotive parts.
   Capacity utilization for manufacturers of motor vehicles and
parts rose for the fifth straight month to 88.1 percent, up from
85.5 percent in November.
   The December operating rate at utilities was 81.9 percent, up
from 81.3 percent a month earlier. In the mining, which includes oil
and gas drilling, the operating rate was up 0.1 percentage point to
83.3 percent.
   The Federal Reserve's industrial production index now stands at
140.2 percent of its 1977 base, reflecting sharp gains in auto
production and continued strength in production of construction
supplies.
   The index has not declined since September 1987, reflecting an
export-driven manufacturing boom accompanied by a surge in spending
for capital equipment to expand and modernize factories.
   Production in manufacturing rose 0.3 percent in December
following a revised increase at the same rate for the month earlier.
Automobiles were assembled at an annual rate of 7.9 million units,
up from 7.6 million in November. Production of light trucks also
rose.
   Output at mines was unchanged in December after a 1.4 percent
rise a month earlier. Production at utilities was up 0.8 percent
from November.
   Total output at factories, mines and utilities was up 4.7 percent
from a year earlier.
</TEXT>
