<FIRST>r a AM-Kunkle-Espionage     01-18 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kunkle-Espionage,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spy Suspect Pleads Innocent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Navy technician pleaded innocent
Wednesday to charges he tried to sell anti-submarine warfare secrets
to the Soviets.
   U.S. District Judge Robert G. Doumar set an April 3 trial for
Craig D. Kunkle, 39, of Virginia Beach, who was arrested and charged
with espionage Jan. 10 in an FBI sting.
   Kunkle said he wanted to become a Soviet spy for the money and to
get back at the Navy, which discharged him for indecent exposure in
1985, the FBI said.
   The former chief petty officer is confident he will be
exonerated, and ``his spirits are good,'' defense attorney James C.
Lewis said after the arraignment.
   ``There are two sides to every story. All you've heard so far is
what the government claims occurred in this case,'' he said.
   Kunkle, a hospital security guard, was arrested in Williamsburg
by two FBI agents posing as Soviet officials.
   As a hidden camera recorded the meeting, Kunkle revealed secret
information that he recalled from his job as an anti-submarine
warfare instructor four years ago, the FBI said. Kunkle was paid
$5,000 for the information, the FBI said.
   Lewis said no classified information reached the Soviet Union.
   Kunkle remained jailed without bail. An FBI agent last week
testified that Kunkle called himself smarter and more professional
than former Navy man John A. Walker Jr., who was sentenced to life
in prison in 1986 for running a Soviet spy ring for 17 years.
   Trial preparations are expected to be complicated because
classified information is involved and court personnel must receive
security clearances.
   Lewis said the defense could be helped by the government's
reluctance to reveal classified materials in court.
   ``There is a disincentive for the government to reveal
information and it can work to your advantage,'' he said. ``Whether
it will in this case remains to be seen.''
</TEXT>
