<FIRST>r w AM-Reagan-Pardons     01-18 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan-Pardons,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Shaw Pardon Case Has Not Reached His Desk</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Wednesday that Patricia
Hearst Shaw's pardon request ``hasn't come to my desk for attention
yet'' as a senior official said he did not expect Reagan to grant
``too extraordinary'' pardons before he leaves office Friday.
   The president, during a picture-taking session with members of
Congress who were given presidential citizens medals, was asked
whether he was going to grant Mrs. Shaw's plea.
   ``There are always pardons coming across my desk from the Justice
Department,'' he said. Asked specifically about Mrs. Shaw, convicted
for her role in a San Francisco bank robbery 14 years ago, Reagan
replied, ``No, that hasn't come to my desk for attention yet.''
   The president on Sunday, however, told reporters he had asked
aides ``to look into'' Mrs. Shaw's case.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said, ``There are pardons
that are in the system, but I don't have any status report on
whether or not he has had a chance to review them.''
   A senior official, speaking on condition he not be identified,
said Reagan has pardoned 10 people in the last few weeks through the
normal process, in which the pardons are announced by the courts
rather than by the White House.
   ``My private guidance is not to expect anything too extraordinary
here in the form of pardons,'' the official said. He added, however,
that Reagan has not made final decisions.
   The official said former national security aide Oliver L. North,
Mrs. Shaw and industrialist Armand Hammer were in the category of
potential pardon recipients he had in mind as ``extraordinary.''
   With time running out on his two-term presidency, Reagan has ``as
many as a couple of dozen'' requests still pending, said another
source, who also declined to be named.
   Mrs. Shaw, 34, said earlier this week that she did not know
whether Reagan would grant her a pardon.
   Administration officials would not divulge the names of the 10
pardon requests that Reagan reviewed and sent back to the Justice
Department. ``There are no big names,'' one official said.
   Patty Hearst was sentenced to seven years in a federal prison for
her role in the 1974 armed robbery. She now is married and living in
Connecticut with her husband and two daughters under the married
name of Patty Hearst Shaw.
   Shaw, granddaughter of newspaper tycoon William Randolph Hearst,
asked for the pardon last August. She has maintained that she was
brainwashed by the radical Symbionese Liberation Army, a group of
revolutionaries who kidnapped her in Berkeley, Calif., in February
1974, and orchestrated the bank heist.
   Her seven-year sentence was commuted by President Carter and she
was released from prison on Feb. 1, 1979, after serving 23 months.
</TEXT>
