<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     01-18 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ryzhkov Says Azerbaijanis Fled 100 Villages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Azerbaijanis fled 105 Armenian villages prior to
the December earthquake because of ethnic strife over
Nagorno-Karabakh that the Kremlin is trying to break by imposing
direct rule, a Soviet official said.
   Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov spent several weeks in Armenia
managing the response to the Dec. 7 quake, and returned Tuesday for
a meeting with party officials and economic managers. A report on
the meeting was published in Wednesday's Communist Party newspaper
Pravda.
   The earthquake struck after another flare-up of ethnic violence
between Azerbaijanis and Armenians in the southern republics. More
than 60 people have been killed in ethnic unrest in the past year,
and 200,000 people have fled the violence.
   Last week, in order to stem the unrest the Kremlin announced it
was suspending the legislature of Nagorno-Karabakh, the region of
Azerbaijan that Armenia wants to annex, and impose direct Kremlin
rule.
   ``This is a compromise under which a mutually acceptable balance
of interests of the two republics is observed,'' Ryzhkov said.
   ``The decision made about Nagorno-Karabakh is no one's victory
and no one's loss. It was dictated solely: to lessen tension in the
region, re-establish order, give people the possibility to live,
work and raise their children normally,'' he said.
   Even prior to the earthquake, the Azerbaijani population of 105
Armenian villages fled because of the ethnic tension, he said. Now
that Armenia is trying to rebuild from the quake that killed about
25,000 people, there is an insufficient number of people to organize
workers and tend cattle and sheep, he said.
   Ryzhkov and Suren Arutunyan, Communist Party chief of Armenia,
both partially blamed Armenian intellectuals for encouraging the
drive to annex Nagorno-Karabakh, which began with demands made by
the primarily ethnic Armenian population of the area in February.
   Ryzhkov said positive changes were seen in the mood of Armenia,
but that in order to heal the wounds left by the violence, changes
must continue to take place from the bottom as well as directed by
the Kremlin.
   On Tuesday, Pravda said 49 Communist Party and government
officials in Armenia had been sacked for encouraging nationalism and
a variety of other offenses including blackmail.
   In a separate article Wednesday, Pravda said Y.P. Kochetkov had
been replaced as the Armenian party's second secretary by O.I. Lobov
and was trasnferred to unspecified other work.
   It said a member of the Armenian Politburo, F.T. Sarkisyan had
retired and his place was taken by Armenian Premier V.S. Markaryants.
</TEXT>
