<HEAD>Reagan Says Lifting Ban on Companies' Libya Operations Studied</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Wednesday that easing
sanctions barring U.S. oil companies from doing business in Libya is
``under study right now.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said no decision had been
reached, and an announcement would be made by the Treasury
Department when there is one.
   Reagan, asked about the possibility at a medal-presenting
ceremony, said, ``I can only say it's under study right now as to
that situation.''
   Officials have said that continuing the prohibition, put into
effect three years ago, could end up benefiting Libyan strongman
Moammar Gadhafi.
   Several U.S. companies have been barred since mid-l986 from doing
business directly in Libya, but they have kept their assets there
under an agreement with the Libyan government.
   The agreement froze the assets of five American companies:
Amerada Hess, Marathon Oil, W.R. Grace, Occidental Petroleum and
Conoco Petroleum.
   Some U.S. officials have expressed concern that if the ban is
continued Gadhafi might seize the frozen assets.
