<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia,0168</SECOND>
<HEAD>5,000 Gather in Prague in Fourth Day of Protests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 5,000 people converged on the
city's central Wenceslas Square today chanting ``Freedom!''
``Truth!'' and ``Human rights!'' in the fourth consecutive day of
public dissent.
   The group also chanted the name of jailed dissident Vaclav Havel
and others arrested for taking part in protests in the Czechoslovak
capital since Sunday.
   In a reversal of tactics that drew strong Western criticism,
police kept watch on the demonstrators but did not try to disperse
them.
   On Sunday, Monday and Tuesday, police used water cannons, tear
gas, dogs and batons to break up crowds that gathered to commemorate
the 20th anniversary of the death of Jan Palach, who set himself
afire Jan. 16, 1969 to protest the presence of Soviet troops in
Czechoslovakia after the 1968 Warsaw Pact invasion.
   The demonstrators who began assembling on the square around 5
p.m. today attracted thousands of curious onlookers on their way
home from work.
