<FIRST>r w AM-Inaugural-HighRollers     01-18 0842</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Inaugural-High Rollers,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Inaugural Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>How the Rich Live It Up During Inaugural Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It costs a pretty penny to ride in style around
the nation's capital this inaugural week, and even wealthy would-be
power travelers may find themselves hailing taxicabs if they
procrastinate.
   Limousine operators report capacity or near-capacity bookings for
the week. One has switched its phones over to an answering service,
whose operators deliver the news: ``They are booked solid.''
   Those fortunate enough to find a limousine are paying to keep it
at their disposal. Because of demand, most Washington-area companies
are leasing on a three- or four-day basis, with the car and
chauffeur on call eight to 10 hours each day.
   The cost: $2,700 at Presidential Limousine Service. There is an
alternative package, referred to among the in-crowd as ``sans
stretch.'' Translation: For $1,600 one can rent a car and driver for
four days, but the car will be a Lincoln Town Car sedan, not the
stretch limousine that comes with the pricier deal.
   Some companies are charging more; some a bit less. ``It's really
a seller's market,'' said Presidential's Herta Mullens.
   Some would-be clients have special requests.
   ``A lot have asked for bodyguards,'' said Mullens. ``We call it
executive protection, but they're essentially bodyguards.''
   High rollers who don't need a limo for four days but want a
classy ride to a single event may find it tough to find one. But,
not surprisingly, where there's a wallet, there's a way.
   ``If they are willing to pay the price, no one will go home
unhappy,'' Mullens said. ``With a little shuffling I can get someone
from their hotel to a ball for $1,000.''
   The ball-bound appear undeterred by the cost.
   ``They pause for a while when they hear the price,'' said
Mullens, ``and then say `OK, put me down.'''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Many of the high-powered Republicans who came to Washington to
see George Bush become president evidently were a bit hesitant about
his chances _ until the pollsters told them to relax and reserve.
   All 240 rooms and suites at the capital's plush Ritz-Carlton are
booked, including one offered as part of a $15,000 inaugural package
the hotel proudly boasted included ``the most expensive hotel room
in Washington.''
   But bookings were slow for a while. Hotel spokeswoman Vivian
Deuschl said the pace of reservations for the inaugural appeared
tied to Bush's lead in the pre-election polls.
   ``Every time Bush went up in the polls we got more phone calls,''
Ms. Deuschl said. ``Then, when everybody was saying it was all over
we started getting requests for room blocks.''
   By Election Day, the Ritz was booked for inaugural week.
   The least expensive room is $290 a night, with a four-night
minimum this week. Those lucky enough to land a suite pay between
$800 and $1,200 a night.
   Among the Ritz's registered guests is real estate mogul Donald
Trump, who apparently signed up for the four-night minimum although
he plans to spend just two nights in Washington, arriving Thursday,
attending the swearing-in ceremony Friday and one of the balls that
night.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Tuxedos and tacos may seem an odd mix, but the hands-down winner
as the most-sought after ticket in town is a ducat for a Texas State
Society black-tie affair with a Tex-Mex menu.
   The 5,500 tickets to the Saturday night Black Tie and Boots Ball
sold out in less than 24 hours, sales fueled by speculation the new
president will show up to salute his adopted home state.
   The tickets sold for $50, well below the $1,500 charged for some
of the fancier inaugural dinners. But as well-heeled Republicans
converge on the capital for Friday's inauguration, many are offering
to raise the ante for coveted tickets to the Texas hoedown.
   ``It's the big thing, at the top of the list,'' said Michelle
Davis, executive director of the Republican Governors Association.
``People are offering $1,000 and more for a $50 ticket. Obviously
this is the hip place to be.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgette Mosbacher made her much-awaited public inaugural week
debut Wednesday, attending a luncheon and saying she was ``very
excited'' about joining Washington's social circuit.
   Mrs. Mosbacher and her husband, Commerce Secretary-designate
Robert Mosbacher, were among the featured guests at the Inaugural
Salute to Women in Business Luncheon.
   Mrs. Mosbacher was a prime topic of conversation at a brief
reception before the luncheon and a murmur spread through the room
as the Mosbachers entered just as Marilyn Quayle, wife of Vice
President-elect Dan Quayle, finished brief remarks to the gathering.
   ``I'm enjoying it very much,'' she said when asked about her
first visit to Washington since President-elect Bush named his
longtime friend to the Commerce post.
   ``It's a very exciting town,'' she said. ``I'm really enjoying
it.''
   The Mosbachers have quickly become desired guests at Washington
parties.
   ``That's what they tell me,'' said Mrs. Mosbacher who was
featured in a Washington Post Magazine profile on Sunday. ``This is
just the beginning,'' she said.
</TEXT>
