<FIRST>r i AM-Kidneys     01-18 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kidneys,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>News Report Says Turkish Peasants Were Paid To Donate Kidneys</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Turkish police have arrested the alleged organizer
of an operation in which peasants were paid to donate kidneys for
transplant recipients at a private London hospital, a newspaper
reported Wednesday.
   The Independent said the peasants were offered the equivalent of
$3,540 to donate one of their kidneys, and traveled to London for
the operations.
   It said police in Istanbul arrested Tunc Kunter on Tuesday and
charged him with cheating people out of body organs. Kunter admitted
running the operation but said he was motivated by a sense of
humanity, not profit, the newspaper reported.
   It said the kidney removal operations were carried out under the
care of Dr. Raymond Crockett at the exclusive, privately owned
Wellington Humana Hospital in west London.
   The paper quoted Crockett as saying: ``I would be satisfied there
is no duress. As far as anything else is concerned, I think it is
not my brief (my concern).''
   Crockett and an unidentified hospital official said the
operations were carried out legally, with the donors' consent,
according to the newspaper.
   It quoted the British government's Health Department as saying
trade in kidneys for transplant into patients suffering kidney
failure is discouraged but not illegal in Britain.
   John Patten, former parliamentary undersecretary of state for
health, ordered an review when a similar trade involving Pakistanis
was disclosed in 1985.
   ``Three years later, a spokesman for the department said
yesterday that no action had yet been taken,'' the newspaper
reported.
</TEXT>
