<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-Books     01-18 0124</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Books,0128</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nine Arrested For Publishing Pro-North Korea Books</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine people were arrested Wednesday for
publishing books supporting North Korean President Kim Il Sung and
his communist idelogy.
   In a raid on several major bookstores and printing shops in
Seoul, prosecutors also seized 3,580 pro-North Korean books,
including ``Kim Il Sung Selections.''
   Those arrested may be charged with violating the tough National
Security Law, prosecution officials said. The law provides for five
to eight years in jail terms for violators.
   South Korea has recently eased restrictions on information on
North Korea, but the books seized were believed extremely harmful
for South Korea's ``wholesome, free, democratic system.''
   Prosecution authorities said they would continue a crackdown on
pro-North Korean publications.
