<HEAD>Liberal Leader John Turner Released From Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Liberal Party leader John Turner checked out of
the hospital Wednesday, eight days after undergoing surgery to
relieve back pain caused by pinched nerves.
   Turner, 59, is ``in good spirits and feeling fine,'' said Jane
McDowell, a party spokeswoman.
   Doctors at Toronto General Hospital performed surgery to remove a
small part of bone in the lower-back region that had been pinching
nerves.
   The problem caused the opposition leader to limp throughout much
of November's federal election campaign.
   Turner will spend a week at his apartment in Toronto before
returning to Ottawa. He also plans a two-week vacation to Jamaica in
February.
   He is expected to take his seat in the House of Commons when
Parliament resumes March 6.
