<SECOND>AM-Deng,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deng Xiaoping's Son Says Dad is Healthy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son of senior leader Deng Xiaoping on
Wednesday denied rumors that his 84-year-old father is in poor
health.
   ``I may tell you that he is very healthy,'' Deng Pufang was
quoted by the official Xinhua News Agency as telling a news
conference.
   Rumors that Deng was in poor health caused a sharp drop in the
Hong Kong stock exchange last week.
   Speculation about the health of China's top leader is common, but
he has appeared fit in recent appearances and his only known
disability is poor hearing in one ear.
   The younger Deng, who heads the China Welfare Fund for the
Handicapped, also denied foreign reports that he has private
accounts in overseas banks, saying ``it is a fairy tale.''
   ``If any of you reporters here find that I have savings in any
overseas banks, 70 percent will go to you and the remaining 30
percent go to a bank of China,'' he said.
   Deng travels abroad frequently as China's leading advocate for
the disabled. He has been paralyzed from the waist down since the
Cultural Revolution in the 1960s, when leftist Red Guards threw him
out of a fifth-floor window.
