<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 1444EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Cyanide-Yogurt     01-18 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cyanide-Yogurt,0683</SECOND>
<HEAD>Family Of Stricken Youth Keeps Low Profile</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELANIE L. BURNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HADDONFIELD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frances and Hsin-Yi Lee have spent two
weeks shuttling between lawyers' offices, the prosecutors office and
a hospital where their son, Thomas, is in a coma from
cyanide-poisoning.
   Their lives have been subject to microscopic scrutiny _
investigators have even rifled through their kitchen garbage _ and
their telephone rings incessantly.
   ``This is a real nightmare for an otherwise private family,''
said Dr. Robert Nagele, a family friend. ``But now every aspect of
their life has been made very public.''
   Thomas, 17, a junior at Haddonfield Memorial High School, has
been in critical condition and on life-support machinery at West
Jersey Hospital-Voorhees since Jan. 3, when he ate black cherry
yogurt laced with cyanide.
   On Thursday a guardian appointed to represent Thomas' welfare
must file court papers over whether his life-support machines should
be disconnected. Hospital officials have painted a dismal picture of
his chances of recovery.
   Police have not ruled out attempted homicide or suicide. But they
say one thing is almost certain: The yogurt package was not tampered
with at the factory or the store.
   The Lees have adamantly insisted in statements released through
attorneys that their son would not have tried to kill himself, and
that he was too popular to be the target of a slaying.
   Camden County Prosecutor Samuel Asbell said last week the boy's
parents and brother were not targets of the investigation into how
the cyanide got into the carton of yogurt.
   But family members were fingerprinted this week and two FBI
agents fingerprinted Thomas at the hospital Saturday, said George
Kerns, a spokesman for Asbell.
   Kerns said investigators wanted the fingerprints for comparison
to items taken from the Lee home and the father's laboratory at
Rutgers University in Camden, where he is chairman of the biology
department.
   Asbell declined to describe the items under investigation, but
the U.S. Food and Drug Administration has said a tiny plastic vial
of cyanide was found at the Lee home. Asbell has declined to confirm
or deny whether cyanide was found at the elder Lee's laboratory.
   In the meantime, Nagele, a former student of Lee and now
professor of pediatrics at the University of Medicine and Dentistry
of New Jersey in Camden, has tried to shield the family from
reporters.
   ``They deserve a little peace,'' he said. ``People are forgetting
that Tommy's still on life support. Their thoughts should be with
him.''
   ``They're just heart-broken,'' said attorney Alan Turner. ``I
think they're experiencing what any parents would experience upon
such a tragedy.''
   Lee, 53, came to the United States from Taiwan in 1961 and earned
his doctorate from the University of Minnesota. He became a
professor at Rutgers in 1968 and is recognized as an expert on early
brain development.
   ``Students are always trying to beat down the door to get in his
lab,'' said Nagele, who worked in Lee's lab for five years and is
currently collaborating with him on a number of projects.
   Outside of his work, Lee has few hobbies or pastimes. His wife,
Frances, also a Taiwanese immigrant who holds a master's degree in
immunology from Eastern Illinois, has primarily been a homemaker
since the birth of Thomas.
   ``They have done the best over the years, to the point of
spoiling their boys,'' said Nagele. ``They were very devoted to
their children.''
   Thomas' brother, Bruce, 20, is a student at Harvard University.
``They were always together,'' Nagele said. ``There was no direct
competition.''
   The brothers have been popular, out-going students.
   Thomas, a 160-pound wrestler, had ``so much going for him,'' said
classmate Zachary Resnicoff, captain of the school's wrestling team.
``He has lots of friends and likes school.''
   Nagele and school officials described Thomas as a good student
and a gifted artist and musician.
   ``He's a super kid,'' said head wrestling coach Joe Frassenei.
``He's very bright, well-liked by his teammates.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890118-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 1456EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Meat-Pesticides     01-18 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Meat-Pesticides,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Audit Finds Slipshod Control Involving Chemicals in Meat and Poultry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An internal audit by the Agriculture Department
says that federal control of illegally high traces of pesticides and
other chemicals in the nation's meat and poultry supply has been
slipshod and sometimes ineffective.
   The investigators found that in some cases meat and poultry
containing too much of these chemical residues slipped through and
got into the consumer pipeline.
   ``Even when animals were presented to inspectors, (agency)
administrative controls and current policies did not ensure timely
and effective response when pesticide residue was suspected or found
in meat and poultry products,'' the report said. ``As a result, some
adulterated products were allowed to enter commerce.''
   The report by the department's Office of Inspector General said
the department's inspection agency _ the Food Safety and Inspection
Service, or FSIS _ has little authority to prevent pesticide
residues from showing up in meat and poultry.
   Accordingly, the FSIS has turned to the food industry itself for
cooperation in monitoring levels of chemicals and ferreting out
violations.
   The agency's chief responsibility is to ensure that
USDA-inspected meat and poultry products are safe, wholesome and
free of adulterating chemicals. As part of its responsibility, the
agency samples and analyzes edible tissues to see if they meet the
federal standards.
   But the system is far from foolproof, and the agency also
includes efforts to enlighten farmers and processors about the
federal standards and how to comply with them.
   The report, which was completed last November but not given wide
distribution by the department, said FSIS was ``unable to
successfully investigate pesticide violations in 79 percent of the
cases'' reviewed by the auditors. A violation was defined as an
illegal level of chemical residue found in a sample of meat or
poultry.
   Some of the reasons for the lack of success in investigating
violations included:
   _Tracing the illegal residue to the original producer was not
always successful.
   _Follow-up samples from suspected meat were seldom taken, or else
the suspected animals or carcasses were not always retained for
further checking.
   _Documentation of regulatory actions was insufficient.
   Starting in June 1986, when a company signed a memorandum of
understanding with FSIS, it agreed to upgrade its own quality
control procedures, was exempted from routine monitoring by the
agency and placed under a less-intensive monitoring program.
   ``In addition, these companies became eligible to make certain
claims on their product labels concerning (chemical) residue levels
or superior quality control procedures,'' the report said.
   By 1988, this ``verified production control'' program included 11
companies and 34 slaughter plants out of a U.S. total of 1,800
plants. The participating plants had an annual slaughter of about 5
billion pounds, or about 8 percent of all animals slaughtered last
year.
   In all, the agency is responsible for inspection in more than
7,000 meat and poultry slaughter and processing plants.
   The USDA investigators visited 96 federally inspected meat and
poultry plants and conducted research at the agency's national
office, three regional offices, three field laboratories and five
USDA-accredited laboratories.
   One of the major problems uncovered is the identification of the
original farmer, feedlot operator or other producer of livestock
that have been found to be in violation of the federal residue
levels.
   The report recommended that the agency seek legislation for
mandatory identification of the source of all animal species
slaughter for domestic food consumption. However, FSIS responded
that such a move be directed to policy-makers, not the regulatory
agency itself.
   Lester M. Crawford, FSIS administrator, said that historically
the agency has pursued animal identification as a related part of
the residue testing program.
   ``We recently were successful in obtaining a swine identification
program outside of the legislative route, and would strongly support
similar identification for the other species which come under our
jurisdiction,'' Crawford said in a response to the report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
