<FIRST>r w AM-FamilyReunion     01-18 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Family Reunion,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>The 230 Bush Kin and 117 Quayle Kin Come to Town</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Inaugural Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's soon-to-be first family crammed
into a government guesthouse Wednesday as some 230 of George and
Barbara Bush's closest relatives, aflutter with excitement, took
over an intimate hotel festooned with flags and bunting.
   ``Isn't it something,'' marveled one family member as she checked
into the flower-filled Jefferson Hotel, with its vaulted ceiling,
damask-covered love seats and imposing portrait of Thomas Jefferson.
``I've been laughing and crying all day.''
   The Bush's brothers, sisters, uncles, aunts, nieces, nephews and
cousins are occupying 90 of the hotel's 100 rooms this week. As they
arrived, weighed down with furs and formal wear, some of them
scheduled manicure and makeup appointments even before checking in.
   In addition to all the official glamour and pomp, the relatives
are throwing a few parties of their own. The family reunion will
culminate with a White House lunch for 250 relatives on Saturday,
the first full day the new president and first lady will spend in
their new home.
   The nomadic couple, billed as having moved 28 times in a 44-year
marriage, won't make their 29th move until Friday after Bush has
taken his oath of office. And their personal belongings aren't due
to arrive at the White House until Monday.
   But they left the vice presidential residence Wednesday for a
two-day transitional stay in Blair House, the government's quarters
for visiting dignitaries.
   ``Our house looks like yours do whenever you make a move,'' Bush
told a group of teachers, referring to the official residence on the
grounds of the U.S. Naval Observatory. ``It's a real wasteland out
there this morning.''
   Blair House, four connected rowhouses across Pennsylvania Avenue
from the White House, is designed to house 19 guests. The Bushes
will number 22, counting children, spouses, grandchildren and the
president-elect's mother Dorothy, 87.
   The whole crew will move to the White House with the first couple
on Friday and Bush's mother, only the 12th presidential mom to see
her son sworn in, will sleep in the Queen's Bedroom.
   Barbara Bush personally packed hundreds of boxes and decided
which belongings would go to the White House, which to Camp David,
which to the summer house in Kennebunkport and which into storage.
   ``We've got dots on everything,'' she told reporters last week,
referring to her system denoting which items are going where. The
move had been exciting but also ``agony,'' she said, ``maybe because
I'm tired.''
   Despite the two moves in the space of a week, ``I don't see that
they look at it as a strain,'' said Sondra Haley, a spokeswoman for
Mrs. Bush. ``They wanted to be with their family and there was no
way the vice president's residence could accomodate everybody.''
   Vice President-elect Dan Quayle, his wife Marilyn and their three
children are expected to move into the official residence early next
month. Renovations for the young family are not expected to be
complete by then, but the Secret Service is anxious to install them
there as soon as possible.
   They can't compete with the Bushes, but the Quayles are no
slouches in the relative department. Quayle put the latest count at
117 coming for the inauguration.
   ``I think some of them, we asked for their birth certificates,''
Quayle joked. ``They started calling up and saying `I am a relative
of the senator' and I said, `Oh?' So we were going to have a
genealogist check their birth certificate and the tree and all that.
   ``But no,'' he added hastily, ``we'll be glad to see them all.''
   According to Haley, the 200-plus Bush relatives are people the
president-elect and his wife have been in touch with over the years,
and many have been guests at the family's summer home in
Kennebunkport, Maine.
   ``We get enormous strength from our family,'' Mrs. Bush said
during her session with reporters. ``Not just our children and
granchildren, but our brothers and sisters. It's always been like
that. And more so now.''
</TEXT>
