<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 1521EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Inauguration-Security     01-18 0724</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Inauguration-Security,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Inaugural Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tight Security, Protests Planned for Inauguration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bullet-proof shield to protect George Bush
when he takes the presidential oath of office Friday is in place.
The manhole covers along the parade route are welded shut. Virtually
every police agency in town has canceled all days off.
   Welcome to Washington, the inaugural city, where protestors are
ready to demonstrate for their own version of a ``kinder, gentler''
nation and authorities hope they're ready for whatever transpires.
   ``We intend to be everywhere,'' Lisa Fithian, a spokeswoman for
the Counter-Inaugural Coalition for a People's Agenda, told a news
conference Wednesday. ``We will be a reminder of the urgency of not
just a kinder, gentler nation but a kinder, gentler, less insulated
government.''
   But she said the coalition's 80 groups _ ranging from the Student
Coalition Against Apartheid and Racism to Environmental Action _
have agreed not to conduct any civil disobedience.
   Anyone going anywhere the first families might go will be checked
with metal detectors. That includes, for the first time, the 150,000
invited guests at the Capitol swearing-in ceremonies, even if
they'll be sitting hundreds of yards away.
   That bit of security has upset Sen. Wendell Ford, D-Ky., chairman
of the Joint Congressional Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies.
   ``Security is something that bothers me considerably,'' he said
Tuesday. ``We're a free and open nation insisting that those in the
inner circle go through megadetectors.''
   The west side of the Capitol, where Bush will take the oath, has
been secured for a week.
   Starting tonight, the Capitol itself will be off-limits to all
unauthorized people. Friday, all streets within a two-block radius
will be closed, with even members of Congress told not to use their
normal parking spaces on the Capitol grounds.
   Many security details remained secret even as the celebrations
got under way Wednesday.
   ``We certainly wouldn't want to give anyone who had harmful
intent any kind of advantage,'' said Secret Service spokesman Ken
Lynch.
   Reports on previous inaugurations have indicated that agents
carrying shoulder-fired Stinger missiles to protect against air
attack were on the Capitol roof.
   The agencies involved refused to say if that would be the case
this year, although Bob Buckhorn of the Federal Aviation
Administration noted that flying over the White House or the Capitol
is normally a violation of federal air regulations.
   Flying over those places during the inauguration ``would be an
extreme, gross violation,'' Buckhorn said. ``The Secret Service
frowns on those kinds of violations.''
   Bush will ride in an armored limousine along the parade route
from the Capitol to the White House after he takes the oath,
according to everyone willing to talk about it.
   But then, that's what all they said about President Carter before
he and his wife, Rosalynn, climbed out of their car and walked the
1{ miles down Pennsylvania Avenue in January 1977.
   Jody Powell, Carter's press secretary, said in a recent interview
that his boss told him about his plans a week before the
inauguration but that the news was ``very tightly held, for security
purposes.''
   ``What he told me at the time was the deal was the Secret Service
wasn't going to fight it as long as it was kept secret, but if word
got out ahead of time they'd be very opposed to it,'' Powell said.
   The Secret Service will be ready to protect Bush if he, too,
decides to stroll down the parade route, says spokesman Rich Adams.
But he admitted the agents would not be too happy about it.
   ``If we had our way, he would not leave the White House,'' Adams
said.
   Even from the White House, the new president will be able to see
protestors.
   A corner of Lafayette Park, across Pennsylvania Avenue from
Bush's new home, has been set aside for demonstrations ``to ensure
First Amendment rights,'' in the words of Park Police Capt. Michael
Barrett.
   Planning to protest along the parade route are the
Counter-Inaugural Coalition and its member groups as well as the
National Organization for Women, which has announced a silent
protest.
   Law enforcement agencies involved in security for the inaugural
ceremonies include the Secret Service, Capitol Police, the District
of Columbia police department, Metro transit police, Park Police,
Federal Protective Service and the District of Columbia National
Guard.
</TEXT>
