<FIRST>r w AM-Abrams-Heritage     01-18 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abrams-Heritage,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abrams Moving to Heritage Foundation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elliott Abrams, an architect of recent U.S.
policy toward Central America, is moving to the Heritage Foundation,
joining Edwin Meese III and other former Reagan administration
officials at the conservative Washington think tank, it was
announced Wednesday.
   Abrams, the assistant secretary of state for inter-American
affairs, was point man on Capitol Hill in President Reagan's efforts
to secure money for the Contra guerrillas of Nicaragua. He turns 40
next Tuesday.
   Starting on Jan. 21, the day after Reagan leaves office, Abrams
will write and lecture on Latin American affairs, foundation
president Edwin Feulner Jr. said in a statement.
   Feulner held no full-time post in the Reagan administration, but
has served as chairman of the U.S. Advisory Commission on Public
Diplomacy, advising Reagan on the conduct of American foreign policy.
   The most prominent former Reagan aide at Heritage is Meese, whose
conduct as attorney general was criticized in a Justice Department
report this week.
   Richard Allen, who resigned as Reagan's first national security
adviser in a flap over unreported gifts, is also a Heritage fellow,
directing the foundation's Asian studies center.
   Cheryl Rubin, a spokeswoman for Heritage, listed other former
Reagan administration officials at the foundation as Terrence
Scanlon, former head of the Consumer Products Safety Commission;
Charles Lichenstein, alternate representative to the United Nations,
1981-84; Kenneth Cribb, assistant to the Reagan for domestic
affairs; Kate Walsh O'Brien, deputy assistant secretary for Health
and Human Services; Roger Brooks, head of planning for the State
Department's bureau of international orgnizations; and Charles
Heatherly, director of the president's commission on White House
fellowships.
   Abrams, an attorney, joined the administration as assistant
secretary of state for international organization affairs in 1981,
then took over the human rights portfolio before assuming his
current postion in 1985.
   Formerly, he worked for Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., and
the late Sen. Henry Jackson, D-Wash.
</TEXT>
