<FIRST>r i AM-CubanFamily     01-18 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuban Family,0300</SECOND>
<UNK>Canada Lets Cuban Family Stay</UNK>
<DATELINE>NIAGARA FALLS, Ontario (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canadian immigration officials said
Wednesday they will ``look the other way'' until a Cuban man and his
family exhausts efforts to return to their home in Miami.
   Milt Best, a spokesman for Employment and Immigration Canada,
said that although Carlos Fajardo and his family are technically
illegal aliens in Canada, officials will not move against them while
they continue talks with U.S. immigration authorities.
   ``We will let them stay until we see what happens next,'' Best
said.
   Canadian officials had issued the Fajardos a temporary visa that
expired Sunday.
   The family has been stranded at a Niagara Falls, Ontario, motel
since Dec. 23, when they crossed into Canada to view the falls and
were prevented from returning after falsely claiming U.S.
citizenship.
   Hispanic groups and U.S. Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., have pleaded
with U.S. immigration officials to allow the family to return on
humanitarian grounds. But authorities have refused, saying Fajardo's
wife, Bermaida, has a history of immigration fraud.
   Fajardo had an application for asylum pending, but by leaving the
country the application was nullified, officials said.
   Roderick McDowall, a Canadian attorney representing the family,
said he expects some new efforts to readmit the family will begin
next week.
   McDowall said Fajardo will submit a new application for asylum
and hope that if he is granted refugee status his wife and her two
children will be allowed to return as well.
   Fajardo owns a home and small boat building business in Miami. He
entered the country illegally in 1985 from Panama.
   Farjardo's wife and her children by a previous marriage entered
the country illegally in 1986 from Venezuela. A U.S. immigration
judge ordered the family deported last August.
</TEXT>
