<FIRST>r a AM-Carter-Ford     01-18 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Carter-Ford,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carter and Ford Say They Can't Figure Why They Got Such Bad Press</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jimmy Carter had the ``killer rabbit'' to contend
with and Jerry Ford was perceived as prone to bumping his head on
helicopter doors. But after all these years, the two former
presidents say they don't know why they got such lousy press.
   ``Presidents Nixon, Johnson, Ford and I had bad relations with
the press. Reagan had good relations,'' said Carter on Wednesday.
``Why, I don't know.''
   Carter and Ford took part in a discussion at Columbia University
on ``The Press, the Presidency and the First Hundred Days.'' They
agreed that when it comes to relations with the news media, George
Bush will find Ronald Reagan a hard act to follow.
   Reagan was treated with kid gloves by the press, Ford said. And
Carter thinks Reagan got away with staying aloof from tough issues _
``a tribute to his acuity.''
   Carter said he had unsuccessful relationships with the press. He
said he spent weeks trying to deflect attention from a story that a
rabbit had swum out to his boat as he was fishing and that he had to
beat it back with oars.
   ``How can you control something like that?'' Cartr asked. The
rabbit story, he said, ``gave an image of an incompetent president
who could not even protect himself against a rabbit.''
   He said that Ford ``was the best athlete ever in the White
House'' but that Ford was dogged by stories about his golf balls
hitting bystanders and his clumsiness generally. ``It hurt him
politically,'' Carter said.
   Ford said news people who accompanied him on ski trips to Vail
fell as much on the slopes as he did ``but nobody took pictures of
them.''
   The images are hurtful, he said, but ``it's part of what they
think the public wants.''
   Ford said that when Bush takes the oath of office this week he
will start out with the best atmosphere, since relations between the
press and Reagan in recent weeks have been pleasant.
</TEXT>
