<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 2035EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-MXSchedule     01-18 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-MX Schedule,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>GAO Says Pentagon Has Ambitious Schedule for Rail Garrison System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department has an ambitious
schedule for developing a rail garrison system for the MX missile,
according to a congressional agency report that says there could be
cost and performance problems if the program is not closely
supervised.
   The General Accounting Office, an investigating arm of Congress,
said in a report this week that the department's acquisition
strategy for the rail garrison system calls for the start of
production two years before development contracts have been
completed.
   This overlap between production and development, known as
concurrency, must be ``well planned and controlled,'' the GAO said,
otherwise, ``it can cause cost, schedule and performance problems,
as demonstrated in other Air Force acquisition programs.''
   In addition, the GAO said that by March 1990, when the department
must make an initial production decision on the rail garrison, only
about two years of the system's planned four-year test program will
have been completed.
   ``Most systems integration testing, all basing verification
missile flight tests, and most of the operational test and
evaluation effort will remain to be done,'' said the GAO.
   The Defense Department, in comments included in the GAO report,
concurred with all of the agency's findings. It added that the
department believes the system of launching missiles from the rails
is similar to silo launches and does not require special tests.
   Under the rail garrison system, 50 missiles would be placed on 25
trains that would be parked inside train alert shelters in garrisons
at Air Force bases around the country. In the event of a threat, the
trains, each carrying two missiles, would move onto the nation's
railroad tracks.
   The Air Force estimates that acquisition cost for the rail
garrison system is about $7.4 billion.
   Congress approved $440 million for research and development of
the rail garrison program in fiscal 1987 and 1988, and appropriated
$600 million in fiscal 1989. However, the Pentagon can only spend
$250 million on the MX rail garrison before Feb. 15, according to
the Department of Defense authorization bill for fiscal 1989.
   The Feb. 15 date is the deadline for the president to decide what
to do with the remainder of the funds.
   Under the system, the trains will be deployed initially at F.E.
Warren Air Force Base in Wyoming, and at up to 10 other possible Air
Force installations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
