<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OK, so the thief kept the cash stolen from
Rufus Edmisten's car. But he returned items that the North Carolina
secretary of state considered far more valuable _ Watergate
memorabilia and two Super Bowl tickets.
   Someone entered Edmisten's unlocked, state-owned Chevrolet in
Raleigh Saturday and stole a briefcase, a raincoat and $500 to $700.
Edmisten reported the theft to police.
   But on Monday morning, Edmisten found that all the items except
the money had been placed in the back seat of his Toyota in front of
his house.
   ``The only thing I can figure is someone looked in there and
said, `Oh my God, it's Rufus' _ I'd better give this back to him.
But I need the money,''' Edmisten said.
   The briefcase that was returned contained mementos from
Edmisten's days working for Sen. Sam J. Ervin, D-N.C., on the Senate
committee that investigated the Watergate scandal, including a
subpoena that Edmisten served on President Nixon demanding that he
turn over the infamous White House tapes.
   The leather case also contained about 30 family photographs,
irreplaceable state documents, and _ last but not least _ two
round-trip airline tickets to Miami and two tickets to Sunday's
Super Bowl.
   ``I fully expected I would never hear of this briefcase again,''
Edmisten said. ``I was heartbroken about the briefcase.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wandering rooster that was picked up as
a fowl-at-large and served time in the pen has been adopted and will
star on a radio show.
   Dog Pound Director Larry Cole said even if the law does instruct
his workers to pick up ``chickens, ducks, geese, turkeys or other
domestic fowl'' running loose, ``we're going to make this our last
rooster.''
   The as-yet-unnamed rooster caused a ruckus during its three-week
stay in the pound when dogs howled at its crowing. The Metro Health
Department auctioned off the bird Tuesday to cover the costs of the
dog food it ate.
   The bidding began at $6 but rapidly increased to $13.50 before
WKDJ disc jockey Carl P. Mayfield, one of the bidders, urged James
W. Peach of Madison, the other, ``to cut a deal.''
   Peach, who said his children wanted the bird because their
8-year-old pet rooster died last year, agreed to let the fowl make
guest appearances on the show as the ``official Rock 103.3 KDF
rooster.''
   The final gavel price was $14. Mayfield said he planned a contest
to name the bird.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What does it take to outfit a 12-member
expedition to the world's third-highest peak?
   In the case of the American 1989 Kangchenjunga Expedition, two
tons of goods ranging from tents, rope and other climbing and
camping gear to footstuffs that included cases of candy bars, Spam,
salamis, peanut butter and canned beans and franks.
   ``My favorite are Snickers,'' said expedition leader Lou
Whittaker of Ashford, operator of Rainier Mountaineering Inc.
   Five Mount Rainier guides and prominent mountaineers Jim Wickwire
and John Roskelly also are participating in the $160,000 effort to
put the first U.S. climbers atop 28,168-foot Kangchenjunga, which
lies in Nepal about 50 miles from Mount Everest.
   Whittaker said Tuesday the group would make its assault on the
north face while a group of 48 Russians heads up from the south. The
Americans hoped to meet the Russians at the summit by early May and
exchange toasts of vodka and scotch, he said.
