<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Gulf     01-18 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Gulf,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Diplomats Hope For Progress On Repatriating Injured Gulf War POWs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diplomats said Wednesday they see little
hope of breaking a deadlock in Iran-Iraq peace talks when a U.N.
envoy visits the region next week, but they were optimistic the
exchange of war prisoners will resume.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar is sending his
representative, Swedish U.N. Ambassador Jan. K. Eliasson, to Baghdad
and Tehran in an effort to prod Iraq and Iran into showing some
flexibility.
   Their nearly eight-year war ground to a halt Aug. 20 after both
sides accepted a cease-fire, but peace talks that opened five days
later immediately stalemated.
   The cease-fire resolution calls on both countries to halt all
military activities; withdraw their troops to the border; exchange
about 100,000 war prisoners; and begin peace talks.
   Iraq still occupies 259 square miles of Iranian territory and
says it will not withdraw until Iran gives up the right to search
ships for war cargo bound for Iraq. It considers that a military
activity.
   Iran, which has not stopped any Iraqi-bound ships since the
cease-fire began, says the withdrawal to the border must be the next
step in the peace process.
   U.N. officials and diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity,
did not foresee the likelihood of Tehran or Baghdad budging from
those positions but said progress was possible on the exchange of
sick or injured POWs and other technical measures.
   Iran and Iraq recently allowed the United Nations to begin direct
flights between the two nations, a U.N. official said.
   Previously, the two nations distrusted each other so intensely
that even U.N. diplomats had to fly to a third country to travel
between them.
   The United Nations has also received ``expressions of interest''
from both sides in resuming the exchange of POWS, the U.N. official
said.
   Last year, the International Committee of the Red Cross worked
out a plan for the registration of all POWs and the exchange of sick
or injured POWs, but the arrangement broke down after only a few
dozen had been exchanged.
   A U.N. official said Iran and Iraq appear ready to initiate
direct contacts between their military officers to work out their
frequent complaints about technical violations of the cease-fire and
other military matters.
   ``We hope to achieve movement, some sense of progress'' he said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He also hoped for progress on substantial issues, including the
impasse over the Shatt-al-Arab waterway forming the border between
Iran and Iraq, but noted ``these are matters of deeper pride.''
   Iraq and Iran shared use of the Shatt-al-Arab under a 1975
treaty. It is Iraq's only deep-water access to the Persian Gulf.
Iraq has repudiated the treaty and said another accord should be
worked out under which the two nations would share use of the
waterway.
   It suggested the United Nations oversee the dredging of the
Shatt-al-Arab, but Iran has refused to go along with that unless
Iraq recognizes the 1975 treaty.
</TEXT>
