<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Libya     01-18 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Libya,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Again Changes Stance On Libyan Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Wednesday again
changed its position on when it knew about a suspected chemical
weapons plant in Libya, and opposition lawmakers shouted their
disapproval in Parliament.
   The latest switch came amid accusations by the opposition that
the government tried to cover up alleged involvement by West German
companies in the Libyan project.
   Wolfgang Schaeuble, Chancellor Helmut Kohl's chief of staff,
delivered a long address in Parliament defending the government's
actions.
   Schaeuble said the U.S. Embassy in Bonn informed West German
officials May 18 about possible German involvement in the Libyan
plant.
   The United States alleges the plant was intended to produce
chemical weapons. Libya says it will produce pharmaceuticals.
   The May 15 date is five months earlier than what the government
acknowledged Monday and six months earlier than the Nov. 15 date
West German leaders mentioned three weeks ago.
   Opposition lawmakers shouted and hooted during the speech.
   When the scandal first broke three weeks ago, West German leaders
angrily denied U.S. allegations German firms were involved in the
plant. They also denied having any knowledge the complex may be
intended for production of chemical weapons.
   Norbert Gansel, a lawmaker with the opposition Social Democrats,
spoke after Schaeuble and criticized the government's handling of
the growing scandal, which has led to criminal investigations into
two West German companies.
   ``The question is, what you knew and what you did about it,''
Gansel said.
   He added, ``You, Herr Chancellor, are politically and personally
responsible that the German and international public were deceived
for a long time.''
   Officials have said the government did not immediately say what
it knew because that would have jeopardized West German
investigations.
   Schaeuble told lawmakers that in August 1987, the West German
Federal Intelligence Service received information the plant ``in all
probability'' was intended for producing chemical weapons.
   He said at the time there was no evidence of West German
involvement in the plant.
   Schaeuble also said that ``on the basis of intelligence reports,
we must assume that this plant in Rabta is intended to produce
chemical weapons.''
   On Tuesday, chief government spokesman Friedhelm Ost refused to
say whether Bonn had evidence backing the U.S. charges about the
plant.
   According to Schaeuble, ``new reports'' by the West German
Intelligence Service ``gave clear indications of involvement by
German companies'' in the Libyan factory.
   Kohl received his first ``comprehensive'' report on the
suspicions Oct. 20, Schaeuble said.
   Schaeuble also provided new information about West German
investigations into the affair.
   He said that on Dec. 14, West German investigators met with an
``informant'' who gave them documents indicating involvement by the
German firm Imhausen-Chemie in the Libyan plant.
   According to Schaeuble, the informant said other documents could
be obtained from I.B.I. Engineering, a now-defunct company that was
based in Frankfurt.
   Criminal investigations have been launched against Imhausen and
I.B.I., which allegedly organized participation by German firms in
the Libyan plant.
   The criminal investigations began as a result of a Jan. 4 seizure
of I.B.I. documents, Schaeuble said.
   He rejected any suggestion West German authorities had tried to
cover up the affair.
   Kohl was present during the debate but did not speak. According
to a government spokesman, Schaeuble delivered the speech because it
was a matter of protocol.
</TEXT>
