<FIRST>r i AM-Haiti     01-18 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haiti,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Haiti Back to Normal After Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Schools and businesses reopened
Wednesday after a strike paralyzed the country, and organizers said
the work stoppage showed that Haitians ``want to turn a new page in
history.''
   Tuesday's strike was called by the Autonomous Union of Haitian
Workers, Haiti's largest and most radical union. It halted public
transport and closed businesses and schools in main provincial towns
and downtown Port-au-Prince.
   The union wants Haitian leader Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril to purge
his government of supporters of former dictator Jean-Claude
Duvalier, who fled the country in 1986.
   They also want the daily minimum wage of $3 raised to $7 and a
decrease in food and fuel prices.
   ``The strike revealed the profound frustrations of the people,''
said human rights activist Jean-Claude Bajeux.
   ``The Haitian people have not only shown the military government
that they want change but that they want to prove it, to prove to
the whole world that they want to turn a new page in history,''
Jean-Auguste Mesyeux, co-leader of the union, said on Radio Haiti
Inter, an independent station.
   State-run Television Nationale reported it ``was not a general
strike'' but that activity had merely slowed in the capital. The
network did not cover the strike in provincial towns.
   The strike had been declared illegal by Avril, who came to power
Sept. 17 in a coup led by rank-and-file soldiers who said they were
fed up with state-sponsored violence. They overthrew Lt. Gen. Henri
Namphy, the military leader who came to power after Duvalier fled.
   Friends continued searching Wednesday for two leftist activists
reported missing Monday night in a slum neighborhood. The two had
set out to distribute leaflets against inflation when they
disappeared, Radio Haiti Inter reported.
   They were identified as Vesner Jean-Francois and Roland Pierre,
members of a leftist umbrella group known as the National
Association of Popular Organizations.
</TEXT>
