<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Parade     01-18 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Parade,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Speculation Mounts: Might Bush Walk in His Own Parade?</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush's penchant for spontanaiety is
raising speculation about whether he might just decide to hop out of
his armored limousine Friday for a bit of inaugural parade
handshaking.
   While there is no word from the Bush camp on whether he might
decide to work the sidewalk crowds, the Secret Service is fully
prepared with protection for whatever fancy might strike him, said
spokesman Special Agent Rich Adams.
   ``We would be derelict in our duty if we weren't prepared for
that,'' he said. ``The possibility always exists ... He's the
president and we're there to provide security.''
   However, Adams said he has no information on whether Bush will
decide to get out of the brand new 1989 Ford Lincoln town car.
   Bush wouldn't be the first president to walk in his own parade.
   Jimmy Carter got out of his limousine in 1977 and walked hand in
hand with his wife Rosalynn for much of the distance down
Pennsylvania Avenue.
   President Reagan did not follow suit in 1981, remaining inside
his car.
   Bush's black limousine, which is being used for the first time,
has a bit less window area than Reagan's did, so that people will
have less chance of glimpsing him inside.
   Both before and since his Nov. 8 election, Bush has set a style
that is much more spontaneous than Reagan's. He likes to dine
spur-of-the-moment at local restaurants and has turned up a local
clothing or specialty shops.
   During the campaign Bush would occasionally stop his motorcade to
chat with farmers in their fields or schoolchildren by the road.
   On one occasion a rural restaurant got word that he might stop
for a meal and the proprietors became irate when he instead walked
into a mom-and-pop store next door and bought a couple slices of
pizza to go.
</TEXT>
