<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Ogonyok     01-18 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Ogonyok,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>One of Glasnost's Vanguard Publications Attacked by Top Newspapers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A trail-blazing Soviet magazine and its
editor-in-chief came under fire from the two most prominent
newspapers Wednesday, with one printing a letter that denounced the
weekly as ``scum'' bent on defaming Soviet history.
   Under President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, the magazine Ogonyok and
its chief, Vitaly Korotich, have become widely known and
increasingly controversial. Many of the sensational revelations made
by Soviet media under Gorbachev's policy of ``glasnost,'' or greater
openness, have appeared in Ogonyok.
   In this week's issue, the slick magazine with more 3 million
subscribers nationwide revealed Soviet suicide statistics for recent
years, denounced pollution and ran the latest episode of an expose
on corruption and cronyism under the late leader Leonid I. Brezhnev.
   Seven prominent cultural figures, in a letter to the Communist
Party daily newspaper Pravda, bitterly attacked Ogonyok, saying it
had gone ``far outside the bounds of literary arguments.''
   ``The magazine has taken upon itself the role of a kind of judge
on all questions of social life, politics, the economy, culture and
morals,'' they wrote.
   The seven grouped Ogonyok along with Soviet publications they
said are engaged in an ``unprecedented distortion of history, and
that revise the social achievements of the people.''
   They accused it of printing unverified hearsay and of deprecating
Soviet cultural icons such as poet Vladimir Mayakovsky and Nobel
literature laureate Mikhail Sholokhov, author of ``And Quiet Flows
the Don.''
   Those signing the letter, including conservative writers Valentin
Rasputin and Vasily Belov, said they supported ``with all their
souls'' the reform program undertaken by Gorbachev, but had become
alarmed by ``scum bubbling up on the crest of the mighty stream of
renovation.''
   Ogonyok has drawn tough and insulting criticism from other Soviet
media before, but Pravda gave great prominence to the letter,
printing it above the fold on its back page. That placement in the
party's top daily could indicate high-level irritation at Ogonyok
and its view of the Soviet past and present.
   Since the magazine has been one of the leaders in the drive for
franker discussion of social problems and a more honest
coming-to-grips with the country's past, any official attack on it
would be perceived by many Soviets as a signal of glasnost's limits.
   Izvestia, the government's afternoon newspaper, ran its own
correspondent's article that cast doubt on Ogonyok's credibility and
wondered aloud why Korotich was trying to run in a Moscow
neighborhood for a seat in a new national assembly, the Council of
People's Deputies, to be elected in March.
   The Ogonyok editor was seen by millions of U.S. television
viewers when CBS News anchorman Dan Rather visited with him in a
segment of the network's 1987 documentary on Soviet life, ``Seven
Days in May.'' Under glasnost, the magazine has been transformed
from a staid journal to a lively and popular magazine.
   Izvestia correspondent A. Stepovoi said he attended a Jan. 9
meeting of voters from Moscow's 21st electoral district called to
nominate Korotich to the new council. Ogonyok this week ran a story
on the same meeting, and said it was broken up by vocal right-wing
Russian nationalists extremists before the necessary quorum of 500
voters could assemble.
   Stepovoi, however, said not only members of the group known as
``Pamyat,'' or ``Memory,'' had caused the disorders, implying
Korotich supporters also were involved. He said the shouting march
began after organizers of the meeting announced they had failed to
assemble a quorum and that Korotich would hold a ``creative
meeting'' instead.
   Stepovoi also questioned why Korotich would want to run for the
new assembly from a Moscow district, since some Soviet social
organizations that are entitled to direct representation in the
assembly have already named Korotich as a candidate.
   ``What's the point?'' Stepovoi asked. ``As Ogonyok has reported,
Korotich was nominated as a candidate for people's deputy of the
U.S.S.R.'' He added: ``I can personally note that he's been chosen
by the magazine's collective.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
