<DOCNO> AP890118-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 2200EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Scotus-Bias     01-18 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Bias,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Hears Case that Could Affect Racial Bias Claims</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, in a case that could affect
on-the-job racial bias lawsuits nationwide, was urged Wednesday to
throw out discrimination charges against Alaska salmon canneries.
   Both sides in the case acknowledged that the industry _ a
seasonal business that relies on migrant workers drawn from remote
areas _ is hardly typical of U.S. commerce.
   But the case could provide standards for handling job
discrimination claims throughout the nation.
   Douglas M. Fryer, a lawyer for two companies based in Washington
state and Oregon, said employers in the case have done more than
their fair share of hiring minorities at canneries they operate in
Alaska.
   The companies ``should not be penalized'' under misplaced legal
theories adopted by a lower court, Fryer said.
   But Abraham A. Arditi, representing Filipinos, Alaska natives and
Asians, said the companies relegated the minority workers to the
lowest-paying jobs in a ``pervasive'' discriminatory system.
   He said the minority workers were capable of doing the
better-paying jobs. ``There's no question about the availability of
skilled personnel'' among the minority groups, Arditi said.
   The court's ruling, expected by July, could clear up questions
left unanswered by a ruling last June that said employees can use
statistical evidence to prove that some subjective decisions made by
their employers violate federal law. The court reinstated a suit by
a black woman who charged a Texas bank with discrimination.
   But that ruling failed to produce a majority of five votes for
any particular legal theory, and some observers believe it could
prove at best a mixed blessing for minority groups.
   In the Alaska case, non-whites charged discrimination by Wards
Cove Packing Co. Inc. of Seattle and Castle &amp; Cooke Inc. of Astoria,
Ore.
   The companies operate salmon canneries in remote areas of Alaska
during the summer salmon run.
   Non-whites say that while they hold nearly half the jobs at the
canneries, the jobs are racially stratified with whites dominating
in the higher-paying positions such as machinists, carpenters and
administrators.
   The companies said any racial divisions are for legitimate
business-related reasons. For example, they said most higher-paying
jobs require skill and prior experience that non-whites have
difficulty acquiring because they are seasonal workers from remote
regions of Alaska.
   Arditi, challenging that claim Wednesday, said nepotism is
pervasive in the canneries with whites hiring inexperienced youthful
relatives for higher-paying jobs.
   ``You have 14-year-olds, 15-year-olds, 16-year-olds who are hired
for upper-level jobs,'' Arditi said.
   Justice Antonin Scalia questioned whether that is proof of racial
bias. He offered the example of a family-owned business that hires
family members.
   One of the key issues in the case is the use of statistics to
demonstrate bias _ or the lack of it.
   Fryer argued that statistics showing non-whites holding most of
the lower-paying seasonal cannery worker jobs and fewer better
positions do not prove discrimination.
   The relevant figures are those showing that the companies hire
for the higher-ranking positions from a Pacific Northwest labor
market that is only 10 percent non-white, he said. The companies say
they filled those more desirable jobs with more than 20 percent
non-whites.
   A federal judge ruled in favor of the companies in 1983, throwing
out the suit. But the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reinstated
the suit in 1987 and ordered a full trial.
   The companies appealed to the Supreme Court to overrule the
appeals court.
   The Reagan administration is siding with the cannery owners. The
Justice Department said the 9th Circuit court placed too heavy a
burden on the companies to disprove the bias claims.
   The case is Wards Cove vs. Atonio, 87-1387.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
