<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 2203EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-MedicalFraud     01-18 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Medical Fraud,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>FTC Acts Against Doctor Who Promised to Improve Odds of Pregnancy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Trade Commission has filed consumer
fraud charges against a Virginia physician who told patients his
treatments would increase their chances of becoming pregnant, the
FTC said Wednesday.
   The complaint alleges that Dr. Cecil Jacobson, director of the
Reproductive Genetic Center of Vienna, Va., told his patients his
hormone-injection treatments had resulted in full-term, successful
pregnancies for more than 80 percent of his patients.
   In fact, no more than 40 percent of those who received repeated
injections of Human Chorionic Gonadotropin, or HCG, became pregnant,
according to FTC Chairman Daniel Oliver.
   While HCG slightly enhances the odds of a woman becoming
pregnant, the hormone is more commonly found simply as a chemical
biproduct of pregnancy, usually showing up in urine tests, according
to the FTC.
   In all, Jacobson treated ``several hundred women'' who lost from
$400,000 to more than $2 million, Oliver said.
   The FTC will be seeking a return of some or all fees collected
from each patient Jacobson treated, Oliver said.
   In addition, the FTC has also asked the U.S. District Court for
Eastern Virginia to issue a preliminary injunction prohibiting
Jacobson from making further such claims.
   Several of Jacobson's patients have also filed civil suits
against him. They are seeking recovery of fees; some also want
unspecified damages.
   While the treatments caused no physical harm, a 38-year-old
patient of Jacobson's was told by another physician that she had
greatly diminished her chances of becoming pregnant because the
several years she spent using Jacobson's program had taken her
closer to the end of her fertility cycle, an FTC official said.
   Jacobson was not immediately available to comment. His license to
practice medicine has not been suspended, Oliver said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
