<FIRST>r i AM-Bangladesh-Crash     01-18 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladesh-Crash,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two More Die In Hospitals, Toll Now 119 In Sunday Train Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two people injured in a weekend train
collision died in a hospital Wednesday, bringing the death toll in
Bangladesh's worst railway accident to 119, hospital officials said.
   Doctors said 116 people were still hospitalized for treatment of
injuries suffered in the accident in central Bangladesh on Sunday.
Forty-seven of them suffered arm and leg fractures and may be
crippled, doctors said.
   The doctors, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said several
will require limb amputations.
   The crash occurred when a passenger train traveling about 50 mph
rammed head-on into a mail train outside the village of Maizdi Khan,
16 miles north of Dhaka.
   At least 100 people died at the scene and 19 others have died in
hospitals. Officials said at least 1,000 people were injured in the
collision.
   The government has put the death toll at 82, but its count is
generally considered too low due to bureacratic delays in counting
the dead. Dhaka newspapers placed the toll at more than 200.
