<HEAD>Bush to Start Work Early in Day</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Inaugural Rdp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater,
indicating at least one way that George Bush will differ from Ronald
Reagan, advised reporters Wednesday that ``we will start earlier in
the day.''
   Fitzwater, who has been President Reagan's chief spokesman since
early 1987 and will continue in that capacity when Bush becomes
president, said ``we will have a lot of earlier coverage events.''
   Bush, he added, ``is going to start his work schedule at 8 a.m.
and he also has breakfast at 7:15 a.m. _ and things like that.''
   Reagan has been a habitual 9-to-5 man, throughout his public and
private career, and the early word on the Bush schedule indicates
longer hours.
