<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 2115EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SoccerTrial     01-18 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soccer Trial,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor: Convictions Needed In '85 Soccer Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor on Wednesday urged a judge
to convict 15 Britons, two Belgian police officers and a former
soccer official on charges stemming from a 1985 stadium riot that
killed 39 soccer fans.
   ``The sentence should be an example,'' Prosecutor Pierre Erauw
said during the third and final day of his closing argument.
   On trial are 26 Britons, two Belgian state police officers, the
Brussels mayor and deputy mayor, two European soccer officials and
Albert Roosens, former secretary-general of the Belgian soccer
federation.
   Erauw said two of the 26 British suspects should be acquitted for
lack of proof and that he had ``reservations'' about eight other
British cases. He also asked that one case be severed from the other
British cases because the suspect is jailed in Britain on an
unrelated matter.
   The judge's decision is expected in March. If convicted of
involuntary manslaughter, the British suspects face up to 10 years
in jail, although Erauw has called for terms of only up to four
years.
   President Judge Peirre Verlynde still can override Erauw's
recommendations.
   However, a defense lawyer said convictions are unlikely against
the 10 suspects against whom the evidence was questioned by Erauw.
   ``He is effectively recommending the (complete acquittal) for
those defendants against whom he says guilt has not been established
to his satisfaction,'' said Sir Harry Livermore of Liverpool.
   But Erauw said two Belgian state police officials and Roosens
should be convicted. They face up to two years in jail.
   On Monday, he cited inadequate organization of the match by
Roosens, who was secretary-general of the Belgian soccer federation
at the time of the tragedy.
   He also blamed state police officers Johan Mahieu and Michel
Kensier for inadequate security measures and failing to act to stem
the rioting.
   On Tuesday, he said the Brussels mayor, his alderman for sports
matters and two officials of the Union of European Football
Associations should not be sentenced.
   The 26 Britons are accused of instigating Europe's worst-ever
soccer riot. The violence broke out on May 29, 1985, before a game
between Juventus Turin of Italy and FC Liverpool of England, the
final match of the European Champions' Cup at Brussels' Heysel
Stadium.
   The Britons were charged based on videotapes and photographs
taken of the rioting, which began when British soccer fans charged
into a neighboring section of the stands filled mostly with Italian
fans. About 500 people were hurt and 39, including 34 Italians, were
killed during the ensuing stampede.
   The British defendants are on trial after their government,
seeking to come to grips with soccer hooliganism, agreed to
extradite them. They are expected to be allowed to return home to
await the end of the trial that began Oct. 15.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
