<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon     01-18 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanon's Two Governments Try To Avoid Permanent Division of Nation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The heads of Lebanon's two rival
governments _ one Moslem, one Christian _ agreed to work with the
Arab League to try to prevent the split in the country from becoming
permanent, officials said Wednesday.
   Newspapers meanwhile said Wednesday that a commander from the
mainstream Shiite Moslem Amal militia was killed by Israeli tank
fire in south Lebanon and that a Syrian peacekeeping soldier was
killed in cross fire from an inter-Shiite clash in south Beirut.
   Lebanon has been torn by civil war for nearly 13 years. A
4-month-old political crisis threatens to solidify Lebanon's
partition into sectarian cantons.
   Salim Hoss, the acting prime Minister and head of the Moslem
Cabinet, told The Associated Press he will go to Tunis to confer
with a special committee of the league on Jan. 28 on how to settle
the political crisis here.
   Army commander Gen. Michel Aoun, who heads the Christian Cabinet,
``welcomed the Arab League's interest in the Lebanese situation and
expressed readiness to cooperate with the committee,'' a political
source in Christian east Beirut said on condition of anonymity.
   The office of Parliament Speaker Hussein Husseini announced that
Husseini will also meet the committee in the Tunisian capital this
month.
   Hoss, a Sunni Moslem, and Husseini, a Shiite, were invited by
Kuwaiti envoys to meet the committee when they visited Damascus,
Syria, on Tuesday.
   The Christian source said Aoun ``would decide on the level of his
representation at a meeting with the committee after he formally
receives an invitation, which is expected later this week.''
   The league committee, created last Thursday in Tunis at a meeting
of Arab foreign ministers, is headed by Kuwait's foreign minister,
Sheik Sabah Ahmed Sabah.
   The committee of the 22-nation league will try to resolve the
Lebanese crisis and facilitate the election of a new president to
succeed Amin Gemayel, whose term expired Sept. 22.
   A squabbling Parliament failed to elect a successor to Gemayel,
and he chose Aoun to head an interim military Cabinet. Moslem
leaders backed by Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, refused
to recognize Aoun's new authority and backed a Cabinet under Hoss, a
leftover of Gemayel's splintered government.
   A communique from Amal leader Nabih Berri said that Amal's head
of operations in south Lebanon, Nabil Hijazi, was killed by a shell
from an Israeli tank Tuesday as he was leading a reconnaissance
mission near Sojod, north of Israel's self-proclaimed security zone.
   Berri's communique, published by all Beirut newspapers, said
Hijazi died while ``gathering intelligence information on the
security zone'' and proclaimed him a ``martyr.''
   The pro-Syrian Amal advocates guerrilla warfare to dislodge
Israel from the border enclave it carved out in south Lebanon in
1985.
   The leftist Beirut newspaper As-Safir and the independent
An-Nahar said a Syrian soldier was killed Tuesday in cross fire
between Amal and the Iranian-backed Hezbollah organization in the
Bir Hasan residential district on Beirut's southern limits.
   The Syrian military refused to comment on the report.
   Amal and Hezbollah are struggling for control of the 1 million
Shiites who make up the largest sect among Lebanon's 4 million
inhabitants.
</TEXT>
