<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Plane     01-18 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Plane,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Plane No Parade Secret Any More</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Inaugural Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Add one more to the list of things that can't
be kept secret in Washington.
   When a float that looks like a Navy boat rounds the corner of
15th Street and Pennsylvania Avenue in Friday's inaugural parade,
newly sworn-in President Bush is supposed to get one of the
surprises of his life.
   Navy men Wednesday draped black plastic over the float which is
topped with a newly painted Grumman Avenger aircraft like the one
that Bush was shot down in during World War II.
   But the men acknowledged the plane was no longer much of a
secret. There was at least one news story published about it, and
photographers were attracted to the shrouded object outside the
Smithsonian Air &amp; Space Museum.
   The idea, according to parade organizers, was to surprise Bush
with the aircraft and a dozen men from his old Navy torpedo squadron.
   The wingspan is so wide, Bush could almost reach out and touch it
from his reviewing stand, said a Navy officer watching over the
plane.
   He said trees along the parade route had to be trimmed to get the
plane through, and a couple of reviewing stands had to be moved back
to accommodate its 54-foot wingspan.
   The wings could be folded back, birdlike, but the officer said
parade officials wanted to be sure it could make it along the route
in full flying position.
   Bush was rescued from the Pacific Ocean on Sept. 2, 1944, after
he bailed out of his flaming Grumman Avenger torpedo bomber over the
Bonin Islands, 600 miles south of Japan. He won the Distinguished
Flying Cross for heroism during the bombing raid. His two crew
members were killed.
   The plane in the parade, built in the 1940s by General Motors on
a Grumman design, was flown to Washington after it was spotted in a
field by a World War II veteran working with the USS Yorktown
Association in Mt. Pleasant, S.C.
   Veterans from the Yorktown arranged for the plane to be in the
parade and also tracked down members of Bush's old torpedo squadron,
Air Group VT 51, to ride along with it, said Joseph Sharkey,
assistant director of the veterans group.
   About 10,000 Avengers were built, according to Grumman historian
Lois Louisolo, with 45 of the antique aircraft still registered to
fly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
