<FIRST>u i AM-Yugoslavia     01-18 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Candidates for Premier Chosen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Croatian and a Serbian were chosen
Wednesday as the candidates to replace Premier Branko Mikulic, whose
government resigned Dec. 30 because it could not end the economic
crisis.
   Ante Markovic, member of Croatia's collective presidency, and
Borisav Jovic, speaker of Serbia's parliament, were named by the
Socialist Alliance, a Communist-led mass organization.
   Mikulic was the first premier to resign since the Communist Party
gained control at the end of World War II. Economic problems he was
unable to solve include high unemployment, an annual inflation rate
of 250 percent and a $21 billion foreign debt.
   Yugoslavia's nine-member collective presidency was expected to
choose the new premier on Thursday.
   Markovic, 64, is an electrical engineer and successful
businessman who has advocated market-oriented economic reforms
coupled with political change. He has the support of Slovenia and
Croatia, the most economically developed and Westward-looking of the
six republic.
   Jovic, 60, is an economists and close associate of Slobodan
Milosevic, chief of the Serbian Communist Party. He is believed to
have the support of poorer regions that fear economic reform would
close money-losing plants, causing mass layoffs.
   The nation's living standard has dwindled to half what it was
when President Tito died in 1980, causing widespread discontent
among workers. A record 1,400 strikes were reported last year.
</TEXT>
