<FIRST>r i AM-Greece-Terrorism     01-18 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-Terrorism,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Shot By Terrorists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DINA KYRIAKIDOU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gunman wounded a Supreme Court prosecutor
on Wednesday, the second major attack on a leading Greek magistrate
in eight days, police said.
   Panayiotis Tarasouleas, 66, was shot three times in the legs as
he was getting into his car at 8:05 p.m. outside his home in the
northern suburb of Maroussi, said Giorgos Vassilopoulos, chief of
the Athens security police.
   Vassilopoulos said the leftist November 17 terrorist group
claimed responsibility for the shooting in leaflets found at the
scene.
   ``The prosecutor and wife were going out for the evening and, as
they approached their car, three men accosted them and one shot him
in the legs,'' Vassilopoulos said. The three fled.
   Tarasouleas was in stable condition at the Athens Medical Center,
said Dr. Constantinos Economou, the hospital director.
   November 17 has claimed responsibility for 12 killings. The group
is named for the day in 1973 when troops crushed a student rebellion
against the 1967-74 military dictatorship.
   November 17 said it was responsible for the death in June of U.S.
Navy Capt. William E. Nordeen, the military attache at the U.S.
Embassy in Athens.
   The organization first became known in 1975, when it claimed
responsibility for the assassination of Richard Welch, the CIA
station chief in Greece.
   In a June 10 attack, three gunmen wounded Constantinos
Androulidakis, 52, a prominent Athens investigating magistrate, as
he was leaving his home for work.
   Androulidakis, known for his tough stand on terrorism, was shot
twice in the legs and once in the arm. He was in stable condition
Wednesday.
   The previously unknown ``Popular Anti-State Groups For Fiery
Action'' claimed responsibility for the attack.
</TEXT>
