<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Iraq     01-18 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Iraq,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Denies Threat to Iraq, Summons German Envoy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governments of Israel and Iraq both denied
reports on Wednesday that Israel threatened to bomb an Iraqi factory
outside Baghdad if it manufactured biological weapons.
   They were responding to ABC-TV reports out of Washington earlier
Wednesday saying that Israel warned Iraq through the U.S. government
that it was planning a strike against such a facility.
   The official Iraqi News Agency quoted an Iraqi Foreign Ministry
official as saying that Iraq does not produce such weaopns.
   ``If we receive such a threat, Iraq will reject it strongly,''
the agency, monitored in Nicosia, Cyprus, quoted the unidentified
official as saying.
   Motti Amihai, spokesman for the Israeli Foreign Ministry, said:
``There is no truth to that information that we did threaten Iraq.''
He also said Israel did not ask the United States or any other
country to pass along any such warning.
   Amihai said Israel was studying the reports that the Iraqi
government was developing biological weapons. ``If this information
is true, we are facing here one more proof of the irresponsibility
of the Iraqi government.''
   Amihai refused to comment on Israel's knowledge of the Iraqi
plant. Israeli sources said this month that Iraq is on the verge of
developing biological weapons, but has not yet produced any.
   When asked if Israel would consider an air raid similar to the
1981 attack that destroyed an Iraqi nuclear facility, Amihai replied:
   ``One should bear in mind that Israel is very sensitive about its
security. ... We will take all measures necessary to ensure the
security of the state of Israel.''
   He was referring to Israel's June 1981 air strike that destroyed
an Iraqi nuclear research facility at Tuwaitha outside Baghdad.
Israel contended that Iraq would use enriched uranium from the
reactor to produce nuclear weapons.
</TEXT>
