<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     01-18 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain In Texas, Snow Around Great Lakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rain flooded streets Wednesday in Houston, Texas, and snow
was scattered around most of the Great Lakes.
   Elsewhere, the sky was sunny and temperatures were near
seasonably normal levels over much of the nation through midday.
   Occasional thunderstorms dropped more than 4 inches of rain
during the morning at Houston, flooding some streets and stalling
cars.
   Rain and thunderstorms were scattered from the Texas Gulf Coast
and eastern Texas across Louisiana, southern Mississippi and
southwestern Alabama by early afternoon.
   During the six hours up to 1 p.m. EST, 2.20 inches of rain fell
at Ellington Air Force Base near Houston, and 1.06 inches fell at
Alexandria, La.
   Snow showers were scattered from northwestern New York state
across northern Lower Michigan, Upper Michigan, Wisconsin and
northeastern Minnesota. Upper Michigan got up to 4 inches of snow
during the night and into the morning.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 4
degrees above zero at Gunnison, Colo., to 81 at Miami. Wednesday
morning's low temperature in the lower 48 states was 23 degrees
below zero at Gunnison.
   For Thursday, snow showers were forecast from northeastern New
York state across northern New England, with snow changing to rain
along the central coast of New England. Snow showers also were
forecast from northeastern Minnesota across Upper Michigan. Rain and
occasional thundershowers were forecast over eastern and central
Texas.
   Highs in the 20s and 30s were predicted over northern New
England, northeastern New York state, the Great Lakes, the upper
Mississippi Valley, much of the northern Plains, the Rockies and the
Great Basin of Nevada and western Utah; in the 40s over southern New
England and New Jersey, the central Plains and the northern Pacific
Coast; in the 70s over the Florida Peninsula, the lower Texas Gulf
Coast and from southern Arizona across the southern coast of
California; and in the 50s and 60s over the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
