<DOCNO> AP890118-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 2108EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NuclearPerformance     01-18 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Performance,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>MIT Study: Nuclear Plants Work Better Overseas Because Of Amity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American nuclear plants perform worse than foreign
ones because of a lack of cooperation among U.S. utilities and
hostility between them and regulators, says a Massachusetts
Institute of Technology study.
   ``What the (U.S.) utilities don't seem to have, typically, is a
culture of reaching out to one another on a company-by-company
basis,'' said professor Michael Golay, a nuclear engineer and one of
the report's authors.
   The report, financed by the U.S. Department of Energy, MIT and
two electric companies, was to be released Thursday in the latest
issue of the school magazine Technology Review.
   The study looked at plants in Japan, Sweden, France, Switzerland,
West Germany and the United States from 1975 to 1984. In the United
States it examined the nearly 200 light water reactors producing
more than 300 megawatts.
   The average plant in the United States produced energy less than
60 percent of the time, while most of the other countries at the end
of the period were at 75 percent, said MIT professor Kent Hansen,
the project's chief author.
   ``One of our conjectures is that all elements concerned with
nuclear power have not been able to work together to solve nuclear
problems,'' Hansen said.
   Golay said that when Japan decided to improve the available of
nuclear-generated power, ``they did it by making it a national goal.
The U.S. has tried to do some of that, but so far, in terms of
availability, it has failed.''
   ``What is unique to the United States is a highly antagonistic
relationship between regulators and utilities,'' the report said.
   ``In other countries, relationships between regulators and
utilities become strained at times, but all parties report that
communication is open and forthright, with no group withholding
information or acting secretly or vindictively. ... Nor do
politicians attempt to interfere in regulatory decisions.''
   Golay said much of the hostility ``is the consequence of
operating in a goldfish bowl. In other countries they operate behind
closed doors.''
   Nuclear industry spokesman Scott Peters agreed with the
assessment of 60 percent efficiency. But in a telephone interview
from the U.S. Council for Energy Awareness in Washington, he said,
``We're getting better.''
   As for cooperation among utilities, after the 1979 accident at
Three Mile Island in Pennsylvania, utilities set up a computer link
to share information, and the industry also has established the
Institute of Nuclear Power Operators.
   He noted that in France, where nuclear power facilities are
considered outstanding, the government owns the utility.
   ``That's a fairly simple relationship. Ours is more complex. The
Nuclear Regulatory Commission is careful not to get too close to the
industry. There's an arm's length (relationship), as it should be,''
he said.
   But he added, ``I don't think it's contributing to inefficency.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890118-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 2108EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SaggingPlywood     01-18 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sagging Plywood,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Building Industry Troubled By Faulty Fire-Retardant Plywood Roofs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARLENE E. SUPERVILLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire-retardant plywood used to build roofs on
thousands of multiple-family dwellings nationwide can weaken and
collapse after prolonged exposure to the sun's heat, building
industry officials said Wednesday.
   ``It really is not the type of problem where people will have to
worry about their roofs caving in on them at night when they're
sleeping,'' said Marshall Frost, a civil engineer and president of
Frost, Christenson and Associates in Florham Park.
   But builders say the fire-retardant plywood weakens after five to
six years and starts to sag, and could collapse under the weight of
heavy snow.
   Fire-retardant plywood is marketed by several companies under
various brand names. Each company uses a different compound to
impregnate the wood to resist fire.
   The treated plywood has been used for roofing for more then a
decade in multiple-family dwellings, to keep fire from bypassing
firewalls and spreading easily across the roofs of adjacent
apartments, but officials only recently realized there was a problem.
   The American Plywood Association of Tacoma, Wash., said it first
learned of the problem in 1986 when it began to get complaints from
engineers.
   ``These were totally different than any other thing we'd ever
heard about,'' said Steve Zylkowski, an APA scientist. ``We didn't
know what to attribute the problem to.''
   Inspectors found the problem was a chemical reaction in the fire
retardant chemicals caused by the sun's heat, Zylkowski said. The
chemical reaction produces an acid that weakens the wood over
several years.
   A committee formed by the National Association of Home Builders
will meet Sunday in Atlanta to discuss a solution.
   The New Jersey Builders Association and the national plywood
group are advising builders to refrain from using fire-retardant
wood until researchers at the National Forest Products Association
laboratory in Madison, Wis., can determine what chemicals are
causing the wood deterioration.
   ``Until the industry comes up with meaningful controls to control
their problems, we will not recommend use of their products,''
Zylkowski said. ``If they do have a problem, we recommend strongly
that they get assurance from the treatment companies that the
problem will not recur.''
   Meanwhile, builders suggest annual inspections of roofs.
   Many suppliers and chemical manufacturers are working with the
forest products association to develop a testing method for the
fire-retardant chemicals, said Susan LeVan, a researcher for the
group.
   Ms. LeVan said 6,000 specimens of plywood are being tested.
   ``We hope to be able to prove that if you know certain lengths of
time that the wood is at elevated temperatures, we will be able to
predict the life of the wood,'' she said.
   The next problem is who should pay for replacing faulty materials
which have been used in thousands of dwellings.
   ``That's a $64,000 question,'' Frost said. ``Somewhere along the
line, the courts will figure out who is responsible to fix it. There
are a lot of discussions going on in the industry. I think the
industry will find a solution which might require some changes.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
