<HEAD>Bomb Explodes Outside Courthouse; Man Shot to Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two masked gunmen killed a store
clerk and a car bomb blew up outside a courthouse in separate
attacks on Wednesday, police said.
   The clerk was slain in Belfast's Smithfield Market area and was
dead on arrival at Royal Victoria Hospital, said a Royal Ulster
Constabulary spokesman.
   Police would not identify the victim, but Press Association, the
domestic British news agency, said he was Ian Catney, 25, a Roman
Catholic who was working in his mother's store.
   There was no claim of responsibility for the shooting or the
bombing.
   The blast occurred outside the high-security Crumlin Road
courthouse. There were no injuries, said a spokesman for the Royal
Ulster Constabulary, requesting anonymity. Damage was slight, he
said.
   The bomb had been placed in a hijacked car taken from a family
held hostage in the Springfield Road area of mainly Roman Catholic
west Belfast, he said.
