<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka-Accident     01-18 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka-Accident,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Acts After School Bus-Train Disaster</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a disastrous train-school bus
collision, the president on Wednesday ordered gates installed at all
758 rail crossings in Sri Lanka and guards posted at all times, a
spokesman said.
   Presidential spokesman Festus Perera said that at a Cabinet
meeting, President Ranasinghe Premadasa specified that the gate
installation be completed by Monday.
   Wailing relatives claimed most of the dead on Wednesday from the
collision in southern Sri Lanka that killed at least 45 people and
injured 68, most of them children.
   Other kin searched hospitals hoping to find their loved ones
alive.
   M.S. Amarasiri, chief minister of the southern provincial
council, said funerals were scheduled to take place Thursday. He
said most homes, shops and vehicles flew white flags on Wednesday to
mourn the dead.
   An express train slammed into a schoolbus carrying about 120
passengers Tuesday at an unprotected rail crossing near Ahungalla,
about 50 miles south of Colombo, police and witnesses said.
   The government said 41 people were killed outright and four died
at hospitals. Authorities said most were children ranging in age
from 5 to 15. Six critically injured people were brought to the
capital for emergency surgery.
   Relatives crowded into government-run hospitals in Galle and
Balapitiya, where the dead and injured were taken.
   Premadasa's wife, Hema, visited the accident site and hospitals
Wednesday, going from bed to bed to comfort the injured and console
relatives of the dead.
   Many victims were mutilated beyond recognition. Nurses asked
families to check clothing for identification.
   Police searched bloodstained schoolbooks and schoolbags for clues
to identify victims.
   The school bus picked up children and teachers from four schools
in Amblangoda on Tuesday and headed toward Urgasmanhandiya, about 10
miles away.
   The driver tried to cross the tracks as the train was approaching
the crossing but the bus engine apparently stalled, police and
witnesses said.
   Five children sitting on bus steps jumped to safety.
   The train, going about 40 mph, hit the bus and knocked it about
150 feet down the track, witnesses said.
   The bus driver escaped with minor cuts and bruises, police said.
   No one on the train was hurt, they reported.
</TEXT>
