<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua     01-18 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>17 Killed In Sandinista-Contra Clashes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government troops clashed with rebels
at least 20 times Jan. 9-16, and at least 17 people were killed,
military sources said Wednesday.
   The fighting was in the southwestern provinces of Boaco,
Chontales and Rio San Juan. The area has been the focus of activity
by the U.S.-backed rebels, known as Contras, since the rebels and
the leftist Sandinista government signed a tentative cease-fire
agreement last March.
   At least 13 rebels and four soldiers were killed and three
soldiers were wounded, the sources said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   The Defense Ministry, meanwhile, accused Honduran troops of
shooting toward the border post of Murupuchi, in northern Nueva
Segovia province, on Sunday. It mentioned no casualties.
   Nicaragua says the post is harassed almost daily by Honduran
troops.
   Col. Manuel Suarez Benavides, chief spokesman for the Honduran
armed forces, called the allegations ``absolutely false'' and said
they ``apparently form part of a new Nicaraguan propaganda offensive
against Honduras.''
   ``It also is completely false that Honduran troops have
repeatedly harassed Sandinista forces in Murupuchi,'' he told The
Associated Press.
   A series of Sandinista-Contra meetings after the March 23 signing
of the temporary truce failed to define terms for a permanent
agreement. Talks broke off on June 9.
   Fighting declined sharply after the signing, which came a month
after the United States cut off military aid to the Contras. Most of
the rebels moved back to base camps in Honduras, but sporadic
fighting continues.
</TEXT>
