<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 2130EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Quayle 1stLd-Writethru a0729 01-18 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0729,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says His Treatment by Reagan to Be Model for Dealing with Quayle</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Inaugural Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 8 grafs with remarks to disabled people</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President-elect Dan Quayle praised
President-elect Bush on Wednesday for ``a capacity to lead'' and in
return received Bush's public commitment that he will be included in
the workings of the new administration.
   Quayle, who has remained largely out of sight during the
transition period, spoke briefly to members of the Republican
National Committee which was meeting in Washington amid the
inaugural festivities.
   He then listened as Bush described both his own treatment as vice
president under Ronald Reagan and his plans for dealing the same way
with Quayle.
   ``I don't believe I'd be standing here as president-elect of the
United States if it hadn't been for the way President Reagan treated
me as vice president,'' Bush told the luncheon crowd at a Washington
hotel.
   Turning then to Quayle, Bush said, ``As for my vice president,
Dan Quayle, I'm excited about working with him, and what we're going
to do is use exactly the same formula that the Reagan-Bush team had.
And he will be included.''
   ``He will do specific assignments that will develop in time,''
Bush said. ``He will take on special missions. He will have full
access to the president of the United States and he is going to be
an outstanding vice president of the United States.''
   Quayle praised Bush as ``a person of immense capabilities,
integrity, knowledge and a capacity to lead. ... There isn't a
better man to lead this nation forward in the challenges ahead than
George Bush.''
   The former Indiana senator spoke briefly of the administration he
will be a part of, promising to ``maintain our commitment to the
basic philosophical principles that brought us here.''
   But he also said they must face ``the challenges of tomorrow head
on.'' He cited the area of defense, ``where we will have to do more
with less, we will have to be smarter.''
   Later, at a ceremony at the Department of Health and Human
Services, Quayle told an audience of about 1,000 disabled and
handicapped Americans that the new administration's commitment to
them is ``deep and it is wide.'' The reception was hosted by Access
to Opportunity, a bipartisan advocacy group for the disabled.
   The vice president-elect pledged that he and Bush will work to
assure that the disabled will be ``included in the mainstream of
American life.''
   ``For too long, they've been left out, but they're not going to
be left out any more,'' he said. ``I can tell you this commitment is
deep and it is wide.''
   ``Without aggressive public and private support disabled people
cannot achieve their dreams of independence, gain full control over
their lives and integrate into the mainstream of American life,''
Quayle said.
   He said the Bush administration will ask the private sector ``to
aggressively hire disabled people'' and will educate employers about
the disabled and let them know that ``disabled people perform above
the average.''
   He also said they would work with Congress to eliminate obstacles
that discourage disabled people from working and support initiatives
to train the disabled for jobs.
   ``Today, I reaffirm support for the cause of the disabled. We
want to inaugurate an era of new hope and opportunity for all
Americans.
   ``It is not only the right thing to do, it is also the smart
thing to do,'' he said.
</TEXT>
