<HEAD>Jury Selection Begins in Sniper Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `The jurors..., with two grafs to UPDATE with
details of jury selection; picks up 8th graf: `Defense lawyer ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jury selection began Wednesday in the
trial of one of two men charged in 11 sniper attacks on isolated
homes in the Blackstone Valley north of here.
   Jurors were told the trial could take six weeks and include as
many as 60 witnesses.
   Jury selection began after Superior Court Judge Dominic F. Cresto
denied a motion by Peter T. Trepanier's attorneys to dismiss the
charges because of lengthy trial delays. He also dismissed a defense
motion to delay the trial still further because of alleged
prejudicial pretrial publicity.
   A group of about 70 potential jurors filled the courtroom as Eva
Marie Mancuso, assistant attorney general, read a list of the dozens
of witnesses who could be called to testify.
   Trepanier, 25, and a second defendant, Russell J. Ducharme II,
24, face 39 charges each, including arson and assault with intent to
commit murder. The charges stem from a series of attacks on isolated
homes in the Woonsocket area in December 1986 and January 1987.
   Both men, if convicted, could face maximum sentences of life in
prison.
   Six potential jurors Wednesday were asked if they were familar
with any of the witnesses or if they had ever been victims of crimes.
   The prospective jurors also were questioned about whether any of
the extensive publicity about the case would color their judgment.
Two people were dismissed, but for unrelated personal reasons.
   Defense lawyers, citing pretrial publicity, tried unsuccessfully
last summer to have the trial moved from Providence.
   Trepanier, of Burrillville, surrendered to police in October
1987, 10 months after the last shooting was reported in North
Smithfield.
   Ducharme, of Smithfield, was arrested and charged the next day.
His trial is set to begin March 13.
