<FIRST>r a AM-Bundy-Appeals     01-18 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bundy-Appeals,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bundy Appeal Filed; Hearing Scheduled</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bundy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE CITY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys who want to save Theodore Bundy
from Florida's electric chair next week filed a Circuit Court appeal
Wednesday, and a hearing was scheduled for Thursday morning, court
officials said.
   ``They've raised three claims for relief,'' said Carolyn
Snurkowski, chief death penalty attorney for Florida's attorney
general office.
   Two of the arguments deal with Bundy's murder convictions in the
deaths of two sorority sisters at Florida State University, Ms.
Snurkowski said. The third deals with Bundy's mental state.
   Bundy, 42, is scheduled to die Tuesday for the February 1978
murder of Kimberly Leach, a 12-year-old Lake City girl.
   His lawyers say the question of Bundy's sanity is not settled
though the U.S. Supreme Court refused Tuesday to consider the issue
in the Lake City case.
   The lawyers say that Bundy's two other Florida cases should be
linked to the Lake City case on the question of his sanity. Bundy,
42, also is under death sentences for fatally bludgeoning two
Florida State University sorority sisters three weeks before Leach
was killed.
   In 1979, Bundy was declared legally sane to stand trial for the
sorority murders. That ruling was used recently by appeals courts to
reject Bundy's claim that he is insane and should not be executed
for the Leach murder.
   On Dec. 12, U.S. District Judge William Zloch in Fort Lauderdale
reopened the sanity issue in the sorority case, saying he would hear
evidence as early as Monday.
   Bundy's lawyers say that decision leaves Bundy's sanity in doubt
and that he should not be executed until it is resolved.
   Defense lawyers and prosecutors have asked for a delay in the
federal court hearing while they deal with the death warrant.
</TEXT>
