<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 1929EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia     01-18 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leftist Guerrillas Kill 13 Members Of A Judicial Commission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER BAENA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspected leftist guerrillas armed with
sticks of dynamite and automatic weapons ambushed a judicial
commission Wednesday, killing two judges and 11 other people, the
army said.
   Two police officers were wounded in the attack near
Barrancabermeja, a port city on the Magdalena River for oil
shipments, 160 miles northeast of the capital, military authorities
said.
   The panel was investigating the October 1987 disappearance of 17
merchants along with more than $235,000 in goods.
   The commission consisted of the judges, 35-year-old Mariela
Morales and 40-year-old Pablo Beltran; two secretaries, nine
judicial police officers and two drivers. The two survivors arrived
in Barrancabermeja, Colombia's largest eastern city, where they told
authorities of the attack.
   ``It is an unprecedented attack on investigators who did not
constitute an attack force,'' said Carlos Eduardo Lozano, director
of criminal judges.
   Army and police reports said the attackers exploded dynamite
buried under a road where two vehicles carrying the judicial
commission passed by, then sprayed the group with automatic weapons
fire.
   The two wounded officers were taken to the hospital of the
state-owned oil company Ecopetrol, where officials said they were
out of danger.
   Gen. Yanine Daz, commander of the army's Second Division, said
from Bucaramanga that the guerrillas belonged to the Revoloutionary
Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC, a communist group. But police
blamed the attack on the Army of National Liberation, or ELN, a
group inspired by Cuban leader Fidel Castro.
   Both groups operate in the region, known as the central Magdalena
River area. Ultra-right paramilitary groups claiming to fight
subversives and leftist collaborators have also been known to
operate in the area.
   It is the first time leftist guerrillas were blamed for killing
judicial officials, although drug traffickers have killed Supreme
Court magistrates and judges investigating drug-related crimes.
</TEXT>
