<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 2132EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Reagan-Archives     01-18 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan-Archives,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Order Could Shield White House Papers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's successors would have the
power to shield portions of the papers of the Reagan presidency from
disclosure, under an executive order issued by the president
Wednesday.
   The order spells out procedures to be followed by Reagan and
other former presidents in claiming executive privilege with regard
to their presidential papers.
   These claims would be subject to review by the archivist, but the
archivist would be bound by any instructions given him by the
incumbent president unless otherwise instructed by court order.
   Thus, if Reagan asserted executive privilege to keep some of his
papers under wraps, and a later president supported him, the
archivist would be prohibited from disclosing them unless ordered by
a court.
   The order arises out of protracted litigation over claims of
executive privilege by former President Nixon with regard to his
papers.
   A Justice Department opinion in 1986 said the archivist is a
presidential appointee and must comply with the president's claim of
privilege, even when it is invoked in support of a former president.
That opinion also said an incumbent president was bound to support
an executive privilege claim by a former president, except in rare
cases when it would conflict with his constitutional duties.
   The opinion touched off criticism in Congress, where some
lawmakers said it would let Reagan and future presidents keep their
own papers under seal years after they have left office.
   Reagan's order establishes procedures governing the assertion of
executive privilege by both present and former presidents.
   It provides that when the archivist decides on release of papers
of a former president, he would notify both the former president and
the incumbent, identifying any materials he thinks might be subject
to executive privilege.
   The incumbent and former presidents, however, would be free to
assert executive privilege with regard to any papers, whether or not
identified by the archivist.
   The archivist would be free to release the papers if he did not
receive a claim of executive privilege within 30 days.
   If he received such a claim from the incumbent president, he
would be prohibited from disclosing the records unless directed to
do so by the president or a final court order.
   When he received a claim of privilege by a former president, the
archivist would consult with the attorney general and the counsel to
the president and then make a ``determination as to whether to honor
the former president's claim of privilege or instead to disclose the
presidential records notwithstanding the claim of privilege.''
   ``Any determination ... that executive privilege shall not be
invoked by the incumbent president shall not prejudice the
archivist's determination with respect to the former president's
claim of privilege,'' the order said.
   However, it said, ``In making the determination ... the archivist
shall abide by any instructions given him by the incumbent president
or his designee unless otherwise directed by a final court order.''
   All presidents before Nixon took their papers with them when they
left office, but under a 1978 law Reagan's documents and those of
his successors will become public property. That law requires the
archivist to decide which papers to withhold and which to make
public 12 years after a president leaves office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890118-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 2135EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-SouthKorea     01-18 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-South Korea,3500</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Korea Agrees to Buy More US Wine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea will drop barriers to imports of
U.S. wine and U.S. vintners have dropped their plea to President
Reagan for action against the barriers, U.S. Trade Representative
Clayton Yeutter announced Wednesday.
   ``The agreement opens an important new market for American wine
at an early stage in that market's development and it assures that
our wine industry can compete fairly with Korean wine producers,''
said a statement by Yeutter, who will be Agriculture secretary in
the incoming Bush administration.
   The American Wine Institute had appealed to Reagan under a law
which lets him retaliate against the trade of countries that damage
or threaten U.S. industry.
   According to the announcement, the South Korean government is to
lift immediately its ban on wine coolers, dessert wines and
fortified wines, and will double its import quota for all wine
products. Beginning in 1990, it will lift restrictions on table
wines, wine coolers -- mixtures of wine and fruit juice -- and
fruit-flavored wines.
   Yeutter added that the South Korean government has agreed to ask
the National Assembly to lower the tax rate on wine coolers to 25
percent from 40 percent.
   In January 1991 the ban on champagne and brandy will disappear.
   Early last year, the South Korean tariff on wine products stood
at 100 percent of their value. The current rate of 50 percent will
drop to 35 percent in July and to 30 percent in January 1990. The
rate on wine coolers will drop to 25 percent.
   Yeutter's announcement said U.S. products will have equal access
to the South Korean distribution system and U.S. companies will have
the right to set up their own networks for American products,
through Korean agents. In 1991 Americans will get the right to
invest directly in importing and wholesale activities on U.S. wines.
   It took three rounds of negotiations to settle the dispute. The
agreement on Wednesday was contained in an exchange of letters,
Yeutter's office said..
</TEXT>
