<FIRST>r i AM-Iran     01-18 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iranian Parliamentarians Demand Judicial Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of Iran's Parliament on Wednesday
demanded a tougher judiciary system that would crack down on
widespread corruption, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
   Iran's official news agency, monitored in Nicosia, said a letter
to the judiciary signed by 190 lawmakers read, ``It is in the
interest of the county to strengthen the judiciary as soon as
possible according to the leader of the Islamic revolution,
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.''
   IRNA said the letter advised the judiciary to heed the warning,
adding that failure to do so could cause irreparable harm.
   The call reflects public concern over government graft and other
issues put to one side after the Iran-Iraq war began in September
1980.
   Parliament deputy Rajai Khorasani told students in northwestern
Tabriz province last month that corruption was a major reason for
Iran's agreeing to a U.N.-mediated cease-fire last August.
   Last month Parliament came under attack for voting down a bill
demanding that all government officials' incomes be investigated.
   Members opposing the measure, among them Speaker Hashemi
Rafsanjani, said it was too far-reaching in requiring that
medium-level officials such as bank managers and heads of
state-owned corporations be investigated.
   In an effort to demonstrate a tough stand on corruption, however,
the government last month sentenced multimillionaire Ali Mousavi to
death for defrauding war victims' families.
   Also, an Expediency Council formed by Khomeini to expedite
legislation bypassed both judiciary and Parliament in passing a
draconian law against drug smugglers.
   The new law, to take effect at the end of this week, carries a
death sentence for anyone found in possession of more than 30 grams
(just over one ounce) of specified hard drugs and 11 pounds of any
narcotic.
   According to Tehran television reports, also monitored in
Nicosia, the public welcomed the crackdown.
   Already, 75 people have been hanged in advance of the new law,
and hundreds of tons of narcotics have been seized.
</TEXT>
