<HEAD>Ex-Convict Found Guilty of Murdering Prison Guard He Married</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENWOOD, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury deliberated about 25 minutes
before convicting an ex-convict of murder in the shooting of his
wife, a prison guard he married after he finished serving a term for
armed robbery.
   Ronnie Ray Strong, 30, of Itta Bena was sentenced Tuesday to life
in prison, the mandatory penalty for murder in Mississippi, by
Circuit Judge Howard Q. Davis.
   The sentencing capped a one-day trial in which Leflore County
prosecutor Charlie Swayze described Strong as ``mean as a snake and
dangerous.''
   The defense argued that Strong should be found guilty of the
lesser charge of manslaughter because he was acting in the heat of
passion when he shot Charlene Meeks Strong four times in the neck
with a .22-caliber pistol.
   Strong met his wife in July 1986, while he was an inmate at the
State Penitentiary at Parchman, where she was a guard. He moved in
with her upon his release, and married her in April 1988.
   Willie Perkins, Strong's attorney, told the jury that on the
night of Sept. 10, Strong was drunk and under the influence of
marijuana when he got into an argument with his wife, whom he
believed was having an affair with another man.
   Strong testified that when he asked her where she had been, she
told him it was none of his business.
   He also said that during the argument, which erupted as Mrs.
Strong was sitting in the kitchen doing her hair, she reached into
her bag and ``put on a pair of brass knuckles.''
   Strong pulled out the gun, which he claimed he never intended to
use, and in the ensuing scuffle, the gun went off. Strong said he
couldn't account for the other three shots.
