<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Marcos     01-18 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Marcos,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos Makes Second Offer To Return ``Hidden Wealth''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Marcos Health</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate president said Wednesday
that ousted President Ferdinand Marcos has offered to return an
undisclosed amount of money stashed in Swiss banks in exchange for
permission to return home.
   Sen. Jovito Salonga said the offer was made in an August letter
and was the second such offer made by Marcos.
   Salonga formerly headed a government body charged with recovering
Marcos' fortune.
   Presidential Executive Secretary Catalino Macaraig confirmed that
a proposal to return $5 billion was made in July but was rejected by
the government, which says Marcos, his family and associates
illegally garnered up to $10 billion during his 20-year presidency.
   President Corazon Aquino said on Wednesday she had received no
formal, unequivocal offers directly from Marcos. She had said she
would let Marcos return only if he returned money obtained illegally
while in office.
   ``It (Marcos' offer) was not very clear. It was coursed through
third parties and there was not anything definite ... Until things
are put down in writing and formally addressed to me, I guess we
cannot really study the matter,'' Mrs. Aquino told reporters.
   Marcos, 71, was toppled in the February 1986 ``People's Power''
uprising that swept Mrs. Aquino into power and forced Marcos into
Hawaiian exile.
   ``He (Marcos) signed a document ... offering to transfer to the
Philippine government the disputed funds in the Swiss banks,''
Salonga told reporters. ``No amount was indicated in the letter.''
   Salonga said the letter was signed in the presence of an Allan
Weinstein, an American professor who was to ``act as a
representative (of Marcos) to deal with the Philippine government,''
Salonga said.
   Marcos faces 39 civil cases in the Philippines involving
embezzlement. No criminal charges have been filed against Marcos or
his family. Philippine laws prohibit trial in the absence of the
defendant.
   On Oct. 21, a U.S. federal grand jury indicted Marcos, his wife,
Imelda, and eight other associates on racketeering charges. They
were accused of plundering their homeland of $103 million to buy New
York real estate and defrauding U.S. banks of more than $165 million
between 1972-1986.
   Mrs. Marcos pleaded not guilty.
   Marcos' lawyers told a federal judge in New York on Wednesday he
is unable to stand trial there on racketeering charges because he is
dying.
   The Manila government has refused to allow the Marcoses to return
for fear that their civilian and military supporters would undermine
the 35-month old Aquino administration. Mrs. Aquino has faced at
least five coup attempts, mostly from troops loyal to Marcos.
</TEXT>
