<FIRST>u i AM-Poland 2ndLd-Writethru a0799 01-18 0881</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0799,0909</SECOND>
<HEAD>Offer to Legalize Solidarity Appears Likely; Jaruzelski Wins Vote</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to fix byline. LEADS throughout to UPDATE with
Jaruzelski winning vote of confidence after offering to resign. Edits to
trim. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Communist Party leader said Wednesday the
way is clear to make the Solidarity trade union legal again. Gen.
Wojciech Jaruzelski won a vote of confidence after offering to
resign in a bitter internal fight.
   The policy-making Central Committee's vote of confidence kept
Jaruzelski, party leader and head of state, in power on the second
day of a meeting in which the party debated union freedoms, the
official PAP news agency said.
   The meeting led to a party resolution that paves the way for the
relegalization of Solidarity, said chief party ideologist Marian
Orzechowski.
   Jaruzelski and other key members of the ruling Politburo,
including Prime Minister Mieczyslaw Rakowski and Interior Minister
Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak, offered to give up their party and government
posts, PAP said.
   In an unusual description of the heated debate, PAP reported
``accusations that party policy was incomprehensible, faulty and
often contradictory of the expectations and view of party members.''
   PAP said the doubts of the 230-member Central Committee were
justified by the ``bad experiences'' of 1980-1981.
   Solidarity, the Soviet bloc's first independent union movement,
was formed during labor unrest in 1980, crushed with martial law in
1981 and outlawed in 1982.
   The 230-member Central Committee gave Jaruzelski and the other
leaders a vote of confidence with only four abstentions.
   It was the first time the government reported such a resignation
offer, suggesting growing official openness.
   PAP said the Central Committee passed a position paper on
political and union freedoms by a vote of 143-32, with 14
abstentions.
   The text was not released, but Orzechowski told state radio it
was a ``great turning point.''
   ``It opens the road to restoration of trade union pluralism,
including Solidarity, formulating at the same time a number of
conditions which have to be fulfilled so the road is not too
bumpy,'' Orzechowski said.
   ``We don't know the reaction of the other side yet,'' he said.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa had insisted on a clear party
statement of its willingness to recognize his union before he would
enter talks with the government on Poland's future.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said in Washington that
the Polish leadership's ``stated willingness to relegalize the
Solidarity trade union under certain conditions is a step forward.
... Relegalization would be a major achievement on the road to
Poland's reform and recovery. We would welcome it.''
   Rakowski had asked the Central Committee for a green light to
offer to restore the union's legal status for a two-year trial
period on condition it help the government in its economic and
political reforms.
   Orzechowski said the conditions ``stem from our experiences and
from the foreseen potential effects of the developing events.'' He
urged the opposition to show a ``sense of responsiblity.''
   A draft of the original resolution on trade union freedoms
obtained by Western news agencies said that at proposed talks with
the opposition, ``the organizational forms of expanded national
reconciliation should be determined.''
   ``There should also be agreed conditions, means and a schedule of
introducing trade union pluralism, and opening the road for creation
of new trade unions, including Solidarity.''
   It was not known if the language concerning Solidarity was
altered during the party debate in which many Central Committee
members spoke against Solidarity.
   Solidarity has remained active despite the ban, first as an
underground organization and later increasingly tolerated by
authorities. Recently, Walesa has been treated as a member of the
``constructive opposition'' whose views are carried in the media.
   Officials have said they would like Solidarity's support in
maintaining calm as the government introduces its potentially
disruptive reforms.
   Officials believe an agreement with Solidarity would also help
the government obtain badly needed Western credits.
   On Tuesday, Rakowski urged a conditional offer of legalization to
Solidarity so long as the union agrees to act as a partner, not a
``political opponent.''
   He said Solidarity would have to declare itself a part of
socialism and disassociate itself from anti-communist groups,
observe a strike moratorium and give up financial assistance from
the West, which has amounted to millions of dollars.
   Legalization would come only after the two-year probationary
period when both sides would evaluate ``positive and negative
experiences,'' Rakowski said.
   A Solidarity source in Warsaw said privately that the conditions
set by Rakowski initially appeared ``unacceptable.''
   But Krzysztof Sliwinski, an independent journalist associated
with Solidarity, was more optimistic.
   Emphasizing that he was giving his own view and not the union's,
Sliwinski said, ``It seems to be a commitment to recognize
Solidarity. So I would would consider it an important first step
that was very difficult for them.''
   Sliwinski said the most difficult condition for the union to
accept would be a moratorium on striking, which Rakowski suggested
should last two years.
   ``Walesa has said many times that he does not want to organize
strikes,'' Sliwinski said. ``But without the right to strike there
is no use being a union.''
   True partnership with the government would be impossible under
those conditions ``because all the power is on the other side,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
