<FIRST>u w AM-InauguralRdp 6thLd-Writethru a0871 01-18 1214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Inaugural Rdp, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0871,1,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 9-10 ``Before the'' with further Bush remarks; should
stand for AMs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Promises to Reach Out to Americans `Still Hurting'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, beginning an inaugural whirlwind
in solemn remembrance and thunderous celebration, promised Wednesday
a government that will reach out to Americans ``still hurting''
despite the recovery of the Reagan era.
   Addressing an exultant throng gathered at the Lincoln Memorial,
Bush invoked the words chiseled onto its walls when he said
```government of the people, by the people and for the people' ...
is the kind of government I plan to lead'' upon taking the
presidential oath Friday.
   On the first of five days of inaugural activity, Bush also paid
parting tribute to Ronald Reagan, his political mentor, and promised
all the nation's teachers that education ``will be on my desk and on
my mind'' from the moment he becomes president.
   At the majestic monument to Lincoln, as evening fell upon an
unusually warm, clear day, Bush said ``America is strong once again,
we are respected around the world ... our children are being born
into a land of oppoortunity.
   ``But the job is not complete,'' he declared. ``Some are still
hurting. And we care.''
   ``Many important tasks lie ahead,'' Bush said. ``Let us rekindle
the flame of confidence and commitment so that we can accomplish the
great goals we have yet to achieve.''
   With that, he ignited his inaugural flame as well, triggering a
massive fireworks display in keeping with his concept of the
nation's diversity and promise as ``a thousand points of light.''
U.S. Park Police estimated the crowd at 250,000; inaugural
organizers put it at 40,000.
   It was a day bursting with moments of quiet reflection as well as
pomp and promises. Memories were stirred in a private meeting with
old Navy comrades who saved his life in the Pacific 44 years earlier.
   Before the night was out, Bush, his wife Barbara, and Dan and
Marilyn Quayle donned their formal wear and dropped in on three
separate $1,500-per-plate dinners for thousands of Republican high
rollers, noting that their contributions helped finance several
inaugural shows free to the public. At one location, the renovated
Union Station, homeless people lined up outside for a soup-kitchen
meal served by anti-poverty activists while the GOP guests dined on
Maryland crab and roast pork.
   A glowing Bush told the swank assemblage at the Corcoran Gallery
of Art that ``It's just beginning to set in'' that he will be
president on Friday. ``It's so hard to describe,'' he said. At Union
Station, he joked that ``The Bushes and Quayles won't interrupt this
dinner for long. We can't. We're exhausted.''
   The two women wore matching black and white _ Mrs. Bush in a gown
with long-sleeve white top, swirled with rhinestones, and a black
A-line skirt tied with a sash; the wife of the Vice President-elect
in a wrap-style gown with fitted bodice and flowing skirt.
   The outdoor pageant produced the only thunder of a
picture-perfect day _ a flyover by 21 Navy combat jets, the Good
Vibrations of the Beach Boys, the bombs bursting in air, in
electric-white glare.
   Bush was accompanied there, too, by his wife and the Quayles. For
that occasion, the women wore matching, shocking-red coats; Mrs.
Bush topped hers with a huge, Stars-and-Stripes scarf.
   President and Nancy Reagan, meanwhile, officially bade farewell
to hundreds of White House staffers. ``We were all revolutionaries,
and the revolution has been a success,'' Reagan told 350 aides.
   Tears streamed down Nancy Reagan's face as the Marine Band played
``Auld Lang Syne.''
   Bush told a meeting of the Republican National Committee that ``I
don't believe I'd be standing here as president-elect of the United
States if it hadn't been for the way President Reagan treated me as
vice president, and then the way he rolled up his sleeves and went
to work ... helping his vice president be elected.
   ``When I go say farewell to him tomorrow, it won't be too easy,''
he said. `` We're not coming in to correct the ills of the past.
We're coming in to build on a proud record.''
   Bush began the day with an address to America's educators. ``This
is my very first event on the inaugural calendar. ...That's the way
I wanted it,'' he told 230 top-rated public school teachers,
gathered from every state.
   ``I know you've heard me say during this campaign that I intended
to be the education president. Two days before I begin trying I
wanted you to know that I meant it.''
   Bush, who attended the exclusive Phillips Academy at Andover,
Mass., and earned his college degree and Phi Beta Kappa key at Yale,
told the teachers: ``I am awed by your work.''
   ``Education will be on my desk and on my mind right from the
start,'' he said.
   With two days to go before he is sworn in, Bush was all over town.
   First off, he moved from the vice presidential mansion into
lodgings closer to the White House, then set off on a schedule
crammed with social events, including the reunion with his Navy
rescuers more than 44 years ago.
   Bush joked, meanwhile, that he was giving wife Barbara ``a little
elbow room'' while she was still in the throes of moving. ``I don't
care if I see her for another 48 hours, because I know there'll be
another crate that she (will say): `Move this one over here.'
   He paused, and added: ``I'm getting tired of that. After all,
I've got big responsibilities.''
   In private, Bush embraced 16 surviving crew members of the USS
Finback, a World War II submarine which rescued him after he bailed
out when his TBM Avenger torpedo bomber was struck by Japanese fire.
   Bush, who has accorded the Finback veterans the choicest seats at
several inaugural events, welcomed them to his temporary quarters at
the Blair House to renew memories. One, Don Kohler, of Rogers, Ark.,
the torpedoman who pulled Bush from the drink, said ``It was very
emotional. You have to remember that very few of us had seen any of
the others for 44 years.''
   Kohler said Bush told the group that ``his relationships in the
war helped him a great deal in guiding his life.''
   Another recollection, according to retired Rear Adm. Lawrence
Heyworth of Virginia Beach, Va., once the Finback's gunnery officer,
was that the crew nicknamed Bush ``Ellie'' for ``his outstanding
imitation of an elephant trumpeting.''
   That wasn't the stunt of an aspiring Republican. Bush, then 20,
merely had seen too many ``Tarzan'' movies in the wardroom.
   In his remarks to the school teachers, Bush said that even under
budgetary constraints, ``We're going to work to make sure that the
nation does what needs to be done for our schools: reward
excellence, weigh standards, expand choice, publicize success,
strive to resolve shortcomings.''
   Paul Parets, a band teacher at Alexis I. DuPont High School in
Wilmington, Del., said, ``I was very moved. I sat there thinking he
could have met with the heads of foreign states, he could have met
with the leaders of the military or the captains of industry and
instead he chose to meet with 230 teachers from across the United
States.''
</TEXT>
