<HEAD>For release Fri PMs Jan. 20, or thereafter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students from 20 Roman Catholic, Protestant,
Eastern Orthodox and Jewish seminaries in the Northeast are taking
part in a program of mutual visits to discuss and learn about each
other's faiths.
   Ellen Charry, director of the program called ``Theology in a
Pluralistic Setting,'' sponsored by the National Conference of
Christians and Jews, says:
   ``The idea is for each of the students to have an opportunity to
identify the distinctiveness of ... who they are ... and also adjust
their thinking to take in a more realistic and full picture of who
the others are.''
   Marcia Prager, a student at Reconstructist Rabbinical College in
Wyncote, Pa., who took part in recent conversations in Washington,
at Howard University Divinity School and Catholic University of
America, says:
   ``People who are going to be religious leaders, if they don't
know how to listen, are going to be lost in an endless forest of
misunderstanding that will only aggravate past wounds.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A record total of 4.1 million people
visited Temple Square, center of the Church of Jesus Christ of
Latter-day Saints (Mormons) in 1988, three-quarters of a million
more than in 1987, according to newly released figures.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Methodist leaders, whose denomination has
been losing members for two decades, called at a meeting on
evangelism here for a return to the basics of Bible study, biblical
preaching and winning converts.
   The church needs to get back to the fundamental task of making
``disciples for Jesus Christ,'' said the Rev. John Ed. Mathison,
pastor of the 4,800-member Frazer Memorial United Methodist Church
in Montgomery, Ala., one the fastest growing in the denomination.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rabbi A. James Rudin, national interreligious
affairs director of the American Jewish Committee, is the new head
of a Jewish body that handles relationships with the Vatican, the
World Council of Churches and othher international religious bodies.
   Rudin was elected chairman of the International Jewish Committee
for Interreligious Consultations, succeeding Rabbi Marc H. Tanenbaum
of the AJC.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic leader says the Soviet release
of a Lithuanian bishop gives ``cautious hope'' of improved
conditions for religion in the Soviet Union.
   Concerning release of Bishop Julijonas Steponavicius from more
than two decades of internal exile and his return to Vilnius,
Lithuania, Monsignor Daniel F. Hoye, general secretary of the U.S.
Catholic Conference, said it is an added ``sign of improvement in
the situation of the church.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 30-second radio spot produced by an ecumenical
media cooperative for broadcast in connection with the birthday of
the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., features his speaking these words:
   ``Life's piano can only produce the melodies of brotherhood when
it is recognized that the black keys are as necessary and beautiful
as the white keys.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents of pornography are commending
action by the Federal Communications Commission in extending to 24
hours a day its ban on indecent communication on radio and TV.
   Larry Braidfoot of the Southern Baptist Christian Life
Commission, the denomination's social action arm, says the FCC
previously had not banned sexually explicit broadcasting on
late-night broadcasts.
   Expansion on Dec. 31 of the ban through all hours ``caps a
struggle which has going on throughout most of the 1980s,''
Braidfoot says.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Jan. 20.</NOTE>
