<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 1402EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-Hibbing7 Adv22   01-18 0951</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Hibbing 7, Adv 22,0982</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Jan. 22, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Seven Women Carry On Fight Against American Linen Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial wires</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MP2 of Jan. 16</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIBBING, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was 15 months ago when seven American
Linen Supply Co. workers walked off the job, a strike that the
plant's other 35 union members didn't honor.
   The strikers, all women, were replaced on the strike's first day
and they have long since been cut from unemployment compensation
rolls.
   They haven't given up. Their stubborness has become a saga in
this northern Minnesota town and a nationwide symbol of
labor-management confrontation in an era when job security has
become a prevailing issue.
   ``We eat, drink, and sleep the strike,'' said Betty Judnitsch,
48. ``You just can't help it.''
   Tom Pender, president of the Iron Range Labor Assembly, said the
women's persistence has astonished observers.
   ``It was amazing that they were standing out there last winter
when it was 30 below,'' Pender said. ``Well, here it is this winter
and they're still there.''
   Known as the Hibbing 7, they take turns picketing outside the
green and white plant where they used to wash, mend and press linen
for $5.42 an hour.
   They walked off the job Oct. 2, 1987, after 11 of 17 members of
United Food and Commercial Workers Union Local 1116 voted to strike
rather than accept management's final contract offer. They had been
working without a contract for 11 months.
   Linda Carpenter, 43, said the four other workers who voted to
strike immediately capitulated when it became apparent they faced
dismissal.
   The strikers objected to a contract provision that eliminated
company contributions to the union pension fund, Carpenter said.
Instead, the company offered to put money into individual retirement
accounts for workers, she said.
   The women also said they believe Ed Pajunen, company president,
was out to destroy the union. They cite a letter found by strikers
in the company's trash.
   The letter, from lawyer William Harding of Lincoln, Neb.,
previewed a meeting at which district executives would be briefed on
``negotiations in the Omaha and Hibbing district which led to
non-union status at various locations.''
   Pajunen said the letter does not reflect an anti-union bias. He
says the plant has operated more smoothly without a union, but adds
he did not intend to break it.
   ``I'm not anti-labor, but they do a lot of intimidating,''
Pajunen said of unions. ``Some of the things they stand for aren't
necessarily always right.''
   Pender said the strikers would have lost interest if it weren't
for favorable rulings by the National Labor Relations Board's
regional office in Minneapolis and a federal administrative law
judge in Washington.
   Judge Robert Leiner in September upheld allegations of wrongdoing
made by the NRLB's regional office. He ordered American Linen to
reinstate the seven workers with back pay and full seniority rights.
A company appeal is pending.
   By firing Carpenter, Judnitsch, Mary Suzick, 61, Ruth Johnson,
52, Roberta Hecimovich, 46; Marge Richards, 51, and Linda Perry, 33,
American Linen unlawfully discriminated against employees engaged in
a lawful union activity, Leiner wrote.
   The judge also said American Linen must recognize Local 1116 as
bargaining agent for the Hibbing workers. A petition to decertify
the union signed by a majority of plant workers four days after the
strike began should be dismissed because the company illegally
helped prepare and file it, the judge ruled.
   ``We've won. We're right,'' Judnitsch said. ``If we didn't feel
that we were right we wouldn't be out there.''
   Pajunen said he never fired the strikers.
   ``They walked off their jobs,'' he said. ``At this point not one
has asked to come back.''
   The company president said he would consider rehiring the
strikers if any of the 70 positions open. Meanwhile, he said, he
would fight any ruling from the NLRB that is ``untrue.''
   William Watters, an attorney for Local 1116, said appeals could
prolong the fight another year or two. He said the women are willing
to battle until they win, bolstered by strong financial support from
the union.
   ``Fortunately it's not too many situations that end up like
this,'' Watters said.
   Ruth Johnson said she and her husband have been limited to her
weekly $40 strike benefits and his monthly wage of about $700 since
the strike began.
   ``You go from burning fuel oil to burning wood,'' said Ms.
Johnson, who has been living without any health insurance coverage
since losing her job. ``You just cut corners. Sometimes it's just
enough heat to keep the pipes from freezing.''
   Pajunen said the strikers are ``misguided.''
   ``There's probably one or two people in that group who get their
kicks from doing something like this and the other people got
trapped,'' he said.
   Not all the strikers knew each other before the walkout and now
they frequently socialize after handling picket duty.
   ``I think we have our down days,'' Judnitsch said. ``But we're
pretty hearty. We're determined.''
   The inevitable lows have been offset by a few highs, Suzick said.
For instance, Crystal Lee Sutton, whose successful union struggle
against a southern textile manufacturer was depicted in the movie
``Norma Rae,'' appeared at a June 25th rally on their behalf. The
Rev. Jesse Jackson invited them on stage during a campaign
appearance.
   In addition, the strikers say they've scored partial success in
promoting a regional boycott of American Linen's service. A local
school district, for example, has stopped taking the service,
Judnitsch said.
   Pajunen said the boycott has not reduced business.
   ``We have a plant full of happy employees producing for our
customers,'' he said. ``We're not hurting.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Jan. 22</NOTE>
