<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   01-18 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0521</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business inventories rose 0.4 percent in
November and sales rose at the same pace, the government said in a
report that analysts said bodes well for the nation's economy in the
new year.
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday inventories held on shelves
and backlots rose to a seasonally adjusted $753.6 billion in
November, while sales reached $503.8 billion.
   The matching 0.4 percent gains kept the ratio of inventories to
sales at 1.50, meaning it would take 1.5 months to exhaust
inventories at the November sales pace.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Takeover strategist Carl C. Icahn has raised his
stake in Texaco Inc. to 16.6 percent and confirmed he was preparing
for the possibility of a second fight for control of the oil giant.
   Icahn also accused Texaco management Tuesday of breaking a
promise to shareholders by devising a new anti-takeover defense to
replace one that expires April 7.
   He said the new strategy was an attempt to ``preclude a bid for
Texaco by me or by anyone else ...''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financier Kirk Kerkorian pumped $180
million into MGM-UA Communications Co. and revealed the latest in a
series of intricate blueprints for selling part of the struggling
movie company he controls.
   MGM-UA announced Tuesday Kerkorian's Tracinda Corp. had bought 10
million shares of newly issued preferred stock for $18 a share.
   The company also announced it would try to sell United Artists
part of the conglomerate Kerkorian assembled a decade ago from
assets of UA and the old Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer studios.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gulf &amp; Western Inc. tentatively has agreed to a
deal that would give it an option to buy a majority interest in TVX
Broadcast Group Inc., which owns nine independent television
stations, the companies said.
   Gulf &amp; Western would buy the TVX stake from an affiliate of
Salomon Brothers Inc., the securities firm that helped TVX finance
its purchase of five television stations in April 1987.
   No price was disclosed Tuesday for the latest deal, but analysts
said it apparently would give Gulf &amp; Western a relatively
inexpensive entry into broadcast television.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Citicorp, the nation's largest bank holding company, and three
other big banking companies reported sharply higher earnings for
both the fourth quarter of 1988 and the whole year.
   Most of the banks, which included J.P. Morgan &amp; Co., Security
Pacific Corp. and Wells Fargo &amp; Co., said Tuesday they were helped
partly by tighter cost controls and Brazil's resumption of interest
payments on foreign loans.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Latin American nations must negotiate debt
reduction agreements with commercial bank creditors or face a
worsening economic situation that could lead to the return of
military dictatorships in the region, a panel of experts said.
   The recommendation was made in a report Tuesday by the
Inter-American Dialogue, a grouping of 66 prominent citizens from
the United States, Canada, Latin America and the Caribbean.
</TEXT>
