<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0506</SECOND>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration's
``Rambo-style diplomacy'' led to frequent trade clashes with
European countries but trans-Atlantic relations remain good,
according to Europe's former top trade official.
   Willy De Clercq, who recently finished four years as a key
official of the European Economic Community, raised the possibility
Tuesday that the latest trade dispute _ sparked by a European ban on
hormone-treated U.S. meat _ might be resolved shortly through
negotiations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has bought an additional
530,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices, the
Agriculture Department said.
   Melvin E. Sims, general sales manager for the department's
Foreign Agricultural Service, said Tuesday the wheat was part of 2
million tons authorized Dec. 23 under the Export Enhancement
Program, or EEP.
   The wheat was bought under a long-term supply agreement with the
United States, a pact now in its sixth year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Delta Air Lines spokesman said the carrier
found emergency sprinkler system wiring errors in two of its Boeing
757s, corrected the problems and advised the Federal Aviation
Administration.
   Similar problems involving sprinkler systems in the U.S.-built
planes were reported earlier in another Delta-operated 757, one
belonging to Royal Brunei Airlines, two owned by Air Holland, and
one operated by the British airline Air 2000.
   One of the Air Holland planes was being used by a charter company
in Canada.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The editor of a leading medical journal dismissed
as ``utterly false'' R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co.'s contention the
publication is being used in its parent group's campaign against
Reynolds' ``smokeless'' cigarette.
   ``The Journal of the American Medical Association has
traditionally been editorially independent and remains so at this
time,'' Dr. George D. Lundberg, editor of the weekly journal
published by the AMA, said Tuesday.
   Reynolds contends that the Jan. 6 issue of JAMA contained
incorrect information about its new product, Premier, which heats
rather than burns tobacco.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal charges were announced against 18 former
employees of First Commodity Corp. of Boston, alleging they
defrauded more than 2,600 investors of some $40 million.
   The charges stem from an ongoing investigation in Chicago,
Boston, New York, Miami and San Francisco _ the largest single
investigation of its kind ever undertaken by federal officials, U.S.
Attorney Anton Valukas said Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell for a second day Tuesday as nervousness over
trade deficit figures due Wednesday contributed to the market's
first back-to-back declines of 1989. The Dow Jones industrial
average fell 10.00 points to 2,214.64.
   The dollar and bond prices slipped in quiet trading, reflecting
investor reluctance to take risky positions prior to the trade
report.
   Corn and soybean futures prices plunged; wheat and oat futures
finished mostly higher; gasoline futures led energy futures higher;
precious metals advanced; livestock and meat futures were mostly
higher; and stock-index futures retreated.
</TEXT>
