<FIRST>r f PM-OilPrices     01-18 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Prices,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil, Gasoline Prices Add to Recent Gains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The oil markets have maintained upward momentum,
fueled by buying amid speculation about possibly tighter supplies in
the future.
   In recent days, crude oil futures prices have soared to a
14-month high. The February contract for West Texas Intermediate,
the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, settled Tuesday at $18.95 a
barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange, up 7 cents a barrel on
the day.
   The last time the contract for the nearby month settled higher
was Nov. 5, 1987 when the price at the end of the trading day
reached $18.98 a barrel. At that time, there were concerns that the
Iran-Iraq war could seriously disrupt shipments of crude from the
Persian Gulf.
   The price of the near-month contract for West Texas Intermediate
now stands sharply higher than last autumn. On Oct. 5, the nearby
contract sank to an intraday low of $12.28 a barrel.
   Analysts say the markets lately have derived support from a
series of factors deemed promising for the price outlook,
particularly speculation that OPEC nations would be able to curb
their crude oil production.
   Jim Fiedler, a vice president at E.D.&amp;F. Man International
Futures Inc., said market operators are not necessarily confident
that an output accord will come out of a meeting beginning Jan. 26
in London between members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries and non-OPEC countries.
   But, they do not expect the meeting to produce any negative news
for the oil markets either, he said.
   The nearby West Texas Intermediate contract reached a high of
$19.21 during the session before traders began to sell to collect
profits amassed during the recent advance.
   Gasoline contracts in the more distant months benefited from
buying partly based on thinking that new environmental
specifications due to take effect this year could restrict
availability in the future. Buying in gasoline spilled over into the
crude oil contracts, brokers said.
   The February contract for unleaded gasoline rose 0.19 cent to
settle at 51.10 cents a gallon.
   Among other refined products traded on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, the February contract for No. 2 heating oil slipped 0.11
cent to 53.05 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890118-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 0134EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TVXBroadcast Bjt   01-18 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-TVX Broadcast, Bjt,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gulf &amp; Western Unit Tentatively Agrees to Buy Stake in TV Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gulf &amp; Western Inc., the entertainment,
publishing and financial services giant, plans to buy a stake in a
company that owns television stations in several major markets.
   Gulf &amp; Western said Tuesday its Paramount Pictures Corp. had
agreed in principle to a deal that would give it an option to buy a
majority interest in TVX Broadcast Group Inc., which owns nine
independent television stations.
   It would buy the stake from an affiliate of Salomon Brothers
Inc., the securities firm that helped TVX finance its purchase of
five television stations in April 1987.
   No price was disclosed for the latest deal, and it is subject to
reaching a definitive agreement as well as regulatory approval.
   But analysts said it apparently would give Gulf &amp; Western a
relatively inexpensive entry into broadcast television.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Gulf &amp; Western fell
62{ cents a share to $41. TVX jumped $1.62{ a share to $3.87{ in
national over-the-counter trading.
   Paramount currently produces and distributes television
programming. Its parent has said it wanted to become involved in TV
station ownership but that high prices discouraged it.
   Gulf &amp; Western would join a growing list of companies involved in
TV programming that have bought television stations.
   Such companies feel that by getting involved in ``the retail end
of distribution,'' they can exert more control over where and when
their programs are aired, said Raymond Katz, media analyst for the
securities firm Mabon Nugent &amp; Co.
   Gulf &amp; Western said Paramount had agreed in principle to acquire
the right to buy Salomon's majority investment in TVX Broadcast,
which is based in Virginia Beach, Va.
   Salomon wound up with preferred and common stock representing a
79 percent equity interest in TVX following the television company's
recent recapitalization.
   As the first step in the deal, Salomon would put all of its TVX
common stock and enough of its TVX preferred in a new joint venture
that would represent about 51 percent of TVX's voting common shares.
   Paramount would buy a 49 percent interest in the joint venture,
and get an option to buy Salomon's stake in the venture and the rest
of Salomon's TVX preferred stock.
   The statement did not say how much Paramount would pay for its
initial stake in the venture, but one source familiar with the deal
and speaking on condition that he not be identified said it was
about $10 million.
   The source said the total cost to Paramount, should it acquire
all of Salomon's stake, would be between $125 million and $180
million, depending on the company's future performance.
   Salomon became involved with TVX Broadcast when it provided
temporary financing for the concern to acquire five television
stations in April 1987.
   Before TVX Broadcast could line up permanent financing, the stock
market crashed in October 1987 and drove up potential costs of
borrowing.
   As part of a recapitalization plan approved last November by TVX
Broadcast shareholders, TVX Broadcast issued preferred and common
stock to Salomon.
   TVX owns nine independent television stations but agreed as part
of the recapitalization plan to sell four of them _ WTVZ in Norfolk,
Va.; KRRT in San Antonio, Texas; WNOL in New Orleans; and WMKW in
Memphis.
   That will leave the company with five stations _ WTXF in
Philadelphia, WDCA in Washington, D.C.; KTXH in Houston; KTXA in
Dallas and WLFL in Raleigh-Durham, N.C.
   TVX Broadcast lost $21.8 million on revenue of $138 million in
the nine months ended Sept. 30, 1988, compared with a loss of $30
million on revenue of $101.7 million during the same period in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
