<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     01-18 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tokyo Stocks Hit Record High Again, Dollar Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's leading index hit another
record high today, while the U.S. dollar gained against the Japanese
yen for the third consecutive day.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which fell 70.86
points on Tuesday, climbed 127.03 points, or 0.41 percent, in
today's trading, closing at 31,354.55. The previous record of
31,298.38 was set last Friday.
   Although early trading was directionless, news reports about the
possibility of a redenomination of the yen boosted buying orders,
dealers said.
   Such a change could mean, for example, that 100 yen now would
become one yen, requiring a reprinting of Japanese money.
   ``Participants were targeting their buying orders to
redenomination-related issues such as paper, pulp and ink,'' said an
analyst at Nomura Securities, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The buying interest helped boost volume on the first section to
an estimated 1.2 billion shares.
   The news reports quoted Shintaro Abe, general secretary of the
ruling Liberal Democratic Party, as saying Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita was considering a redenomination of the yen.
   Other dealers said the majority of institutional investors stayed
on the sidelines to await the announcement of monthly U.S. trade
figures, expected later today in Washington.
   On the currency market, the dollar closed at 127.90 yen, up 0.20
yen from Tuesday's 127.70-yen close. The currency also opened today
at 127.70 yen and ranged between 127.63 yen and 128.00 yen.
   The dollar now has gained 1.78 yen in three days.
   Trading was thin ahead of the U.S. trade figure announcement, a
dealer at Mitsubishi Bank said.
   The market was expecting a U.S. trade deficit of $11 billion,
said the dealer, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``If the deficit increases, it won't be a strong dollar-selling
force because nobody expected the figure to improve dramatically in
the first place,'' he added.
</TEXT>
