<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Stocks     01-18 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Rise Strongly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rose strongly at midday Wednesday,
pushed up by bullish sentiment as the market surpassed last June's
post-crash high.
   Late morning news that the British government's December budget
surplus was larger than market predictions extended the morning
rally, dealers said.
   By about 12:30 p.m., the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share
index was up 19.5 points, or 1 percent, at 1,887.2, just two points
below the day's best level of 1,889.2. The index registered its
minimum of 1,871.7 at the outset of official trading at 9 a.m.
   The June post-crash high was 1,879.3.
   Volume was 301.6 million shares compared with 250.6 million
shares at the same time Tuesday.
   The market's rise also was attributed to market makers being
short of stock, dealers said.
   ``We're short of just about everything,'' one market maker said,
``and whatever comes on the market is being snapped up in the blink
of an eye.''
   However, dealers detected a slowing in trading early in the
afternoon as players grew cautious ahead of the 1:30 p.m. release of
the U.S. trade report for November.
   ``As long as (the trade figures) aren't a disaster, we're locked
into an upward path,'' one analyst contended.
</TEXT>
