<DOCNO> AP890118-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 0908EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru   01-18 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with six grafs to UPDATE with trade report, early reaction
in foreign exchange and credit markets. Picks up 4th graf pvs, In foreign
... Will be led with reports on December industrial production and capacity
utilization scheduled for 9:15 a.m. EST release.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A huge jump in imports helped widen the nation's trade deficit to
$12.5 billion in November, the largest imbalance in five months, the
government reported today.
   The Commerce Department said the gap between what the United
States imports and what it sells overseas was about 22 percent
higher than the October deficit of $10.3 billion.
   The sharply higher shortfall was blamed on an increase in
imports, which shot up to $39.7 billion, $1.6 billion above the
October level. Exports, which have been booming this year, declined
by $639 million to $27.2 billion.
   The November deficit was the largest since a $13.2 billion
imbalance in June.
   Shortly after the report was released the dollar fell in hectic
domestic trading while bond prices were narrowly mixed.
   The financial markets had weakened slightly on Tuesday amid
uncertainty over the trade figures, which have frequently moved the
markets in the past.
   In foreign exchange, the dollar's decline came in quiet trading
and reflected traders' reluctance to take risky positions before the
release of the report in Washington, analysts said.
   The consensus is for a trade deficit of about $11 billion,
compared with $10.35 billion in October, but the numbers are
renowned for defying predictions.
   A number sharply higher than $11 billion could possibly incite a
big selloff in dollars, while a much smaller number could encourage
a surge in demand for the U.S. currency.
   The dollar's decline also weighed on Wall Street, where the Dow
Jones average of 30 industrials finished down 10.00 points to
2,214.64 and broader market indicators also declined.
   In the bond market, the bellwether 30-year Treasury bond dipped
about $1.50 per $1,000 in face value.
   Among commodities, crude oil futures ended higher to extend their
recent rally to their highest levels since late 1987.
   The February contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude, finished 7 cents higher at $18.95 a barrel
Tuesday on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   It was the highest settlement for a near-month contract since the
Nov. 5, 1987 close of $18.98 per barrel, and marked a nearly
$7-a-barrel rise since last autumn.
   Analysts say the energy markets lately have derived support from
speculation that the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
would be able to restrain crude oil output.
   In other economic news Tuesday, the Commerce Department reported
0.4 percent November growth rates in both business inventories and
business sales. Analysts said the report is an indicator that the
economy is likely to keep growing in 1989.
   Inventories rose to a seasonally adjusted $753.6 billion in
November, while sales reached $503.8 billion, for matching growth
rates of 0.4 percent.
   When not accompanied by increasing sales, rising inventories can
signal economic weakness because they may lead manufacturers to
order production cuts and layoffs while they sell reserve goods.
   The November increase in inventories followed a small rise in
October and a 0.9 percent jump in September. It was the 23rd
straight month in which inventories had risen, but sales generally
have kept pace.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
