<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against other major currencies in
Europe Wednesday after the U.S. government reported that the U.S.
trade deficit widened dramatically to a worse-than-expected $12.5
billion in November.
   The dollar, however, remained mostly higher against other
currencies compared with late Tuesday.
   Gold prices rose in morning trading.
   The dollar fell after the Commerce Department reported at 1:30
p.m. that the trade gap was 21.9 percent higher than the October
deficit of 10.3 billion dollars.
   Despite the dollar's quick decline, the trade figures were not
expected to jolt the financial markets, as poor trade reports have
in the past.
   That's because the foreign exchange markets had been expecting a
widening in the deficit, albeit a smaller one, to $11.1 billion.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.7695 to buy one pound after the trade report was released, more
than $1.7643 before. On Tuesday, it cost $1.7680.
   Here are other dollar rates in Europe after the trade report was
released, with midmorning rates in parentheses, and compared with
late Tuesday's rates: 1.8525 (1.8560) West German marks, up from
1.8505; 1.5745 (1.5808) Swiss francs, down from 1.5755; 6.3210
