<DOCNO> AP890118-0265 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 1008EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Trade-Japan     01-18 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trade-Japan,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trade Surplus Narrows in 1988, But Was Widening in Recent Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's trade surplus shrank in 1988, but was
widening in the year's last four months and hit a monthly record in
December, the Finance Ministry reported today.
   For all of 1988, the ministry said, the surplus on a customs
clearance basis amounted to $77.4 billion, down from $79.7 billion
in 1987.
   With the United States, Japan's 1988 surplus was $47.6 billion,
down from $52.1 billion in 1987. The December surplus with the
United States was $5.03 billion, up from $4.92 billion in the
previous December.
   The overall surplus in December hit a record $9.65 billion, up
from $8.61 billion in the previous December and from $6.56 billion
in November 1988.
   It was the fourth consecutive month when Japan's surplus exceeded
that of the corresponding month in 1987.
   Japan's major trading partners have been pressing it for years to
take greater steps toward reducing its huge trade surpluses.
   ``We hear the voices of concern, and we have concern,'' Mitoji
Yabunaka, director of the Foreign Ministry's Second North America
Division, said at a news conference. ``But at the same time, we see
encouraging trends.''
   In December exports grew 11.6 percent from a year earlier to
$26.1 billion, while imports grew 11.3 percent to $16.4 billion.
   Lower prices for crude oil, Japan's most important import
commodity, coupled with strong demand overseas for Japanese-made
computers, semiconductors and automobiles contributed to the record
December figure.
</TEXT>
