<FIRST>r f PM-MCorp     01-18 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-MCorp,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pritzkers Latest To Eye MCorp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A firm backed by Chicago's wealthy Pritzker family
is working with a New York investment banking firm on a possible bid
for MCorp, according to industry sources.
   The firm, called GKH Partners, also includes Corpus Christi
resident Melvyn Klein, the Houston Chronicle reported today.
   GKH is considering whether to send a team into MCorp to inspect
the books of the troubled banking company, the industry officials
said.
   If GKH goes in, it will be the third group to examine MCorp in
preparation for a possible bid. Kohlberg, Kravis &amp; Roberts, the
investment firm that won the bidding for RJR Nabisco last year, had
been visiting MCorp and left the bank last week. Wells Fargo &amp; Co.,
the giant San Francisco bank, also has paid a visit.
   The partners of GKH have worked with each other before. Last
year, Harry Gray founded a firm called Harry Gray, Melvyn Klein &amp;
Partners, whose backers included the Pritzkers. They joined in last
year's failed attempt by Resource Holdings, another Pritzker-backed
operation, to win the bidding for RJR Nabisco.
   The partners also have worked with the investment firm Donaldson,
Lufkin &amp; Jenrette. Klein is a former special counsel to United
Technologies and a former senior vice president of DLJ. Dan Lufkin,
a founding partner of DLJ, is an adviser to the Gray Klein group.
   Gray Klein reportedly has equity of more than $500 million, and
has made several unsuccessful takeover attempts. Gray Klein was part
of a bidding group for Federated Department Stores. It is unclear
whether GKH and Gray Klein are one and the same.
   Neither Gray nor Klein could be reached for comment by The
Associated Press this morning.
   The Pritzkers, based in Chicago, are among America's wealthiest
families. Among their holdings are Hyatt Corp. Last year, they sold
Dallas-based Braniff to Philadelphia real estate investor Jeffrey
Chodorow for $105 million.
   Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette is acquainted with bank bailouts.
Last year, it teamed up with A. Robert Abboud to recapitalize First
City Bancorporation of Texas. The firm helped Abboud raise $500
million in private capital for the bank. The Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp. provided another $1 billion in assistance.
   MCorp is the last of the major Texas banks to retain its
independence in the face of the state's banking crisis. Last
October, it announced that it needed federal assistance to survive.
   MCorp management has a recapitalization plan of its own that
calls for $1 billion in private money to be matched with $1 billion
in FDIC assistance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
