<FIRST>u f PM-IndustrialProduction 1stLd-Writethru f0046 01-18 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Industrial Production, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0046, f0055,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Factory Use Hit Nine-Year High in December</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combinres pvs files</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The operating rate at U.S. factories, mines and
utilities rose in December to the highest rate since November 1979,
the government reported today.
   The Federal Reserve Board said the use of industrial capacity
rose 0.1 percentage points to 84.2 percent last month, the highest
rate since 84.3 percent in November 1979. The operating rate for
November 1988 was a revised 84.1 percent.
   As capacity use edges toward 85 percent, economists fear
factories will have trouble producing enough goods to meet demand,
leading to shortages and price increases.
   In an accompanying report, the Federal Reserve said industrial
production climbed 0.3 percent in December following a revised
increase of 0.4 percent in November.
   The Fed's industrial production index now stands at 140.2 percent
of its 1977 base, reflecting sharp gains in auto production and
continued strength in production of construction supplies.
   At manufacturing plants, the operating rate climbed to 84.4
percent last month from 84.3 percent in October. Production of
durable goods _ ``big-ticket'' items expected to last at least three
years _ rose 0.1 percentage points to 83.0. Production of
non-durable goods fell by a like margin to 86.4 percent.
   Industries with especially strong operating rates over the past
two years include primary metals, chemicals, fabricated metal
products, non-electrial machinery, autos and automotive parts.
   Use of motor vehicles and parts manufacturing capacity rose for
the fifth straight month to 88.1 percent, up from 85.5 percent in
November.
   The December operating rate at utilities was 81.9 percent, up
from 81.3 percent a month earlier. In the mining sector, which
includes oil and gas drilling, the operating rate was up 0.1
percentage points to 83.3 percent.
   The Federal Reserve's production index has not declined since
September 1987, reflecting an export-driven manufacturing boom
accompanied by a surge in spending for capital equipment to expand
and modernize factories.
   Production in the manufacturing sector rose 0.3 percent in
December following a revised increase at the same rate for the month
earlier. Automobiles were assembled at an annual rate of 7.9 million
units, up from 7.6 million in November. Production of light trucks
also rose sharply.
   Output at mines was unchanged in December after a 1.4 percent
rise a month earlier. Production at utilities was up 0.8 percent
from November.
   Total output at factories, mines and utilities was up 4.7 percent
from a year earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
