<FIRST>r f PM-Steinberg-Penn     01-18 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steinberg-Penn,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Steinburg Give $25 Million To Penn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saul P. Steinberg, chairman and chief
executive officer of Reliance Group Holdings Inc., has pledged $25
million to the University of Pennsylvania, Penn President Sheldon
Hackney said today.
   Steinberg's gift to his alma mater is the largest single
contribution in the Ivy League School's history, Hackney said.
   The money will be shared by the Wharton School, which will get
$15 million, and the school of arts and sciences, which will receive
$10 million.
   Administrators of arts and sciences, in consultation with
Steinberg, have decided to invest the entire $10 million in Penn's
English Department for faculty and student recruitment.
   Steinberg is chairman of the Wharton School's Board of Overseers
and has been instrumental in supporting the strategic plan developed
by the school.
   As part of that plan, the school will endow five school-wide
professorships, create 20 ``term chairs'' for use in a program to
recruit young professors, establish a financial aid program for
masters of business degrees, provide additional funding for the
Steinberg Conference Center and increase funding for new academic
programs.
   ``All of us at Penn are deeply grateful to Saul Steinberg for
this act of leadership,'' Hackney said. ``He has been a champion of
the university for many years, and his latest bold step is pivotal
in our campaign to strengthen Penn's position in the front rank of
America's universities.''
   The money to the English department will be used to endow four
professorships, create an annual visiting professorship for a
nationally renowned writer, fund eight fellowships for graduate
students and establish a humanities fund that will extend the
department's connections with other departments of the university.
   Steinberg received his bachelor's degree in economics from
Wharton in 1959.
</TEXT>
