<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 1114EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-MostStolen     01-18 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Most Stolen,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Camaro Continues Lock on No. 1 Stolen Car Spot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chevrolet Camaro is continuing its lock on the
No. 1 spot on a vehicle valuation services's list of most-stolen
cars.
   Certified Collateral Corp. of Chicago, which sets values of
stolen vehicles for insurance companies, said today the 1986 Camaro
was the most-stolen car in 1988.
   It was followed by the 1987 Camaro, the 1984 Camaro, the 1985
Camaro and the 1981 Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme.
   The company began compiling lists of the most frequently reported
stolen domestic and imported cars in 1985, and every year since then
a Camaro has topped the domestic list, CCC spokesman Tom Figel said.
   Among imported cars, the 1987 Hyundai Excel topped the 1988 CCC
list. It was followed by the 1985 Mazda RX7 GT and Toyota Corollas
from 1983, 1982 and 1981.
   For its 1988 list, CCC compiled 111,440 insurance claims for
stolen cars. The company defined a stolen car as one in which the
entire vehicle was taken, and did not include break-ins or wheel
thefts, for example.
   The 1986 Camaro amounted to 0.9 percent of the theft claims
handled by CCC.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
