<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   01-18 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mostly Higher In Technical Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened mostly
higher today on the Chicago Board of Trade in what many analysts
said was a technical correction following two days of steep losses
in the corn and soybean markets.
   ``The general feeling is that after the big break of the last two
days, you're technically oversold and you're entitled to some sort
of rebound,'' said Jerry Zusel, manager of Balfour Maclaine Corp's
floor operations at the Board of Trade.
   The recent drop in corn and soybean prices came in reaction to a
government report that showed larger-than-expected supplies of those
commodities.
   Analysts said additional buying this morning was linked to higher
soybean meal prices in Europe and news that South Korea had
purchased 200,000 metric tons of U.S. corn overnight.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent lower to 2 cents higher with
the contract for delivery in March at $4.36 a bushel; corn was 1}
cents to 2\ cents higher with March at $2.70 a bushel; oats were }
cent to 2 cents higher with March at $2.35 a bushel; soybeans were
1\ cents to 2} cents higher with March at $7.72 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent lower to .05 cent higher with February
at 74.12 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .55 cent
lower with January at 84.80 cents a pound; live hogs were .52 cent
lower to .48 cent higher with February at 44.40 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .20 cent to .45 cent lower with February at
41.80 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
