<FIRST>r f PM-ForeignOvertures     01-18 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Foreign Overtures,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>17 Percent Of Biggest U.S. Firms Were Wooed By Foreigners In 1988:
Survey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign firms approached 17 percent of the largest
U.S. companies about possible takeovers last year, according to a
study released today by Northwestern University's Kellogg Graduate
School of Management.
   Only a handful of such initial approaches by overseas firms
became public or amounted to a bid, the survey found.
   The study _ a survey of the chief executive officers of 95
corporations with annual sales of at least $1 billion _ also found
that while 60 percent of the respondents felt foreign ownership
tends to maximize shareholder value, just over half said they would
prefer a U.S. firm as a new owner if they were taken over.
   Slightly less than 23 percent of the CEOs reported being
approached by a prospective domestic buyer last year.
   Two-thirds of the chief executives responding to the survey said
they were more interested in joint ventures and similar linkups with
foreign companies than they were in selling.
   Northwestern University Professor Edward Zajac, project director
for the survey, said he was surprised by the number of firms that
reported overtures by foreign companies.
   Zajac said the survey showed ``the world is getting smaller'' and
U.S. firms are finding that to survive in an increasingly complex
world, they must turn to international alliances.
</TEXT>
