<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Noon,0294</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market headed highter today, shrugging
off what analysts described as mildly disappointing news on
international trade.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials edged up 7.32 to 2,221.96
by noontime on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 8 to 7 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 650 up, 576 down and
602 unchanged.
   The Commerce Department reported this morning that the nation's
trade deficit widened to $12.51 billion in November from a revised
$10.26 billion the month before.
   The latest number exceeded most advance estimates on Wall Street,
although analysts said it caused no great dismay among traders.
   Meanwhile, the market also absorbed the news of quarterly
earnings from International Business Machines Corp. that fell
slightly short of expectations.
   IBM, which posted profits of $3.97 a share for the fourth quarter
against $3.47 in the like period a year earlier, dropped ] to 123{.
   Tandem Computers jumped 1] to 18 and led the active list. The
company reported earnings for its first fiscal quarter ended Dec. 31
of 32 cents a share, up from 24 cents in the like period a year
earlier.
   RJR Nabisco slipped [ to 95[. Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. said
it had lined up more than $14 billion in bank loans to help finance
its buyout of the company.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.47 to 159.95. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .10 at 316.47.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 76.64 million shares at noontime,
up from 69.58 million at the same point Tuesday.
