<FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru   01-18 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Surge To Close At New Post-Crash High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite disappointment with the latest set of U.S.
trade figures, London stocks extended their recent broad-based rally
in active trading Wednesday, reaching their best levels since the
1987 stock crash.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index closed up 24.4
points, or 1.3 percent, at 1,892.1, well above the previous
post-crash closing high of 1,879.3, reached in June.
   Volume also continued its recent brisk pace, with 603 million
shares changing hands, compared with 424.4 million shares on Tuesday.
   Equities took their cue from the dollar, which also successfully
weathered news that the U.S. trade deficit was a wider-than-expected
$12.5 billion in November, dealers and analysts said.
   A buying spree by institutions drove prices higher in early
trading. In addition, a shortage of stock held by market makers
discouraged any fall in prices even after business tapered off,
dealers said.
   ``London has been rather late as far as other equity markets go
in reaching a post-crash high,'' said Bill Smith, equities market
strategist at Prudential-Bache Capital Funding Ltd.
   Sentiment has turned bullish amid growing evidence of a cooling
of inflationary pressures on the British economy, the analyst said.
</TEXT>
