<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 1414EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-RockwellTrial     01-18 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Rockwell Trial,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guilty Plea Expected in Defense Double-Billing Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rockwell International Corp.'s federal trial
on charges of overbilling the Air Force for work on a satellite was
delayed until Thursday amid reports the company was negotiating a
guilty plea.
   The trial in U.S. District Court was scheduled to begin Tuesday.
   Prosecutors and the company declined to comment on the reasons,
but the Wall Street Journal and the New York Times, quoting sources
familiar with the case, said the company was discussing a bargain to
plead guilty in exchange for reduced penalties.
   Rockwell, the El Segundo-based high-technology manufacturer that
made the B-1B bomber and works on the space shuttle, is charged with
seven counts of conspiracy, mail fraud and contempt.
   The company is accused of overcharging the Air Force by $446,000
for work on the Navstar global Positioning satellite in 1983. The
governmentalleges Rockwell's satellite systems division in Seal
Beach submitted bills for the same work under two contracts.
   The company has denied wrongdoing and maintained its own official
alerted the Air Force to the problem.
   The charges carry a maximum fine of $1 million, and if Rockwellis
found guilty, the company could be suspended from bidding on
government contracts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
