<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 1413EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     01-18 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0336</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market climbed toward new post-crash
highs today, shrugging off what analysts described as mildly
disappointing news on international trade.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 15.54 to 2,230.18 by
2 p.m. on Wall Street. The average reached its highest close since
October 1987 at 2,226.07 last Friday.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 8 to 5 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 826 up, 516 down and
534 unchanged.
   The Commerce Department reported this morning that the nation's
trade deficit widened to $12.51 billion in November from a revised
$10.26 billion the month before.
   The latest number exceeded most advance estimates on Wall Street,
although analysts said it caused no great dismay among traders.
   The news had only a short-lived impact on the markets. The dollar
and bond prices quickly rebounded from it, and as they moved higher
stocks followed their lead.
   Meanwhile, the market also absorbed the news of quarterly
earnings from International Business Machines Corp. that fell
slightly short of expectations.
   IBM, which posted profits of $3.97 a share for the fourth quarter
against $3.47 in the like period a year earlier, was unchanged at
123~.
   Tandem Computers jumped 1} to 18] and led the active list. The
company reported earnings for its first fiscal quarter ended Dec. 31
of 32 cents a share, up from 24 cents in the like period a year
earlier.
   RJR Nabisco was unchanged at 95\ in active trading. Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. said it had lined up more than $14 billion in
bank loans to help finance its buyout of the company.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
1.08 to 160.56. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .47 at 317.04.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 129.32 million shares with two
hours to go.
</TEXT>
