<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     01-18 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Surges Despite Intervention, Trade Report; Gold Steady</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMer planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar defied gravity in hectic European
trading Wednesday, surging despite a bearish set of U.S. trade
figures and two reported rounds of central bank intervention.
   Gold prices were mostly higher.
   Dealers were surprised by the dollar's ability to shrug off the
bearish factors, and predicted the U.S. currency would rise further.
   News that the U.S. trade deficit widened sharply to $12.5 billion
in November from a revised $10.3 billion in October surprised the
market and knocked the dollar down, dealers said.
   The market expected a November deficit of about $11 billion.
   Dealers said the dollar's reaction reflected a markdown in rates
rather than any heavy selling, and the U.S. currency immediately
bounced higher. That triggered a round of concerted intervention by
the U.S. Federal Reserve, the West German Bundesbank and the central
banks of France and Italy, dealers said.
   Despite the first round of intervention, the dollar continued to
climb higher, and a second round of dollar sales by the Bundesbank,
the Fed, and the Bank of Canada also failed to have much impact,
dealers said.
   The intervention appeared to be fairly light, one dealer said.
   The dollar's recovery was aided by a few large buy orders that
triggered a snowballing rally, a dealer said.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.7550 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.7680 late Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday's
prices, included: 1.8705 West German marks, up from 1.8505; 1.5890
Swiss francs, up from 1.5755; 6.3800 French francs, up from 6.3085;
2.0925 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0855; 1,356.75 Italian lire, up
from 1,354.00; and 1.1937 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1973.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 0.20 Japanese yen to a closing 127.90
yen. Later, in London, it was quoted at 128.45 yen.
   Gold held steady in London. The late bid price was $402.25 a troy
ounce, unchanged from late Tuesday.
   In Zurich, gold closed at a bid $402.40, compared with $402.15
bid late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 21 cents to close at a bid
$404.64.
   Silver bullion rose on the London market to a late bid price of
$5.94 a troy ounce from $5.92 bid late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
