<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 0725EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f AM-Heartland-JapanesePlants Adv23   01-18 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Heartland-Japanese Plants, Adv 23,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, Jan. 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Where the Plants Are</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Heartland-Motor Cities</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Following is a list of Japanese-associated auto plants in the
United States. The information is provided by company officials.
   _ Diamond-Star Motors Corp. in Normal, Ill., a joint
Chrysler-Mitsubishi venture, began producing Plymouth Lasers and
Mitsubishi Eclipses in September.
   The workforce is about 1,500 and could reach 2,900 by this fall.
By 1990, annual production will be 240,000 cars a year.
   _ Subaru-Isuzu Automotive Inc., next to Lafayette, Ind., a joint
venture of Fuji Heavy Industries Ltd. and Isuzu Motors Limited, is
expected to begin producing cars and trucks this September.
   The plant will initially employ 1,700 workers and, depending on
the market, could expand to a workforce of 3,200 by 1992-93. By
1990, production of Isuzu Troopers and Pups and the Subaru Legacy
will total 120,000 vehicles a year.
   _ Mazda Motor Manufacturing (USA) Corp. in Flat Rock, Mich.,
began making the Mazda MX-6 and Ford's sporty Probe in September
1987. It has nearly 3,500 employees and produces about 240,000 cars
annually.
   _ Toyota Motor Manufacturing, U.S.A., Inc. in Georgetown, Ky.,
was dedicated in October. It has about 1,750 employees and produces
about 360 Camry sedans a day.
   By the end of 1989, it will produce 200,000 cars annually and
have 3,000 employees. An additional 500 workers will be added when a
power train plant that produces engines, axles and steering
components becomes operational in 1991.
   _ Nissan Motor Manufacturing Corp. U.S.A. in Smyrna, Tenn.,
opened in June 1983 and has 3,100 workers. The plant produces about
220,000 Sentra cars and Nissan light trucks annually.
   _ Honda of America Manufacturing Inc. in Marysville, Ohio, began
making motorcycles in 1979. Auto production started in 1982. The
company now has two plants at Marysville and one at Anna, Ohio. It
has expanded at Anna and is building a fourth plant in East Liberty,
Ohio. The workforce is 6,700 and expected to increase to 8,500 by
1991. This year, Honda is expected to produce 360,000 Accord and
Civic cars, as well as motorcycles.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   New United Motor Manufacturing Inc., the only Japanese-affiliated
plant located out the country's midsection, opened in Fremont,
Calif., in 1984. The joint Toyota-General Motors venture has 2,640
employees and produces about 200,000 cars a year. It manufactures
the Corolla sedan and the Geo Prizm, a replacement for the Chevy
Nova.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Jan. 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
