<DOCNO> AP890118-0293 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 0726EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f AM-Heartland-AutoFacts Adv23   01-18 0757</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Heartland-Auto Facts, Adv 23,0794</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, Jan. 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Statistics on U.S. and Japanese Auto Production</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Heartland-Motor Cities</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some facts about the U.S. auto industry, the Japanese
impact on it and black employment within it. The statistics are
provided by the General Accounting Office, the United Auto Workers
union, the Wefa Group, a Michigan State University study by Richard
Hill and Cynthia Negrey, a study by University of Michigan
professors Robert Cole and Donald Deskins Jr., and ``The State of
Black Michigan: 1988,'' a report published by Michigan State and the
Michigan Council of Urban League Executives.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Market Share:
   _ Japanese companies increased their share of the U.S. market
from about 8 percent in 1976 to about 23 percent in 1987.
   _ An estimated 2.08 million Japanese imports and 737,513
``transplants'' _ cars built totally or partly by the Japanese at
U.S. sites _ were sold in this country last year. That accounted for
26.6 percent of the 10.52 million cars purchased in the United
States.
   Imports include cars such as the Dodge Colt, built by Mitsubishi
in Japan. Transplants include products of joint U.S.-Japanese
ventures, such as the Ford Probe, built by Mazda.
   _ The number of transplant autos built in the United States has
risen steadily. The Wefa Group, an economic consulting organization,
estimates Japanese transplants in North America will total 1.7
million cars in 1990, compared with 600,000 in 1986.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Imports:
   _ Japan exported 2.21 million cars to the United States in the
1987 fiscal year, which ended last March. The Japanese government
said shipments in the April-November period were 10.4 percent below
those of a year earlier, but it still estimates Japan will have
exported 2.2 million cars to this country when the current fiscal
year ends in March.
   In 1981, Japan imposed a voluntary export restraint in response
to U.S. political pressure. It first limited annual exports to the
United States to 1.68 million units. The cap was increased in steps
to 2.3 million units in 1985. It has remained there since.
   Some Japanese automakers feel the quota is outdated because
domestic car prices have become more attractive against the cost of
Japanese cars, driven upward as the yen doubled in value over the
last three years.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Exports:
   _ In 1986, North America produced 12.5 million vehicles and
exported 40,000. Japan produced 12.2 million vehicles, 6.6 million
of which were exported.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Japanese Investment:
   _ In the 1980s, Japanese automakers have invested $5 billion in
U.S. assembly plants for cars and light trucks.
   _ Seven automakers and more than 100 auto parts suppliers with
partial or total Japanese ownership are operating or building plants
in the United States. Since 1984, the number of Japanese-affiliated
auto suppliers has nearly doubled in this country.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Job Loss:
   _ A 1988 GAO report said Japanese-affiliated automakers could
cause the loss of 45,000 jobs in the industry in 1990 if there was a
high displacement rate (`transplant' autos built in lieu of domestic
cars), a production level of 1.8 million vehicles by those companies
and 50 percent of the cars' parts and materials were made in the
United States compared with 83 percent for traditional U.S.
automakers.
   But the UAW said the government underestimated the potential job
loss due to transplants. The union said up to 74,000 jobs could be
lost.
   _ The GAO estimated a job loss of 360,000 from 1985 to 1990 from
all factors, including transplants, gains in productivity, rising
auto imports and increased use of foreign parts. However, the UAW
estimate was 470,000, noting Japanese-affiliated plants have built
only a third of planned capacity.
   _ From 1985 to 1987, 169,000 auto manufacturing jobs have
disappeared. That includes workers at the plants as well as those
employed by industry suppliers.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Minorities:
   _ In 1984, according to reports filed with the Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission, blacks comprised 17.2 percent of all workers
employed by the Big Three automakers and 8.4 percent of white-collar
employees.
   Blacks make up nearly 11 percent of the civilian labor force.
   _ General Motors Corp. estimated its 1987 payroll for its black
employees was $3 billion. The March 1988 Current Population Survey
estimated total 1987 wage and salary income for 12.9 million blacks
was $178.8 billion.
   So, although GM's black workers represented just six-tenths
percent of all black employees, they received 1.7 percent of the
nation's black wage and salary income in 1987.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Jan. 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
