<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 1519EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet3pm     01-18 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0338</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market pushed ahead toward new
post-crash highs today, shrugging off what analysts described as
mildly disappointing news on international trade.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 13.75 to 2,228.39 by
3 p.m. on Wall Street. The average reached its highest close since
October 1987 at 2,226.07 last Friday.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 9 to 5 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 935 up, 513 down and
497 unchanged.
   The Commerce Department reported this morning that the nation's
trade deficit widened to $12.51 billion in November from a revised
$10.26 billion the month before.
   The latest number exceeded most advance estimates on Wall Street,
although analysts said it caused no great dismay among traders.
   The news had only a short-lived impact on the markets. The dollar
and bond prices quickly rebounded from it, and as they moved higher
stocks followed their lead.
   Meanwhile, the market also absorbed the news of quarterly
earnings from International Business Machines Corp. that fell
slightly short of expectations.
   IBM, which posted profits of $3.97 a share for the fourth quarter
against $3.47 in the like period a year earlier, was down [ at 123}.
   Tandem Computers jumped 1{ to 18[ and led the active list. The
company reported earnings for its first fiscal quarter ended Dec. 31
of 32 cents a share, up from 24 cents in the like period a year
earlier.
   RJR Nabisco slipped [ to 95[ in active trading. Kohlberg Kravis
Roberts &amp; Co. said it had lined up more than $14 billion in bank
loans to help finance its buyout of the company.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.99 to 160.47. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .59 at 317.16.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 147.87 million shares with an
hour to go.
</TEXT>
