<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 2013EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-UnisysComputer     01-18 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Unisys Computer,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unisys Blurs Line Between Personal Computer, Mainframe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unisys Corp. introduced what it called ``the
industry's first true desktop mainframe,'' a personal computer that
has a special circuit board with all the features of its big
mainframe computers.
   The Micro A further blurs the distinction between personal
computers and mainframes, which were once as different as
motorcycles and buses. It can can run either standard personal
computer programs or programs written for its big A series of
mainframes, Unisys said.
   Unisys used advanced chip-packing techniques to get mainframe
features onto a board small enough to fit into a single slot in one
of its standard PW2 personal computers.
   The Micro A should help Unisys against competitors such as
International Business Machines Corp. and Digital Equipment Corp.,
which are also emphasizing their ability to run the same programs on
big and small computers, analysts said.
   ``I think they've got something real here,'' said Wendy
Abramowitz, an analyst for Argus Research Corp. But she said Unisys'
A series would still have trouble competing with the likes of IBM's
new AS-400 line because there are fewer programs available for it.
   ``It's a positive but it's not a cure-all,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890118-0301 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 1557EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-ForeignOvertures Bjt   01-18 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foreign Overtures, Bjt,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey Says 17 Percent of Biggest US Firms Wooed by Foreigners in
1988</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign firms made takeover overtures to 17
percent of the largest U.S. companies last year but only a handful
of the approaches grew into a formal buyout bid, according to a
survey released Wednesday.
   The survey by Northwestern University's Kellogg Graduate School
of Management also found that about two-thirds of the 95 chief
executives who participated said they were more interested in joint
ventures with foreign companies than they were in selling out.
   The findings were based on a survey of the chief executive
officers of 95 U.S. corporations with annual sales of at least $1
billion.
   Northwestern Professor Edward Zajac, project director for the
survey, said he was surprised by the number of firms that reported
overtures by foreign companies.
   ``Look at our sample _ those firms are very large,'' Zajac said
in a telephone interview from his office in Evanston. ``To say that
17 percent of Fortune 500 and Forbes 500 companies have been
approached, that's a healthy number.''
   But Ian Dunn, managing director of Samuel Montagu Inc., the New
York-based investment-banking unit of Britain's Midland Bank PLC,
was unimpressed with the survey results.
   ``It surprises me that it's as low as it is,'' Dunn said, citing
the takeovers by British firms last year of such notable U.S.
companies as Pillsbury Co., Farmers Group Inc. and Macmillan Inc.
   ``It doesn't surprise me at all that 17 of the 95 had been
contacted,'' said Dunn, whose firm assisted in Maxwell Communication
Corp.'s buyout of Macmillan.
   Twenty-three percent of the survey respondents said they had been
approached about a prospective buyout by a domestic company.
   The survey did not attempt to identify the nationalities of the
foreign companies that made takeover overtures for U.S. firms.
   But a report released Tuesday by the Translink International
Group, an investment banking firm, said British companies went on a
record $32.5 billion spending spree in America last year, buying 398
U.S. companies.
   Japanese companies spent $12.7 billion on U.S. acquisitions in
1988, according to the quarterly British-American Deal Review, which
is published by Translink.
   The Northwestern survey also found that while 60 percent of the
respondents felt foreign ownership tends to maximize shareholder
value, just over half said they would prefer a U.S. firm as a new
owner if they were taken over.
   Only 5.7 percent of the CEOs expressed a preference for foreign
ownership.
   Sixty-four percent of the companies surveyed said they were
involved with foreign allies in ``strategic alliances'' that ranged
from joint ventures and licensing agreements to co-marketing
agreements.
   ``I think that really shows how firms are adjusting to the new
global economy,'' Zajac said.
</TEXT>
