<FIRST>r f AM-CombustionEngineering     01-18 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Combustion Engineering,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Combustion Engineering Plans Joint Venture with French Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Combustion Engineering Inc. and
Paris-based Alsthom SA announced plans Wednesday to combine their
steam-boiler businesses in a joint venture that would have combined
revenues of about $2 billion.
   Combustion Engineering and Alsthom would own roughly equal shares
in the joint venture, which is subject to approval by each company's
board of directors and regulatory agencies in the United States,
France, Canada and the European Common Market.
   Talks leading to a definitive agreement are expected to take
several months, the companies said in a joint statement.
   The fossil-fueled steam boilers are used by electric utilities
and industrial users for generating power.
   ``Alsthom has been a licensee of C-E's steam generating
technology for 40 years and is an important supplier in the European
community and elsewhere,'' Charles E. Hugel, Combustion's chairman
and chief executive, said in a statement. ``We have great respect
for their capability.''
   Alsthom said its equity in the venture will be transferred to a
new joint venture company recently announced with General Electric
Co. of Great Britain.
   Combustion Engineering, which had net income of $56.6 million on
sales of $3 billion in 1987, provides engineering products, services
and systems to power-generating customers worldwide.
   Alsthom, which had sales of $4.7 billion in 1987, is a leading
manufacturer of industrial products and services concentrated in
energy, mass transportation and ship building, and a leading
supplier of power generation equipment, services and plants.
</TEXT>
