<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 1655EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-GasolineVapors     01-18 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gasoline Vapors,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Still Hopes To Move On Gas Vapor Pollution Regulation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency said
Wednesday it still hoped to move further before the end of the
Reagan administration toward a regulation requiring larger gasoline
vapor recovery canisters on cars.
   The agency's proposed regulation, and a companion rule requring
refiners to lower the volatility of gasoline, has been held up by
the Office of Management and Budget since October on safety grounds.
   A trade publication, Inside EPA, reported last week that C.
Boyden Gray, counsel to President-elect Bush, had asked Lee M.
Thomas, EPA administrator, to take no action on the canister rule
but to adopt the volatility rule.
   ``We are still hopeful that some type of agreement can be made
that would allow us to take the next step procedurally,'' EPA
spokesman Dave Cohen said Wednesday.
   Gasoline vapors are a principal source of urban smog, and the
trend in recent years toward higher volatility gasoline has
increased vapor emissions over EPA expectations. Several
northeastern states recently adopted regulations of their own
requiring refiners to lower volatility.
   Existing small canisters on cars are designed to recover vapors
only while the car is running or parked, not the large amounts
emitted during refueling. Recent EPA research has shown the
higher-volatility fuel used today can overhelm the capacity of
current canisters when running in hot weather.
   EPA estimates its canister and volatility rules together would
reduce emissions of ozone-forming compounds by up to 30 percent in
some areas.
   The Office of Management and Budget, the auto industry and Rep.
John Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of the House Energy and Commerce
Committee and a staunch guardian of the auto industry's interests,
all have objected that EPA's plan would increase the fire risk in
crashes.
   A report from the National Highway and Traffic Safety
Administration said unresolved safety questions remain; EPA's
consultants have said the risk would be reduced.
   When it published the draft canister rule for public comment, EPA
acknowledged it would have to seek public comment again on the NHTSA
report.
   In his comment Wednesday, Cohen was referring to that second
solicitation of comment. That would not require the agency to go
ahead with the volatility standard alone.
   Thomas' successor, William Reilly, has expressed no opinion on
the issue. He could revoke any action Thomas took, but such
revocations are bureaucratically as complicated as the issuance of a
new regulation.
   Thomas has been convinced for more than a year that the gasoline
volatility rule, opposed by the oil industry, and the canister rule,
favored by the oil industry, must be adopted together to keep the
industry mollified if not satisfied.
   If the canister rule is not adopted, there is a risk that the
entire issue of gasoline vapor emissions during refueling would be
thrown back to where it was when it started 10 years ago, pitting
the oil and auto industries against each other.
   The alternative to a canister rule is a requirement for
vapor-recovering hoses at service stations, already used in the
District of Columbia and parts of California and coming into use in
parts of New Jersey and the St. Louis area. The oil industry opposes
these because it costs several thousand dollars to eequip each
stations.
   Thomas believes the larger canister on the car is the better way
to reduce vapors because monitoring compliance among two dozen or so
manufacturers and importers on the device is easier than checking
tens of thousands of gasoline stations using the dual-hose systems.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
