<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 1701EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MostStolen Bjt   01-18 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Most Stolen, Bjt,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>Camaros Take Top Four Spots on Most-Stolen List for 1988</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Car thieves love Camaros.
   The autos made by General Motors Corp.'s Chevrolet Division were
the four most-stolen cars last year, according to a list compiled by
an automobile valuation service in Chicago.
   In fact, thieves picked GM cars as their 22 most-popular targets,
according to the list developed by CCC Information Services Inc., a
business used by insurance companies to determine the value of a
stolen car.
   The 1986 Chevrolet Camaro topped the CCC list of stolen cars for
the second consecutive year.
   This year's list, based on 1988 car thefts, has the '87 Camaro as
No. 2; the '84 Camaro following that, and the '85 Camaro as No. 4.
   The top five was rounded out by the 1981 Oldsmobile Cutlass
Supreme.
   ``It (the Camaro) appears as popular with thieves as with lawful
owners,'' said Ralph Kramer, a spokesman for the Chevrolet Division.
``That car is extremely popular and if you think of a huge
percentage of auto thefts being joy-ride kinds of things, the people
who tend to go joy riding tend to do so in Camaros.''
   The most popular imported car among thieves last year was the
1987 Hyundai Excel, made in South Korea. It was followed on the
import list by the 1985 Mazda RX7 GT, and the '83, '81 and '82
Toyota Corolla, all made in Japan.
   Of the 111,440 nationwide insurance claims handled by CCC, there
were reports of 1,006 thefts of '86 Camaros, making up 0.9 percent
of all the stolen cars. There were 780 thefts of '87 Camaros; 748
thefts of '84 Camaros and 673 thefts of '85 Camaros.
   The '87 Hyundai Excel wound up No. 23 on the overall list,
following nearly two dozen GM cars. Automobiles made by GM accounted
for 76 of the top 100, Ford Motor Co. had four cars on the list,
Chrysler Corp. had none and imported brands had 20.
   The first non-GM, U.S.-made car on the list is the 1985 Ford
Escort, holding down spot No. 45.
   GM cars make up about 50 percent of those on the road today, said
company spokesman Dave Hudgens.
   Kramer said the company has taken note of the high theft rate of
some of its cars and is fighting it. ``I think the VATS system is
going to make it a whole lot more difficult to steal a car,'' he
said.
   VATS, for vehicle anti-theft system, was introduced on the
Corvette and now is being used on Camaros and Firebirds, Kramer said.
   CCC provides an information database for insurance companies to
settle theft and collision claims. CCC said the insurance companies
with which it deals with represent 75 percent of all automobile
property and casualty insurance in force.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890118-0310 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 1702EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Trade Bjt   01-18 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Trade, Bjt,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan's Trade Surplus Narrows in 1988, But Was Widening in Recent
Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan said Wednesday its surplus of exports over
imports surged in December to a monthly record, despite official
assurances that the Asian economic giant is moving forcefully to
open markets to foreign goods.
   Although the Finance Ministry said the surplus shrank for all of
1988, figures showed it was widening in the last four months of the
year, capped by the $9.65 billion imbalance recorded last month.
   The Finance Ministry's announcement coincided with news from
Washington that the trade deficit of the United States, Japan's most
important trading partner, ballooned to $12.5 billion in November,
the biggest imbalance in five months.
   Taken together, the figures suggested that simmering
U.S.-Japanese disputes could worsen over restricted American access
to Japan's markets, and Japan's exploitation of the American
marketplace.
   For all of 1988, the Finance Ministry reported, the surplus
totaled $77.39 billion, down from $79.71 billion in 1987.
   But the figure was overshadowed by the December surplus, which
compared with an $8.61 billion surplus a year earlier and $6.56
billion surplus in November. It was the fourth straight month that
Japan's surplus exceeded that of the corresponding month in 1987.
   ``We hear the voices of concern, and we have concern,'' Mitoji
Yabunaka, director of the Foreign Ministry's Second North America
Division, said at a news conference. ``But at the same time, we see
encouraging trends.''
   Japan's major trading partners have been pressing it for years to
take greater steps toward reducing its huge trade surpluses by
opening Japanese markets to greater competition from abroad.
   The Finance Ministry said exports totaled $264.87 billion in
1988, up 15.6 percent from the previous year, while imports climbed
25.4 percent to $187.47 billion.
   Japan's December exports grew 11.6 percent from a year earlier to
$26.08 billion while imports grew 11.3 percent to $16.43 billion.
   With the United States, Japan's 1988 surplus totaled $47.61
billion, down from $52.10 billion in 1987. But the December surplus
with the United States totaled $5.03 billion, up from $4.92 billion
in the previous December.
   Lower prices for crude oil, Japan's most important import,
coupled with strong demand overseas for Japanese-made computers,
semiconductors and automobiles contributed to the record December
figure.
   Japan ran a $22.8 billion surplus with the European Economic
Community in 1988, up from $20.02 billion in 1987. In December, the
surplus totaled $2.15 billion, up from $1.92 billion a year earlier.
   For fiscal 1988, which ends March 31, Yabunaka stressed that the
projected 23.4 percent increase in imports is better than initially
expected and shows Japan is ``on the right track.''
   In fiscal 1989, the government sees imports growing by 17.4
percent compared with 9.4 percent for exports.
   Yabunaka attributed the 13.5 percent growth in fiscal 1988
exports to the strong world economic performance in general, and
added: ``There will be a moderate growth in exports over the course
of the next (fiscal) year, but we expect the speed to slow down due
to a slowing in the world economy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
