<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 1712EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Computers 1stLd-Writethru   01-18 0735</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Computers, 1st Ld-Writethru,0759</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Earnings Rise 12.4 Percent In Quarter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, The company's ..., to UPDATE with closing price;
picks up 9th graf, The pressure ....</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. said Wednesday its
quarterly earnings rose 12.4 percent, a gain that appeared to
reflect the improving health of the computer industry in general.
   Some analysts predicted that in 1989 IBM would approach and maybe
surpass its record profits of 1984, the year before a computer
industry slump that produced the first back-to-back earnings
declines in IBM history.
   ``'87 and '88 were kind of recovery years. Maybe '89 is when
we're going to break the all-time records,'' said Stephen Cohen, an
analyst at SoundView Financial Group in Stamford, Conn., who is
bullish on IBM stock.
   Makers of big mainframe computers and engineering workstations
are generally doing well while personal computer makers are muddling
along, although results for individual companies vary widely.
   Tandy Corp., a personal computer maker, reported a narrow 3
percent gain in profit Wednesday. Wang Laboratories Inc., a
minicomputer maker that has struggled in recent years, said its
earnings tumbled 97 percent.
   IBM, the world's largest computer company, said its profits were
helped by increased efficiency and positive response by customers
``in every segment of our business.''
   The Armonk, N.Y.-based company also announced it had trimmed its
staff even more than expected through voluntary separation
incentives.
   The company's stock rose $1.12{ to $125 a share in consolidated
New York Stock Exchange trading. It had dropped as much as $1.75 a
share right after the announcement but soon recovered.
   The pressure on IBM's stock came mainly from the company's
statements to analysts that its tax rate in 1989 would be higher
than in 1988, depressing net income, Cohen and others said.
   IBM said it earned $2.35 billion, or $3.97 a share, up from $2.09
billion, or $3.47 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to $20
billion from $18.3 billion in the 1987 period.
   For all of 1988, IBM said its earnings rose 10.4 percent to $5.81
billion, or $9.80 a share, from $5.26 billion, or $8.72 a share, a
year earlier. Revenue rose 8 percent to $59.7 billion from $55.3
billion.
   IBM said it recorded a fourth-quarter gain of $220 million on
payments from Fujitsu Ltd., its Japanese rival, under an arbitration
order that ended a software copyright dispute.
   But that gain was more than offset by a charge of $270 million to
cover unexpected costs of consolidating its operations.
   The company said 6,500 employees had chosen to leave the company
under a voluntary separation incentive program, more than the 3,000
to 4,000 that the company had expected when it announced the
incentives in June as part of a $600 million consolidation program.
   The separation offer was made to some manufacturing and
headquarters employees. IBM spokeswoman Marti Mattia said it had
been especially popular with heaquarters employees.
   Jay Stevens, an analyst for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., said of
IBM's results, ``It was a good quarter.''
   ``Some hot money moved in to anticipate a better-than-expected
quarter'' and moved out when the hopes failed to materialize, he
said, explaining the stock drop.
   ``The IBM company is continuing to show improvement in our
product line, our relationships with our customers and our financial
performance,'' John F. Akers, IBM's chairman and chief executive,
said in a statement.
   Wang Laboratories, based in Lowell, Mass., said its earnings fell
to $1 million, or 1 cent per share, in its second fiscal quarter,
from $34.1 million, or 21 cents a share, a year earlier. The
office-automation company said revenue fell to $760.7 million from
$784.7 million a year earlier.
   Wang said its earnings for the six months ended Dec. 31 were
$14.1 million, or 9 cents a share, down from $56.6 million, or 34
cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue edged up to $1.483 billion
from $1.477 billion a year earlier.
   Tandy, based in Fort Worth, Texas, said its second-quarter
earnings rose to $135.1 million, or $1.50 a share, from $130.8
million, or $1.46 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 8 percent to
$1.4 billion from $1.3 billion.
   For the first six months of its fiscal year, Tandy said its
earnings rose 2.5 percent to $200 million, or $2.23 a share, from
$195 million, or $2.17 a share. Revenue rose 9.2 percent to $2.34
billion from $2.14 billion.
</TEXT>
