<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 1811EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     01-18 0769</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0797</SECOND>
<HEAD>Livestock Futures Break Under Weight Of Supplies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Livestock futures prices plunged Wednesday on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange as the combined weight of the corn market's
recent collapse and large supplies of frozen pork bellies broke the
cattle and hog markets.
   Elsewhere on Wednesday, grain and soybean futures rebounded; oil
futures surged; precious metals retreated; and stock-index futures
advanced.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, live cattle settled .25 cent
to 1.35 cents lower with the contract for delivery in February at
73.32 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .90 cent to 1.35 cents lower
with January at 84.47 cents a pound; live hogs were 1.32 cents lower
to .10 cent higher with February at 43.60 cents a pound; and frozen
pork bellies were .45 cent to 1.78 cent lower with February at 40.55
cents a pound.
   ``I feel like the market's decided to stop selling the grains and
sell livestock for a change,'' said Paul Hare, a livestock-market
analyst with Chicago-based Linnco Futures Inc.
   That was a facetious reference to steep declines in corn and
soybean futures prices Monday and Tuesday on the Chicago Board of
Trade following an Agriculture Department crop report that showed
larger-than-expected supplies of those commodities.
   But another analyst said it was no exaggeration that the grain
sell-off had spilled over into the livestock markets.
   ``I think it started on the Board of Trade after the grain report
last week,'' said Chuck Levitt, senior livestock analyst with
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in Chicago. ``With corn down and beans
down, it kind of created a negative overall psychology in the
agriculture sector.''
   Analysts said another factor may have been this week's sluggish
pork demand, which contradicts normal seasonal trends.
   Levitt said the slowdown redirected traders' attention to the
nation's growing supply of frozen pork bellies. The Chicago
Mercantile Exchange reported after the close that supplies in
out-of-town warehouses had increased by 736,000 pounds during the
week that ended Saturday.
   ``January is supposed to be an out month for bellies, but we're
not getting withdrawals on a net basis,'' Levitt said.
   With no bullish news to support the cattle market, prices dropped
below 3- and 4-week lows, triggering a flood of sell orders from
speculators who had been holding out higher prices. Many experts
have predicted that live cattle futures will rise to record highs
above 80 cents a pound by spring.
   ``The well-publicized bull markets are often most vulnerable to a
break, and there were tremendous bullish expectations for the cattle
markets,'' Hare said.
   Corn and soybean futures rebounded on the Chicago Board of Trade
in a largely technical correction from the losses of the previous
two sessions, analysts said.
   And wheat futures rallied strongly late in the session on rumors
that China was seeking to buy or had bought 750,000 metric tons of
U.S. wheat for delivery this summer.
   ``I wouldn't be surprised if it turned out to be true,'' said
Katharina Zimmer, a grain-market analyst with Merrill Lynch Capital
Markets Inc.
   Wheat settled 3 cents to 6 higher with March at $4.39} a bushel;
corn was 2} cents to 6 cents higher with March at $2.70{ a bushel;
oats were 4{ cents to 6 cents higher with March at $2.37} a bushel;
and soybeans were unchanged to 8} cents higher with March at $7.71 a
bushel.
   Energy futures surged ahead on the New York Mercantile Exchange
with crude oil prices breaking the psychologically important
$19-a-barrel level and reaching new 14-month highs.
   Wholesale home heating oil and unleaded gasoline were up more
than a penny a gallon.
   Analysts attributed the rally largely to a bullish trade report
on oil production and to continued optimism that the 13-nation
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries will abide by its
production-cutting pact that went into effect Jan. 1.
   ``It seems there's a general perception that the steps taken to
shore up this market are no temporary affair ... and that OPEC has
found the discipline it needs,'' said Peter Beutel, an analyst with
Elders Futures Inc. in New York.
   Gold and silver futures prices fell modestly on New York's
Commodity Exchange in reaction to the dollar's gains against major
foreign currencies, analysts said.
   Gold settled 70 cents to $1 lower with February at $403.30 a troy
ounce; silver was 3.9 cents to 4 cents lower with March at $5.97 a
troy ounce.
   Stock-index futures advanced strongly on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for March delivery of stocks
represented by the Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index settled 2.60 points
higher at 288.70. The contract is worth $500 a point.
</TEXT>
