<HEAD>Investors Considering National Lampoon Bid Are Named to Magazine's
Board</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investor group led by actor Tim Matheson has
been named to the board of directors of National Lampoon Inc., the
magazine and entertainment company said Wednesday.
   The group headed by Matheson _ who starred in the National
Lampoon-produced movie ``Animal House'' in 1978 _ said last month it
might seek control of the firm.
   At that time, National Lampoon Chairman Matty Simmons said the
group, Grodnick Matheson Co., told him it might not pursue a
takeover if they were named to company's board.
   On Wednesday, Simmons announced that the board had been expanded
from four to seven directors, with Matheson and his partners, Daniel
Grodnick and Alan Parsow, filling the three new seats.
   Matheson's group owns 21 percent of the outstanding stock in the
publicly-traded National Lampoon.
   Grodnick Matheson Co. is a Los Angeles-based independent
production firm. Simmons said last month National Lampoon is
recovering from a four-year economic slump that he said was
contributed to in part by opposition by fundamentalist religious
groups and the Justice Department's Commission on Pornography.
   On Wednesday, Simmons said Grodnick and Matheson would be part of
a new management committee. ``They are experienced entertainment
executives ideally suited to contribute to the everyday operation of
the company,'' he said.
   National Lampoon said Grodnick Matheson had retained Batchelder &amp;
Partners for advice in raising capital for the magazine and
entertainment company. Batchelder was founded by David Batchelder, a
former key adviser to takeover strategist T. Boone Pickens Jr.
