<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     01-18 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rallies Despite Worsening Trade Figures; Gold Slips</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Money traders scrambled to buy dollars Wednesday
and boosted the currency despite a surprisingly big monthly U.S.
trade deficit, confounding conventional wisdom that when the
imbalance grows the dollar drops.
   Moreover, the dollar's strength grew despite repeated
intervention by central banks, which sold the currency about an hour
after the trade report was released in Washington.
   ``This is the last time we ever want to pay attention to the
trade numbers again,'' said Zlatko Glamuzina, a senior foreign
exchange dealer for the New York branch of Italy's Banco di Sicilia.
   Gold prices eased in U.S. trading. In New York, Republic National
Bank quoted bullion at $401.75 a troy ounce at 4 p.m. EST, compared
with $402.50 at the same time Tuesday.
   The big story was the dollar's resilience despite a surprisingly
huge $12.5 billion excess of imports over exports for November
reported by the Commerce Department. Market predictions were for an
$11 billion deficit.
   The dollar declined initially when the trade number was released,
but quickly stabilized against key currencies _ a signal to
professional speculators that the dollar was undervalued and they
should buy it.
   ``It was a trade number that would indicate sell dollars, which
was done,'' said Stuart Yannalfo, a senior foreign exchange dealer
at Refco Inc., a New York commodities futures firm. ``But then it
stopped on a dime, buyers came in and the entire market realized the
dollar wasn't going down any further.''
   The Federal Reserve entered the market at least three times to
peddle dollars, but traders said the moves only slowed the dollar's
rise and provided more opportunities for buying what they considered
cheap dollars.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 0.20 Japanese yen to 127.90 yen. Later
in London it was quoted at 128.45 yen. By the time trading ended in
New York the dollar fetched 128.64 yen, up from 127.83 yen late
Tuesday.
   The dollar gained against the British pound in London, where
sterling fetched $1.7550 vs. $1.7680 late Tuesday. Later in New
York, sterling was quoted at $1.7535, down from $1.7707 late Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with rates late
Tuesday, included: 1.8721 West German marks, up from 1.8495; 1.5915
Swiss francs, up from 1.5746; 1.1906 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1982; 6.3825 French francs, up from 6.3065; and 1,370.375 Italian
lire, up from 1,355.375.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with rates late
Tuesday, included: 1.8705 marks, up from 1.8505; 1.5890 Swiss
francs, up from 1.5755; 6.3800 French francs, up from 6.3085; 2.0925
Dutch guilders, up from 2.0855; 1,356.75 lire, up from 1,354.00; and
1.1937 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1973.
   In gold trading, the New York Commodities Exchange quoted bullion
for current delivery at $402.30 a troy ounce, down 40 cents from
Tuesday. Earlier in London, gold remained unchanged at $402.25; in
Zurich, it rose 15 cents to $402.40; and in Hong Kong it rose 21
cents from Tuesday to $404.64.
   Silver bullion for current delivery fell 3.9 cents on New York's
Comex to $5.905 a troy ounce. In London, silver rose 2 cents to
$5.94 an ounce.
</TEXT>
