<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 1837EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Banks-Securities 1stLd-Writethru   01-18 0701</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Banks-Securities, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0249,0724</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fed Authorizes Five Banks to Underwrite Corporate Debt</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: ADDS 3 grafs with congressional reaction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve Board on Wednesday
authorized five of the nation's largest banks to underwrite
corporate debt and said it would decide in a year whether to allow
banks to underwrite stock.
   The unanimous decision by the seven-member board greatly expands
the type of underwriting permitted, but still severely limits the
quantity of underwriting.
   In 1987, the board approved bank underwriting of municipal
revenue bonds, commercial paper, mortgage-backed securities and
securities backed by consumer loans.
   In line with previous decisions, the Fed said bank holding
companies may only conduct securities underwriting through a
separate subsidiary regulated by the Securities and Exchange
Commission. And, the subsidiary may earn no more than 5 percent of
its revenue from underwriting activities authorized Wednesday and in
1987.
   The rest of the revenue must come from other types of business,
such as the underwriting of general obligation bonds issued by
municipalities and of U.S. government securities, two areas that
have always been open to banks.
   The five percent limit is designed to comply with the
Depression-era Glass-Steagall Act which separated commercial and
investment banking as part of the reforms passed by Congress
following the 1929 stock market crash and subsequent wave of bank
failures.
   In another restriction, the Fed prohibited loans from federally
insured banks and savings institutions to their securities
affiliates.
   Also, the Fed said it ``expects banking organizations
contemplating major expansion proposals to maintain strong capital
levels substantially above minimum levels.''
   ``This is quite a conservative framework for conducting this
activity,'' said Michael Bradfield, general counsel of the Federal
Reserve.
   He noted that the board said previously it plans by mid-year to
consider whether to raise the revenue limit to 10 percent.
   The five bank holding companies affected by Wednesday's decision
are Citicorp, the nation's biggest; Chase Manhattan Corp.; Bankers
Trust New York Corp.; J.P. Morgan &amp; Co. Inc., and Security Pacific
Corp.
   The decision permits the underwriting of all types of corporate
debt, including bonds that can be converted into stock, provided the
convertible bonds sell for 15 percent more than the equivalent
amount of stock.
   Bradfield said the board decided to see how well banks do with
debt underwriting before considering whether to allow stock
underwriting.
   ``The board felt it was appropriate to proceed cautiously,'' he
said.
   Bradfield said once the banks show they have the necessary
managerial knowledge, operational capacity and capital to safely
underwrite corporate debt, final approval will be issued ``on a
fairly automatic basis,'' perhaps as soon as 30 days.
   The Fed's decision fits in with a trend in recent years in which
advances in bank deregulation have come through administrative and
court decisions. Congress is fragmented on the issue and failed last
year to pass comprehensive legislation restructuring the financial
system.
   Donald Oglivie, executive vice president of the American Bankers
Association, a trade group, praised Wednesday's move as ``another
positive step by the Fed toward banking reform.''
   ``This should increase competition in the financial services
industry and lower cost for consumers and businesses,'' he said in a
statement.
   However, Edward I. O'Brien, president of the Securities Industry
Association, said the Fed action ``represents piecemeal dismantling
of the appropriate separation which exists in the financial services
industry _ a system which has worked exceedingly well for more than
50 years.''
   The SIA has launched court challenges to previous deregulation
moves by the Federal Reserve. O'Brien, in his statement, said only
that the SIA would review the decision.
   Two of the most vocal opponents in Congress of weakening the
Glass-Steagall barriers criticized the Fed decision.
   ``The Fed is on its way to giving banks an invitation to shoot
craps with the taxpayer's money,'' said Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich.,
chairman of the House Energy and Commerce Committee. ``This is the
kind if irresponsible behavior that gave us the savings and loan
crisis and brought about the 1929 crash.''
   ``It's troubling that regulators would go ahead and legislate
simply because Congress hasn't done what they wanted it to. It's
galling,'' said Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., a member of the House
Banking Committee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
