<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 2ndLd-Writethru   01-18 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, The Dow ... to CORRECT closing level of Dow to
2,238.75 sted 2,230.75. Picks up 3rd graf, Advancing issues ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unfazed by disappointing news on international
trade, stock prices staged a broad advance Wednesday that carried
the market to new highs since the 1987 crash.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 24.11 to
2,238.75, surpassing the recovery peak of 2,226.07 it reached last
Friday.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by more than 2 to 1 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
1,036 up, 474 down and 468 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board reached 187.54 million
shares, their highest level so far in the new year, against 143.93
million in the previous session.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 220.23 million shares.
   The Commerce Department reported Wednesday morning that the
nation's trade deficit widened to $12.51 billion in November from a
revised $10.26 billion the month before.
   The latest number exceeded most advance estimates on Wall Street.
But the news had only a short-lived impact on the markets.
   The dollar and bond prices quickly rebounded from it, and as they
moved higher stocks followed their lead.
   Wall Streeters said they were heartened to see the market
shrugging off unfavorable news on the trade situation, which has
been a touchy issue for the markets for a long time.
   They also described the pickup in trading activity as a
significant plus, suggesting that the market's recent advance was
attracting a wider following among investors.
   Meanwhile, the market also absorbed the news of quarterly
earnings from International Business Machines Corp. that fell
slightly short of expectations.
   IBM, which posted profits of $3.97 a share for the fourth quarter
against $3.47 in the like period a year earlier, sold off early in
the day but finished with a 1[ gain at 125.
   Among other actively traded blue chips, Exxon rose ] to 45[;
American Telephone &amp; Telegraph | to 29}; Ford Motor ~ to 53, and
General Electric | to 45~.
   Tandem Computers jumped 1| to 18\. The company reported earnings
for its first fiscal quarter ended Dec. 31 of 32 cents a share, up
from 24 cents in the comparable period a year earlier.
   RJR Nabisco slipped [ to 95[ in active trading. Kohlberg Kravis
Roberts &amp; Co. said it had lined up more than $14 billion in bank
loans to help finance its buyout of the company.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $26.34 billion, or 0.94
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks gained
1.53 to 161.01.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose 3.58 to 331.56, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index was up 2.98 at 286.53.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market picked
up 2.83 to 388.88. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 318.22, up 1.65.
