<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 2259EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-HollyFarms     01-18 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Holly Farms,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Holly Farms Directors Consider Buyout Offers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Directors of Holly Farms Corp. met late
into the night in New York Wednesday to consider $1 billion takeover
bids from two rival suitors.
   Officials on all sides of the long-running battle for control of
Holly Farms and leadership of the U.S. chicken industry declined
comment Wednesday.
   Executives of ConAgra Inc. of Omaha, Neb., declined to say
whether they raised their bid for Holly Farms. Rival bidders at
Tyson Foods Inc. of Springdale, Ark., could not be reached for
comment.
   Holly Farms executives said they did not expect to announce
results of the meeting until this morning.
   If the board recommends a sale to ConAgra and if shareholders go
along with that recommendation, Holly Farms executives have said the
company is expected to operate independently of the food
conglomerate.
   If the board recommends that shareholders sell their stock to
Tyson, and the shareholders follow that advice, Holly Farms will
become part of the poultry empire founded by a man who ran out of
gas in Springdale, Ark., and started what became the country's
largest chicken processor.
   ConAgra is seeking court permission to proceed with a contract
reached in November to acquire Holly Farms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
